{"title_page": "Buckinghamshire New University", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|University of Buckingham}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{coord|51.628|-0.752|display=title|region:GB_scale:10000}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name            = Buckinghamshire New University \n|image_name      = Buckinghamshire New University logo.svg\n|caption         = \n|motto           = {{lang-la|Arte et industria}}\n|mottoeng        = \"By Art and Industry\"\n|established     = 2007 \u2013 gained [[Universities in the United Kingdom|university status]] <br> 1891 \u2013 Science and Art School\n|type            = [[public university|Public]]\n|staff           = \n|chancellor      = \n|vice_chancellor = [[Prof Nick Braisby]]\n| students       = {{HESA student population|INSTID=0009}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\">{{HESA citation}}</ref>\n| undergrad      = {{HESA undergraduate population|INSTID=0009}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n| postgrad       = {{HESA postgraduate population|INSTID=0009}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n|other           = 125 [[further education|FE]]<ref name=\"HESA\">{{cite web|url= http://www.hesa.ac.uk/dox/dataTables/studentsAndQualifiers/download/institution0607.xls|title= Table 0a \u2013 All students by institution, mode of study, level of study, gender and domicile 2006/07|accessdate=5 April 2008|format= [[Microsoft Excel]] spreadsheet|publisher=[[Higher Education Statistics Agency]]}}</ref>\n|city            = [[High Wycombe]]\n|state           = [[Buckinghamshire]]\n|country         = England, UK<br>Campus in [[Uxbridge]], [[Middlesex]]<br> England, UK\n|former_names    = School of Science and Art (1891) <br>Wycombe Technical Institute (1920)<br>High Wycombe College of Technology and Art (1961)<br>Buckinghamshire College of Higher Education (1975) <br>Buckinghamshire Chilterns University College (1999)\n|campus          = \n|colours         = \n|affiliations    =[[Million+]], [[GuildHE]] \n|footnotes       = \n|website         = http://www.bucks.ac.uk/\n|coor            = \n|logo            = \n}}\n\n'''Buckinghamshire New University''', styled '''Bucks New University''', is a [[public university]] with campuses in [[High Wycombe]], [[Buckinghamshire]]; [[Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire]]; [[Uxbridge]], [[Middlesex]]; and [[Great Missenden]], Buckinghamshire. The [[Vice-Chancellor]] of the University is Professor Nick Braisby. The institution dates from 1891 when it was founded as the School of Science and Art, and has since that date been re-invented variously as the Wycombe Technical Institute, the High Wycombe College of Technology and Art, and the Buckinghamshire College of Higher Education. It was a [[university college]] from 1999 until 2007 when it announced that its application for university status had been accepted.\n\nThe University is a member of the [[GuildHE]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:High Wycombe Technical School 1906.jpg|thumb|left|200px|High Wycombe Technical School in 1906]]\n\n===19th century origins===\nFounded in 1891 as the School of Science and Art,<ref>[http://bucks.ac.uk/about_us/ Official Site] Retrieved November 2013</ref> it was initially established with public funds raised from a tax on [[beer]] and spirits and set about providing evening classes to residents of High Wycombe and the local area.<ref name=\"Official\">[http://bucks.ac.uk/about_us/history Official history] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140123163356/http://bucks.ac.uk/about_us/history |date=23 January 2014 }} Retrieved January 2014</ref>\n\n===20th century===\nAfter [[World War I]], it was renamed the Wycombe Technical Institute, forging close links with local crafts such as furniture making and cabinetry and helping to provide skills to injured war veterans in order that they might find work in local industries.<ref name=\"Official\"/>\n\nFurther building took place after [[World War II]], and on 6 May 1963 the new facilities were officially opened by the Minister of Education, [[Edward Boyle, Baron Boyle of Handsworth|Sir Edward Boyle]].<ref name=\"Official\"/> A new change of name, the High Wycombe College of Technology and Art accompanied this expansion.<ref name=\"Official\"/>\n\nEven as late as the 1960s, around 3,000 people worked in the manufacture of furniture in High Wycombe,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=HSblAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA22&dq=high+wycombe+furniture&hl=en&sa=X&ei=cBzgUvLTKNT07AaitIGgAg&ved=0CGMQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=high%20wycombe%20furniture&f=false Ashton, John, p.4, ''The Epidemiological Imagination: A Reader''] Retrieved January 2014</ref> and 80% of the wooden chairs manufactured in Britain were made there.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=HSblAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA22&dq=high+wycombe+furniture&hl=en&sa=X&ei=cBzgUvLTKNT07AaitIGgAg&ved=0CGMQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=high%20wycombe%20furniture&f=false Ashton, John, p.21, ''The Epidemiological Imagination: A Reader''] Retrieved January 2014</ref>\n\nIn 1975 High Wycombe College of Art and Technology merged with the Newland Park College of Education in [[Chalfont St Giles]], and was renamed the Buckinghamshire College of Higher Education. In the same decade [[Missenden Abbey]], a former Augustinian monastery founded in 1133, was acquired, and in May 1988 it was officially opened as a management centre by [[Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester]].<ref name=\"Official\"/>\n\nIn March 1999 it was awarded University College status by the government, changing its name once again to Buckinghamshire Chilterns University College. Around this time the ''Which University'' guide described it as a \"concrete labyrinth\", which was unlikely to be \"bringing home architectural awards\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=VFZOZvjEo8IC&pg=PA96&dq=high+wycombe+university&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5SPgUtrpJe_e7AaPxoHoBw&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=high%20wycombe%20university&f=false Rich, Jonny, p.96 ''Push Guide to Which University''] Retrieved January 2014</ref>\n\n===21st century===\n[[File:bcuc.jpg|thumb|right|High Wycombe campus in 2004, before construction of the Gateway Building]]\nIn 2007 it changed its name again, this time from \"Buckinghamshire Chilterns University College\" to its current name of \"Buckinghamshire New University\" (\"Bucks\") when its application for university status was approved by the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]].<ref>[http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/buckinghamshire-new www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk] Retrieved January 2014</ref>\n\nAlternative names such as 'University of Wycombe', 'Wycombe University', 'University of High Wycombe', 'High Wycombe University', 'University of Buckinghamshire' and 'Buckinghamshire Chilterns University' were rejected. The chosen name was swiftly attacked by the [[University of Buckingham]] for using the county name.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://education.guardian.co.uk/higher/comment/story/0,,2209847,00.html|title= What's in a name? Our reputation, for a start|accessdate=4 June 2008|last= Kealey|first= Terence|date=13 November 2007|website=The Guardian |location=UK}}</ref> Critics have argued that the 'New' element of the university's name will look out of place in the long-term.\n\nBucks had ambitious plans to consolidate its divided campuses into a purpose-built site near to Hughenden Park in High Wycombe on land previously owned by [[CompAir]].{{citation needed|date=June 2011}} While these plans fell through, the University changed plans to renovate and enlarge the main campus as well as consolidate both the Wellesbourne and Chalfont campuses onto the High Wycombe site.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}} Additionally new halls of residence have been built at the Hughenden Park site.\n\nThe University is a lead academic sponsor of [[Buckinghamshire University Technical College]], a new [[university technical college]] which opened in [[Aylesbury]] in September 2013.\n\nIn February 2015, Professor Rebecca Bunting was appointed as the new Vice Chancellor and Chief Executive Officer of Buckinghamshire New University, taking over from Professor Ruth Farwell on her retirement.\n\nIn February 2019, Professor Nick Braisby was appointed as the new Vice Chancellor of Buckinghamshire New University, taking over from Professor Rebecca Bunting.\n\n==Campuses==\n[[File:Bucks 25.jpg|thumb|Hughenden Park Student Village under construction in 2009]]\n\nThe University currently operates over four campuses: High Wycombe Campus (previously belonging to the High Wycombe College of Art and Technology), since 2009 a site in Uxbridge in the [[London Borough of Hillingdon]], a thriving base for nursing students and applied healthcare research, a campus in Aylesbury and a site known as Missenden Abbey which is also a conference centre.\n\nIn 2008, the University disposed of two existing campuses; the Chalfont Campus (near [[Little Chalfont]]) and the Wellesbourne Campus (near [[Hazlemere]]).\n\n[[File:Gateway building BNU.jpg|left|thumb|200x200px|\nGateway Building\n]]\n\n=== Gateway building ===\nThe University undertook a major development of the High Wycombe Campus with a large structure, known as the Gateway Building, being built onto the front of the existing building. It won a RIBA award in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bucks.ac.uk/newsroom/news/may_2010/gateway_award.aspx|title=Newsroom|accessdate=16 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717112954/http://bucks.ac.uk/newsroom/news/may_2010/gateway_award.aspx|archivedate=17 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA state-of-the-art complex, the Gateway offers a rich mix of commercial-standard facilities, including a sports/events hall, fitness centre and performance lab, dance and drama studios, sound design labs, music recording studios and video production suites, a modern integrated learning resources centre, a cafe and meeting and conference rooms. It also has green screen facilities and a motion capture system.<ref>[http://bucksanimation.blogspot.co.uk/2014/01/motion-capture-come-to-bucks.html Bucks Animation Blog 12 January 2014] Retrieved January 2014</ref>\n\n===Halls of residence===\n[[File:Bucks-P4230055.JPG|thumb|right|Brook Street Halls]]\nThere is a range of accommodation at Bucks New University including halls of residence, managed houses and the student village:\n* Brook Street Halls, the first to be built for Bucks New University, has 396 rooms and is situated opposite High Wycombe bus station, a five minutes' walk from the University campus.\n* Hughenden Park Student Village was completed in 2009. All 410 student rooms are en-suite and the area is a 15 minutes' walk from the University's Wycombe campus.\n* Windsor House is located in High Wycombe town centre. Much of the estate used to build the halls has been bought from [[Eden, High Wycombe#The Chilterns Shopping Centre|The Chilterns Shopping Centre]].\n\n==Academic profile==\n[[Image:Denhamcabair.jpg|thumb|Cabair at Denham International]]\n\nSeveral courses run at the university are rarities in British universities.\n\nThe Air Transport with [[Commercial pilot license|Commercial Pilot Training]] is a course offering students the opportunity to study for a professional [[pilot's licence]] whilst undertaking university studies in areas such as globalization of the air transport industry and health safety and security for airlines and airports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bucks.ac.uk/courses/course/bs2acp1|title=Search Results|accessdate=16 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205034131/http://bucks.ac.uk/courses/course/bs2acp1|archivedate=5 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Many former students (including [[Virgin Atlantic]] deputy chief pilot David Brooks) have gone on to attain jobs as pilots in flying schools, charter companies and airlines around the world including [[Susi Air]], [[Cathay Pacific]], [[Qatar Airways|Qatar]], [[BMI (airline)|BMI]] and [[Ryanair]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bucks.ac.uk/content/newsroom/2012/cathay-pacific|title=Graduate preparing for new life as pilot with Cathay Pacific|accessdate=16 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717101237/http://bucks.ac.uk/content/newsroom/2012/cathay-pacific|archivedate=17 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the Air Transport with Commercial Pilot Training course aims to provide guidance and support to students with the aim of becoming commercial pilots, many students are inspired by various modules of the course and pursue careers in other areas within the air transport industry. In 2009 graduate Antony Coe set up his own business DexFix computer repairs.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} Following this and in conjunction with his studies in Health safety and security for airlines and airports Antony now provides contract services to the counter terrorism task forces worldwide.\n\nThe university offers several other innovative courses such as Music Management and [[video production|Film and Television Production]]. The university also offers a course in Animation and Visual Effects, launched in September 2013.<ref>[http://bucks.ac.uk/courses/course/bg1ave1 Bucks New University Official Site] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621002028/http://bucks.ac.uk/courses/course/bg1ave1 |date=21 June 2013 }} Retrieved November 2012</ref>\n\nBucks New University is one of very few universities that has created a degree in Policing. In partnership with territorial Police service [[Thames Valley Police]], Bucks New University is one of only two UK Universities to offer the Foundation Degree in Policing as a pre-entry route into Police careers. The University also hosts a [https://web.archive.org/web/20141112030031/http://www.college.police.uk/en/20024.htm CKP] course, which allows applicants into the majority of UK forces.\n\nBucks New University is one of the leading providers of nursing students in London. Students can choose to follow one of three routes: adult, child and mental health pre-qualifying nursing.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2009/may/10/universityguide-buckinghamshire-new-uni The Guardian, 10 May 2009] Retrieved January 2014</ref> The University's Society and Health Faculty offers a range of courses in advanced healthcare; community care and public health; social work and integrated care; psychology; criminal justice and social studies; and applied education.\n\n=== Reputation and rankings ===\n{{Infobox UK university rankings\n| ARWU_N = \n| ARWU_W =\n| QS_N =\n| QS_W =\n| THE_N =\n| THE_W =\n| LINE_1 = 0\n| Complete = 115\n| The_Guardian = 120\n| Times/Sunday_Times = 126\n| LINE_2 = 0\n| TEF = Silver <ref>{{cite web |first1=|title=Bucks New University scoops silver in learning and teaching excellence awards |url=https://bucks.ac.uk/news/2018/june/bucks-new-university-scoops-silver-in-learning-and-teaching-excellence-awards |website=Bucks New University |accessdate=13 July 2018}}</ref>\n}}\nIn November 2013 it was ranked 12th in the UK by the ''[[Huffington Post]]'' in a list of creative universities.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/11/01/top-creative-universities-in-the-uk-revealed_n_4191550.html?+Education&ir=UK+Universities+ Huffington Post 5 November 2013] Retrieved November 2013</ref>\nIt was also included in a list of the top 14 creative universities in the UK by ''The Daily Telegraph'' in December 2013.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/universityeducation/student-life/10446225/Student-life-top-creative-universities.html?frame=2530436 Daily Telegraph December 2013] Retrieved December 2013</ref> However, its overall rankings nationally tend to be among the lowest in the country.\n\n== Academics ==\n[[Trevor Baylis]] was a frequent guest lecturer, and was present at a 2004 graduation ceremony and graduate degree show; he received an honorary degree from the University in 2007, and was present at the official opening of the Gateway building in 2010.\n\n==Alumni==\n*[[Noel Fielding]] \u2013 Actor and comedian\n*[[Dave Brown (comedian)|Dave Brown]] \u2013 Actor and comedian\n*[[Veronica Carlson]] \u2013 Model and actress\n*[[Philip Koomen]] \u2013 Furniture designer\n*[[Rebecca Stephens]] \u2013 Singer\n*[[Fans of Kate]] \u2013 Band\n*[[Otto Decker]] \u2013 English\u2013U.S. soccer player \n*[[Lucian Ercolani]] \u2013 Furniture designer\n*[[John Bolam]] \u2013 Artist\n*[[Chris Joyce]] \u2013 Actor\n*[[Robin Day (designer)]]\n*[[Naomi Riches]]\n*[[Brooke Kinsella]]\n*[[Chloe Rogers]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Thames Valley Health Innovation and Education Cluster]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n* [https://www.youstudy.com/  YouStudy.com | admission, bachelor, masters, phd, english ]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://bucks.ac.uk/ Buckinghamshire New University] \u2013 official website\n* [http://www.bucksstudentsunion.org/ Bucks Students' Union]\n\n{{Universities in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Universities and colleges in South East England}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Buckinghamshire New University| ]]\n[[Category:Education in Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Higher education colleges in England]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1999]]\n[[Category:High Wycombe]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|University of Buckingham}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{coord|51.628|-0.752|display=title|region:GB_scale:10000}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name            = Buckinghamshire New University \n|image_name      = Buckinghamshire New University logo.svg\n|caption         = \n|motto           = {{lang-la|Arte et industria}}\n|mottoeng        = \"By Art and Industry\"\n|established     = 2007 \u2013 gained [[Universities in the United Kingdom|university status]] <br> 1891 \u2013 Science and Art School\n|type            = [[public university|Public]]\n|staff           = \n|chancellor      = \n|vice_chancellor = [[Prof Nick Braisby]]\n| students       = {{HESA student population|INSTID=0009}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\">{{HESA citation}}</ref>\n| undergrad      = {{HESA undergraduate population|INSTID=0009}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n| postgrad       = {{HESA postgraduate population|INSTID=0009}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n|other           = 125 [[further education|FE]]<ref name=\"HESA\">{{cite web|url= http://www.hesa.ac.uk/dox/dataTables/studentsAndQualifiers/download/institution0607.xls|title= Table 0a \u2013 All students by institution, mode of study, level of study, gender and domicile 2006/07|accessdate=5 April 2008|format= [[Microsoft Excel]] spreadsheet|publisher=[[Higher Education Statistics Agency]]}}</ref>\n|city            = [[High Wycombe]]\n|state           = [[Buckinghamshire]]\n|country         = England, UK<br>Campus in [[Uxbridge]], [[Middlesex]]<br> England, UK\n|former_names    = School of Science and Art (1891) <br>Wycombe Technical Institute (1920)<br>High Wycombe College of Technology and Art (1961)<br>Buckinghamshire College of Higher Education (1975) <br>Buckinghamshire Chilterns University College (1999)\n|campus          = \n|colours         = \n|affiliations    =[[Million+]], [[GuildHE]] \n|footnotes       = \n|website         = http://www.bucks.ac.uk/\n|coor            = \n|logo            = \n}}\n\n'''Buckinghamshire New University''', styled '''Bucks New University''', is a [[public university]] with campuses in [[High Wycombe]], [[Buckinghamshire]]; [[Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire]]; [[Uxbridge]], [[Middlesex]]; and [[Great Missenden]], Buckinghamshire. The [[Vice-Chancellor]] of the University is Professor Nick Braisby. The institution dates from 1891 when it was founded as the School of Science and Art, and has since that date been re-invented variously as the Wycombe Technical Institute, the High Wycombe College of Technology and Art, and the Buckinghamshire College of Higher Education. It was a [[university college]] from 1999 until 2007 when it announced that its application for university status had been accepted.\n\nThe University is a member of the [[GuildHE]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:High Wycombe Technical School 1906.jpg|thumb|left|200px|High Wycombe Technical School in 1906]]\n\n===19th century origins===\nFounded in 1891 as the School of Science and Art,<ref>[http://bucks.ac.uk/about_us/ Official Site] Retrieved November 2013</ref> it was initially established with public funds raised from a tax on [[beer]] and spirits and set about providing evening classes to residents of High Wycombe and the local area.<ref name=\"Official\">[http://bucks.ac.uk/about_us/history Official history] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140123163356/http://bucks.ac.uk/about_us/history |date=23 January 2014 }} Retrieved January 2014</ref>\n\n===20th century===\nAfter [[World War I]], it was renamed the Wycombe Technical Institute, forging close links with local crafts such as furniture making and cabinetry and helping to provide skills to injured war veterans in order that they might find work in local industries.<ref name=\"Official\"/>\n\nFurther building took place after [[World War II]], and on 6 May 1963 the new facilities were officially opened by the Minister of Education, [[Edward Boyle, Baron Boyle of Handsworth|Sir Edward Boyle]].<ref name=\"Official\"/> A new change of name, the High Wycombe College of Technology and Art accompanied this expansion.<ref name=\"Official\"/>\n\nEven as late as the 1960s, around 3,000 people worked in the manufacture of furniture in High Wycombe,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=HSblAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA22&dq=high+wycombe+furniture&hl=en&sa=X&ei=cBzgUvLTKNT07AaitIGgAg&ved=0CGMQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=high%20wycombe%20furniture&f=false Ashton, John, p.4, ''The Epidemiological Imagination: A Reader''] Retrieved January 2014</ref> and 80% of the wooden chairs manufactured in Britain were made there.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=HSblAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA22&dq=high+wycombe+furniture&hl=en&sa=X&ei=cBzgUvLTKNT07AaitIGgAg&ved=0CGMQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=high%20wycombe%20furniture&f=false Ashton, John, p.21, ''The Epidemiological Imagination: A Reader''] Retrieved January 2014</ref>\n\nIn 1975 High Wycombe College of Art and Technology merged with the Newland Park College of Education in [[Chalfont St Giles]], and was renamed the Buckinghamshire College of Higher Education. In the same decade [[Missenden Abbey]], a former Augustinian monastery founded in 1133, was acquired, and in May 1988 it was officially opened as a management centre by [[Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester]].<ref name=\"Official\"/>\n\nIn March 1999 it was awarded University College status by the government, changing its name once again to Buckinghamshire Chilterns University College. Around this time the ''Which University'' guide described it as a \"concrete labyrinth\", which was unlikely to be \"bringing home architectural awards\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=VFZOZvjEo8IC&pg=PA96&dq=high+wycombe+university&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5SPgUtrpJe_e7AaPxoHoBw&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=high%20wycombe%20university&f=false Rich, Jonny, p.96 ''Push Guide to Which University''] Retrieved January 2014</ref>\n\n===21st century===\n[[File:bcuc.jpg|thumb|right|High Wycombe campus in 2004, before construction of the Gateway Building]]\nIn 2007 it changed its name again, this time from \"Buckinghamshire Chilterns University College\" to its current name of \"Buckinghamshire New University\" (\"Bucks\") when its application for university status was approved by the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]].<ref>[http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/buckinghamshire-new www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk] Retrieved January 2014</ref>\n\nAlternative names such as 'University of Wycombe', 'Wycombe University', 'University of High Wycombe', 'High Wycombe University', 'University of Buckinghamshire' and 'Buckinghamshire Chilterns University' were rejected. The chosen name was swiftly attacked by the [[University of Buckingham]] for using the county name.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://education.guardian.co.uk/higher/comment/story/0,,2209847,00.html|title= What's in a name? Our reputation, for a start|accessdate=4 June 2008|last= Kealey|first= Terence|date=13 November 2007|website=The Guardian |location=UK}}</ref> Critics have argued that the 'New' element of the university's name will look out of place in the long-term.\n\nBucks had ambitious plans to consolidate its divided campuses into a purpose-built site near to Hughenden Park in High Wycombe on land previously owned by [[CompAir]].{{citation needed|date=June 2011}} While these plans fell through, the University changed plans to renovate and enlarge the main campus as well as consolidate both the Wellesbourne and Chalfont campuses onto the High Wycombe site.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}} Additionally new halls of residence have been built at the Hughenden Park site.\n\nThe University is a lead academic sponsor of [[Buckinghamshire University Technical College]], a new [[university technical college]] which opened in [[Aylesbury]] in September 2013.\n\nIn February 2015, Professor Rebecca Bunting was appointed as the new Vice Chancellor and Chief Executive Officer of Buckinghamshire New University, taking over from Professor Ruth Farwell on her retirement.\n\nIn February 2019, Professor Nick Braisby was appointed as the new Vice Chancellor of Buckinghamshire New University, taking over from Professor Rebecca Bunting.\n\n==Campuses==\n[[File:Bucks 25.jpg|thumb|Hughenden Park Student Village under construction in 2009]]\n\nThe University currently operates over four campuses: High Wycombe Campus (previously belonging to the High Wycombe College of Art and Technology), since 2009 a site in Uxbridge in the [[London Borough of Hillingdon]], a thriving base for nursing students and applied healthcare research, a campus in Aylesbury and a site known as Missenden Abbey which is also a conference centre.\n\nIn 2008, the University disposed of two existing campuses; the Chalfont Campus (near [[Little Chalfont]]) and the Wellesbourne Campus (near [[Hazlemere]]).\n\n[[File:Gateway building BNU.jpg|left|thumb|200x200px|\nGateway Building\n]]\n\n=== Gateway building ===\nThe University undertook a major development of the High Wycombe Campus with a large structure, known as the Gateway Building, being built onto the front of the existing building. It won a RIBA award in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bucks.ac.uk/newsroom/news/may_2010/gateway_award.aspx|title=Newsroom|accessdate=16 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717112954/http://bucks.ac.uk/newsroom/news/may_2010/gateway_award.aspx|archivedate=17 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA state-of-the-art complex, the Gateway offers a rich mix of commercial-standard facilities, including a sports/events hall, fitness centre and performance lab, dance and drama studios, sound design labs, music recording studios and video production suites, a modern integrated learning resources centre, a cafe and meeting and conference rooms. It also has green screen facilities and a motion capture system.<ref>[http://bucksanimation.blogspot.co.uk/2014/01/motion-capture-come-to-bucks.html Bucks Animation Blog 12 January 2014] Retrieved January 2014</ref>\n\n===Halls of residence===\n[[File:Bucks-P4230055.JPG|thumb|right|Brook Street Halls]]\nThere is a range of accommodation at Bucks New University including halls of residence, managed houses and the student village:\n* Brook Street Halls, the first to be built for Bucks New University, has 396 rooms and is situated opposite High Wycombe bus station, a five minutes' walk from the University campus.\n* Hughenden Park Student Village was completed in 2009. All 410 student rooms are en-suite and the area is a 15 minutes' walk from the University's Wycombe campus.\n* Windsor House is located in High Wycombe town centre. Much of the estate used to build the halls has been bought from [[Eden, High Wycombe#The Chilterns Shopping Centre|The Chilterns Shopping Centre]].\n\n==Academic profile==\n[[Image:Denhamcabair.jpg|thumb|Cabair at Denham International]]\n\nSeveral courses run at the university are rarities in British universities.\n\nThe Air Transport with [[Commercial pilot license|Commercial Pilot Training]] is a course offering students the opportunity to study for a professional [[pilot's licence]] whilst undertaking university studies in areas such as globalization of the air transport industry and health safety and security for airlines and airports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bucks.ac.uk/courses/course/bs2acp1|title=Search Results|accessdate=16 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205034131/http://bucks.ac.uk/courses/course/bs2acp1|archivedate=5 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Many former students (including [[Virgin Atlantic]] deputy chief pilot David Brooks) have gone on to attain jobs as pilots in flying schools, charter companies and airlines around the world including [[Susi Air]], [[Cathay Pacific]], [[Qatar Airways|Qatar]], [[BMI (airline)|BMI]] and [[Ryanair]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bucks.ac.uk/content/newsroom/2012/cathay-pacific|title=Graduate preparing for new life as pilot with Cathay Pacific|accessdate=16 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717101237/http://bucks.ac.uk/content/newsroom/2012/cathay-pacific|archivedate=17 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the Air Transport with Commercial Pilot Training course aims to provide guidance and support to students with the aim of becoming commercial pilots, many students are inspired by various modules of the course and pursue careers in other areas within the air transport industry. In 2009 graduate Antony Coe set up his own business DexFix computer repairs.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} Following this and in conjunction with his studies in Health safety and security for airlines and airports Antony now provides contract services to the counter terrorism task forces worldwide.\n\nThe university offers several other innovative courses such as Music Management and [[video production|Film and Television Production]]. The university also offers a course in Animation and Visual Effects, launched in September 2013.<ref>[http://bucks.ac.uk/courses/course/bg1ave1 Bucks New University Official Site] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621002028/http://bucks.ac.uk/courses/course/bg1ave1 |date=21 June 2013 }} Retrieved November 2012</ref>\n\nBucks New University is one of very few universities that has created a degree in Policing. In partnership with territorial Police service [[Thames Valley Police]], Bucks New University is one of only two UK Universities to offer the Foundation Degree in Policing as a pre-entry route into Police careers. The University also hosts a [https://web.archive.org/web/20141112030031/http://www.college.police.uk/en/20024.htm CKP] course, which allows applicants into the majority of UK forces.\n\nBucks New University is one of the leading providers of nursing students in London. Students can choose to follow one of three routes: adult, child and mental health pre-qualifying nursing.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2009/may/10/universityguide-buckinghamshire-new-uni The Guardian, 10 May 2009] Retrieved January 2014</ref> The University's Society and Health Faculty offers a range of courses in advanced healthcare; community care and public health; social work and integrated care; psychology; criminal justice and social studies; and applied education.\n\n=== Reputation and rankings ===\n{{Infobox UK university rankings\n| ARWU_N = \n| ARWU_W =\n| QS_N =\n| QS_W =\n| THE_N =\n| THE_W =\n| LINE_1 = 0\n| Complete = 115\n| The_Guardian = 120\n| Times/Sunday_Times = 126\n| LINE_2 = 0\n| TEF = Silver <ref>{{cite web |first1=|title=Bucks New University scoops silver in learning and teaching excellence awards |url=https://bucks.ac.uk/news/2018/june/bucks-new-university-scoops-silver-in-learning-and-teaching-excellence-awards |website=Bucks New University |accessdate=13 July 2018}}</ref>\n}}\nIn November 2013 it was ranked 12th in the UK by the ''[[Huffington Post]]'' in a list of creative universities.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/11/01/top-creative-universities-in-the-uk-revealed_n_4191550.html?+Education&ir=UK+Universities+ Huffington Post 5 November 2013] Retrieved November 2013</ref>\nIt was also included in a list of the top 14 creative universities in the UK by ''The Daily Telegraph'' in December 2013.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/universityeducation/student-life/10446225/Student-life-top-creative-universities.html?frame=2530436 Daily Telegraph December 2013] Retrieved December 2013</ref>\n\n== Academics ==\n[[Trevor Baylis]] was a frequent guest lecturer, and was present at a 2004 graduation ceremony and graduate degree show; he received an honorary degree from the University in 2007, and was present at the official opening of the Gateway building in 2010.\n\n==Alumni==\n*[[Noel Fielding]] \u2013 Actor and comedian\n*[[Dave Brown (comedian)|Dave Brown]] \u2013 Actor and comedian\n*[[Veronica Carlson]] \u2013 Model and actress\n*[[Philip Koomen]] \u2013 Furniture designer\n*[[Rebecca Stephens]] \u2013 Singer\n*[[Fans of Kate]] \u2013 Band\n*[[Otto Decker]] \u2013 English\u2013U.S. soccer player \n*[[Lucian Ercolani]] \u2013 Furniture designer\n*[[John Bolam]] \u2013 Artist\n*[[Chris Joyce]] \u2013 Actor\n*[[Robin Day (designer)]]\n*[[Naomi Riches]]\n*[[Brooke Kinsella]]\n*[[Chloe Rogers]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Thames Valley Health Innovation and Education Cluster]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n* [https://www.youstudy.com/  YouStudy.com | admission, bachelor, masters, phd, english ]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://bucks.ac.uk/ Buckinghamshire New University] \u2013 official website\n* [http://www.bucksstudentsunion.org/ Bucks Students' Union]\n\n{{Universities in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Universities and colleges in South East England}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Buckinghamshire New University| ]]\n[[Category:Education in Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Higher education colleges in England]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1999]]\n[[Category:High Wycombe]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "82.1.109.96", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReputation and rankings)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buckinghamshire_New_University"}
{"title_page": "Andrea Bocelli", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Bocelli|his second album|Bocelli (album)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name               = Andrea Bocelli\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|OMRI]] [[Order of Merit of Duarte, S\u00e1nchez and Mella|OMDSM]]\n| image              = https://images.app.goo.gl/PyYkc4HHhjX68ZEU6\n| caption            = Bocelli receiving a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], 2010\n| background         = solo_singer\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age |df=y|1958|9|22}}\n| birth_place        = [[Lajatico]], Italy\n| genre              = {{hlist|[[Opera music|Opera]]|[[Operatic pop]]|[[Crossover music#Classical crossover|Classical crossover]]|[[Easy listening]]|[[Latin pop]]|[[Traditional pop]]}}\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Opera singer ([[tenor]]) |Songwriter|Multi-instrumentalist|Record producer}}\n| instrument         = {{hlist|Vocals|piano|[[flute]]|[[fiddle]]}}\n}}\n'''Andrea Angel Bocelli''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|OMRI]] [[Order of Merit of Duarte, Sanchez and Mella|OMDSM]]}} ({{IPA-it|an\u02c8dre\u02d0a bo\u02c8t\u0283\u025blli}}; born 22 September 1958) is an Italian singer, songwriter, and record producer.<ref name=\"Decca\">{{cite web|title=Andrea Bocelli|url=http://www.decca.com/artists/andrea-bocelli-192|work=[[Decca Records]]|publisher=Universal Music|accessdate=10 December 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430171029/http://www.decca.com/artists/andrea-bocelli-192|archivedate=30 April 2011}}</ref><ref>http://www.classicalbrits.co.uk/artist/andrea-bocelli{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Celine Dion]] has said that \"if God would have a singing voice, he must sound a lot like Andrea Bocelli\",<ref name=\"Decca\"/><ref name=\"2009 Bocelli Interview\"/> and record producer [[David Foster]] has often described Bocelli's voice as the most beautiful in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andreabocelli.com/|title=Andrea Bocelli - Sito Ufficiale - Tour, discografia e opere}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andreabocelli.com/en/|title=En Aranjuez con tu amor - Andrea Bocelli|access-date=4 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019065145/http://www.andreabocelli.com/en/|archive-date=19 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n \nBocelli was diagnosed with [[Primary juvenile glaucoma|congenital glaucoma]] at 5 months old, and became completely blind at age 12, following a [[Association football|football]] accident. Since 1982, Bocelli has recorded 15 solo studio albums of both pop and classical music, three greatest hits albums, and nine complete operas, selling over 90 million records worldwide.<ref name=\"BillboardMastersofAlbums\">{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli to Receive Master's Degree|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5763005/andrea-bocelli-to-receive-masters-degree|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=18 October 2013|agency=AP}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli to receive Classic Brit honour|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-19508008|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=6 September 2012}}</ref> He has had success as a crossover performer, bringing classical music to the top of international pop charts.<ref name=\"Decca\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Bearn|first=Emily|title=Operation Bocelli: the making of a superstar|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/02/25/1046064026608.html|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Age]]|date=26 February 2003}}</ref><ref name=\"Obama\">{{cite news|last=Malitz|first=David|title='Christmas in Washington' sticks to the classics|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/12/12/AR2010121204423.html|accessdate=27 July 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=12 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Bocelli was named one of ''People'' magazine's [[People (magazine)#100 Most Beautiful People|50 Most Beautiful People]].<ref name=\"People1998\">{{cite journal|title=Andrea Bocelli: Singer|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20125222,00.html|journal=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=11 May 1998|volume=49|issue=18|accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> In 1999, he was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]] at the [[Grammy Award]]s. \"[[The Prayer (Celine Dion and Andrea Bocelli song)|The Prayer]]\" is his duet with [[Celine Dion]] for the animated film ''[[Quest for Camelot]]'' which won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]] and was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]].<ref name=\"Decca\"/> He captured a listing in the ''[[Guinness World Records|Guinness Book of World Records]]'' with the release of his classical album ''[[Sacred Arias (Andrea Bocelli album)|Sacred Arias]]'', as he simultaneously held the top three positions on the US Classical Albums charts.<ref name=\"Decca\"/>\n\nBocelli was made a Grand Officer of the [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] in 2006 and was honored with a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] on 2 March 2010 for his contribution to Live Theater.\n\n==Early life==\nBocelli was born to Alessandro and Edi Bocelli.<ref name=\"BlindAmbition\">{{cite news|last1=Day|first1=Carol|title=Blind Ambition|url=http://people.com/archive/blind-ambition-vol-48-no-19/|work=People|accessdate=22 July 2017|date=10 November 1997|quote=Bocelli's parents, Alessandro, 68, and Edi, 59, sold farm equipment and produced wine in tiny Lajatico, in Tuscany about 20 miles from Pisa.}}</ref> Doctors had advised the couple to abort him, as they predicted that the child would be born with a disability. It was evident at birth that Bocelli had numerous problems with his sight, and he was eventually diagnosed with [[congenital glaucoma]].<ref name=\"TelegraphGordon\"/> He has stated that his mother's decision to give birth to him and overrule the doctor's advice was the inspiration for him to oppose abortion.<ref name=\"TelegraphGordon\">{{cite news|author=Bryony Gordon|title=Andrea Bocelli: The truth about my friend \u2013 the strong-willed, kind and intelligent Silvio Berlusconi|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/classicalmusic/8884646/Andrea-Bocelli-The-truth-about-my-friend-the-strong-willed-kind-and-intelligent-Silvio-Berlusconi.html|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=14 November 2011|author-link=Bryony Gordon}}</ref>\n\nBocelli grew up on his family's farm where they sold farm machinery and made wine in the small village of [[La Sterza]], a ''[[frazione]]'' of [[Lajatico]], Tuscany, Italy, about {{convert|40|km|abbr=on}} south of [[Pisa]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Sodomka|first=Dennis|title=Wine Time: Bocelli Prosecco NV, Italy|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/things-do/applause/2013-10-08/wine-time-bocelli-prosecco-nv-italy|accessdate=14 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Augusta Chronicle]]|date=8 October 2013}}</ref> His mother and younger brother Alberto still live in the family home; his father died in 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Interview: Andrea Bocelli, opera singer|url=http://www.scotsman.com/what-s-on/music/interview-andrea-bocelli-opera-singer-1-471747|accessdate=14 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|date=23 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nBocelli showed a great passion for music as a young boy. His mother has said that music was the only thing that would comfort him. He started piano lessons at age 6 and later learned to play the flute, saxophone, trumpet, trombone, guitar, and drums.<ref name=\"BlindAmbition\"/> His nanny Oriana gave him the first record of [[Franco Corelli]], and he began to show interest in pursuing the career of a tenor.<ref name=\"Ability\">{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli \u2013 Singing to the Top|url=http://abilitymagazine.com/andrea-bocelli.html|accessdate=25 October 2013|newspaper=[[Ability (magazine)|Ability]]|date=October\u2013November 2013}}</ref> By age 7, he was able to recognize the famous voices of the time and tried to emulate the great singers.<ref name=\"Ability\"/>\n\nAt age 12, Bocelli lost his sight completely following an accident during an [[association football]] game.<ref name=\"People1998\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Hooper|first=John|title=Tenor's story acclaimed by anti-abortion campaigners|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jun/10/andrea-bocelli-abortion-italy|accessdate=28 July 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=10 June 2010}}</ref> He was hit in the eye playing goalkeeper during a match and suffered a brain hemorrhage. Doctors resorted to [[leech]]es in a last-ditch effort to save his sight, but they were unsuccessful and he remained blind.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pisa|first=Nick|title=Doctors tried to cure Andrea Bocelli's blindness with leeches|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/8100281/Doctors-tried-to-cure-Andrea-Bocellis-blindness-with-leeches.html|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=31 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nBocelli also spent time singing during his childhood.<ref name=\"chronicle\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 1958\u20131991|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle.htm|accessdate=20 January 2008}}</ref> He gave his first concert in a small village not far from where he was born.<ref name=\"Ability\"/> He won his first song competition at age 14 with \"[['O sole mio]]\" at the Margherita d'Oro in [[Viareggio]].<ref name=\"chronicle\"/> He finished secondary school in 1980, and then studied law at the [[University of Pisa]].<ref name=\"BillboardMastersofAlbums\" /><ref name=\"BlindAmbition\"/> To earn money, he performed evenings in piano bars, and it was there that he met his future wife Enrica in 1987.<ref name=\"BlindAmbition\"/> He completed law school and spent one year as a court-appointed lawyer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rogers|first=Paul|title=Andrea Bocelli at the MGM Grand|url=https://www.latimes.com/custompublishing/vegas/la-ss-andrea-bocelli-at-the-mgm-grand-20130904-dto,0,3390210.story|accessdate=21 December 2013|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=5 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===1992\u201394: Sanremo and ''Il mare calmo della sera''===\nIn 1992, Italian rock star [[Zucchero]] held auditions for tenors to make a [[Demo (music)|demo tape]] of his song \"Miserere\", to send to Italian tenor [[Luciano Pavarotti]]. After hearing Bocelli on tape, Pavarotti urged Zucchero to use Bocelli instead of him.  Zucchero eventually persuaded Pavarotti to record the song with Bocelli, and it became a hit throughout Europe. In Zucchero's European concert tour in 1993, Bocelli accompanied him to sing the duet, and he was also given solo sets in the concerts, singing \"[[Nessun dorma]]\" from [[Giacomo Puccini]]'s opera ''[[Turandot]]''.<ref name=\"BOC1992\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 1991\u20131994|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle1992.htm|accessdate=20 January 2008}}</ref> Bocelli signed with the [[Sugar Music]] label in [[Milan]] after Caterina Caselli heard Bocelli sing \"Miserere\" and \"Nessun Dorma\" at a birthday party for Zucchero.\n\nIn December, Bocelli entered the preliminary round of the [[Sanremo Music Festival]] in the category of Giovani, performing \"Miserere\". He won the preliminary competition with the highest marks ever recorded in the newcomers section. On 28 December, he debuted in the classical world in a concert at the [[Teatro Romolo Valli]] in [[Reggio Emilia]].<ref name=\"BOC1992\"/> In February 1994, he entered the main Sanremo Festival competition with \"[[Il mare calmo della sera (song)|Il mare calmo della sera]]\", and he won the newcomers section, again with a record score. Following his win, Bocelli released his debut album [[Il Mare Calmo della Sera|of the same name]] in April, and it entered the Italian Top Ten, being certified [[Music recording sales certification|platinum]] within weeks.<ref name=\"BOC1992\"/>\n\nIn May 1994, he toured with pop singer [[Gerardina Trovato]].<ref name=\"BOC1992\"/> In September, he sang at Pavarotti's annual Charity Gala concert, ''Pavarotti International'' in [[Modena]], where he sang [[Ruggiero Leoncavallo]]'s \"Mattinata\" and sang a duet with Pavarotti, Maurizio Morante's \"Notte e Piscatore\".<ref name=\"BOC1992\"/> In September, he made his opera debut as [[Macduff (Macbeth)|Macduff]] in Verdi's ''[[Macbeth (opera)|Macbeth]]'' at the Teatro Verdi in Pisa.<ref name=\"PBS8\">{{cite web|last=Ardoin|first=John|authorlink=John Ardoin|title=Bocelli and Chung|publisher=[[PBS]]|year=2007|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/gperf/shows/andreabocelli/essay3.html|accessdate=20 January 2008}}</ref> Bocelli had been an agnostic, but around 1994, partly as a result of immersing himself in the works of Russian author [[Leo Tolstoy]], he returned to the practice of the Catholic faith.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bocelli, l' inno per il Papa nasce a Lourdes|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1999/settembre/21/Bocelli_inno_per_Papa_nasce_co_0_9909214577.shtml|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=Corriere Della Sera|date=21 September 1999|language=Italian}}</ref> He performed the hymn \"[[Adeste Fideles]]\" in Rome before [[Pope John Paul II]] in [[St. Peter's Basilica]] at Christmas.<ref name=\"BOC1992\"/>\n\n===1995\u201397: ''Bocelli'' and ''Romanza''===\nAs winner of the newcomers section at the 1994 Sanremo Festival, Bocelli was invited to return the following year. He entered the main competition with \"[[Con te partir\u00f2]]\" and finished in fourth place.<ref name=\"BOC1995\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 1995\u20131997|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle1995.htm|accessdate=20 January 2008}}</ref> The song was included on his second album, ''[[Bocelli (album)|Bocelli]]'', produced by [[Mauro Malavasi]] and released in November 1995. In Belgium, \"Con te partir\u00f2\" became the best-selling single of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bocellionline.com/Bio.html |title=Andrea Bocelli Online Biography |publisher=Bocellionline.com |accessdate=6 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827214958/http://www.bocellionline.com/Bio.html |archivedate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nHis third album, ''[[Viaggio Italiano]]'', was released in Italy in 1996.<ref name=\"BOC1995\"/> He was invited to sing a duet with English soprano [[Sarah Brightman]] at the final bout of German [[boxer]] [[Henry Maske]]. Brightman had approached Bocelli after she heard him singing \"Con te partir\u00f2\" whilst she was dining in a restaurant. Changing the title lyric of the song to \"[[Con te partir\u00f2|Time to Say Goodbye]]\", they re-recorded it as a duet with members of the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] and sang it as a farewell for Maske.<ref name=\"Liebergen2008\">{{cite book|last=Liebergen|first=Patrick M.|title=Singer's Library of Arias: 15 Vocal Masterworks from the Baroque Era Through the Twenty-First Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VnS5WNme3skC&pg=PA81|accessdate=29 January 2018|date=July 2008|publisher=Alfred Music Publishing|isbn=978-0-7390-5142-9|page=81}}</ref> The single debuted atop the German charts, where it stayed for fourteen weeks. With sales nearing three million copies, and a sextuple platinum award, \"Time to Say Goodbye\" eclipsed the previous best-selling single by more than one million copies.<ref name=\"BOC1995\"/> He topped the Spanish singles chart in 1996 with a duet with [[Marta S\u00e1nchez]], \"Vivo Por Ella\", the Spanish version of \"[[Vivo per lei]]\", recorded with Giorgia for his 1997 compilation album, ''[[Romanza]]''. He also recorded a Portuguese version of the song with Brazilian singer [[Sandy (singer)|Sandy]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nThe same year, Bocelli recorded \"Je vis pour elle\", the French version of \"Vivo per lei\", as a duet with French singer [[H\u00e9l\u00e8ne S\u00e9gara]]. Released in December 1997, the song became a hit in Belgium (Wallonia) and France, where it reached No. 1 on the charts. To date, it is the best-selling single for S\u00e9gara, and the second for Bocelli after \"Time to Say Goodbye\". On 3 March, he appeared in [[Hamburg]], Germany, with Sarah Brightman to receive the ECHO music award for \"[[Echo (music award)#Single of the Year (National)|Best Single of the Year]]\".<ref name=\"BOC1995\"/>\n\nIn the summer of 1997 he gave 22 open-air concerts in Germany, and an indoor concert in [[Oberhausen]] on 31 August. In September, he performed in concert at the [[Piazza dei Cavalieri]] in Pisa for the home video ''[[A Night in Tuscany]]'' ({{lang-it|una notte nella Toscana}}) with guests [[Nuccia Focile]], Sarah Brightman and Zucchero. The concert was also Bocelli's first concert to air on PBS part of the ''In The Spotlight'' series. It also marked as Bocelli's debut to the American audiences. On 14 September, in [[Munich]], Germany, he received an [[ECHO Klassik]] Best Seller of the Year award for his album, ''Viaggio Italiano''.<ref name=\"BOC1995\" /><ref name=\"echo1997\">{{cite news|title=ECHO Klassik 1997 winners |language=German |publisher=[[Echo (music award)|ECHO]] |url=http://www.echo-deutscher-musikpreis.de/echo/echo_klassik_1997_gewinner.htm |accessdate=20 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107235337/http://www.echo-deutscher-musikpreis.de/echo/echo_klassik_1997_gewinner.htm |archivedate=7 January 2009 }}</ref>\n\nBack in Italy in Bologna on 27 September, he sang at the [[International Eucharistic Congress]]. On 19 October, he sang at the [[TeleFood]] benefit concert held in the [[Vatican City]] to raise awareness about world hunger. On 25 October, he received a [[Bambi Award]] in the Klassik category in Cologne, Germany.<ref name=\"BOC1995\" />\n\n===1998\u201399: ''Aria: The Opera Album'', ''Sogno'' and ''Sacred Arias''===\nBocelli made his debut in a major operatic role in 1998 when he played Rodolfo in a production of ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' at the Teatro Comunale in [[Cagliari]] from 18 to 25 February.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Berger|first1=Kevin|title=Beyond the criticism: Deconstructing Andrea Bocelli's voice|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2010/12/beyond-the-criticisms-deconstructing-andrea-bocellis-voice.html|accessdate=29 January 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=8 December 2010}}</ref> His fifth album ''[[Aria: The Opera Album]]'' was released in March.<ref name=\"BOC1998\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 1998|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle1998.htm|accessdate=20 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 April, Bocelli made his United States debut with a concert at the [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts]] in Washington, D.C., followed the next day by a reception at the [[White House]] with then US President [[Bill Clinton]].<ref name=\"BOC1998\"/> On 5 May, he appeared in [[Monte Carlo]], winning two [[World Music Awards]], one in the category \"Best Italian Singer\", and one for \"Best Classical Interpretation\".<ref name=\"BOC1998\"/><ref name=\"IHT6768960\">\n{{cite news|title=People|work=[[International Herald Tribune]]|date=8 May 1998|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-6768960.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103051442/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-6768960.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 November 2012|accessdate=20 January 2008}}</ref> He was also named one of [[People Magazine's 50 Most Beautiful People|''People'' magazine's 50 Most Beautiful People]] of 1998.<ref name=\"People1998\"/>\n\nFrom June to August, he toured North and South America. In September, he received his second Echo Klassik award, this time for Best Selling Classical Album with ''Aria: The Opera Album''.<ref name=\"BOC1998\" /> On Thanksgiving Eve, Bocelli was a guest on [[C\u00e9line Dion]]'s television special ''These Are Special Times'' in which he joined Dion to sing \"[[The Prayer (Celine Dion and Andrea Bocelli song)|The Prayer]]\" and he also sang \"[[Ave Maria (Vavilov)|Ave Maria]]\" solo. The duet was included on Dion's album ''[[These Are Special Times]]'' (1998) and was re-issued with the DVD of the TV special in 2007. The song also appeared on the ''[[Quest for Camelot]]'' soundtrack in 1998 and on Bocelli's album, ''[[Sogno]]'', the following year.\n\nIn the New Year, he performed two concerts at the [[Bellagio (resort)|Bellagio]] hotel in Las Vegas. At the [[56th Golden Globe Awards]] held on 24 January, \"The Prayer\" won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song#1990s|Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]] from the film ''Quest for Camelot''.<ref name=\"BOC1999\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 1999|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle1999.htm|accessdate=20 January 2008}}</ref> At the [[41st Grammy Awards]] ceremony on 24 February, Bocelli was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist#1990s|Best New Artist]], which was won by [[Lauryn Hill]].<ref name=\"Decca\"/> Bocelli and Dion sang \"The Prayer\" at the ceremony.<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/> The song was also nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] and performed by Bocelli and Dion at the ceremony held at the [[Los Angeles Music Center]] on 21 March.<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/>\n\nFrom 11 to 24 April, he toured the West Coast of North America, from [[San Diego]] to [[Vancouver]], with a final performance at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] in Los Angeles. Actress [[Elizabeth Taylor]] stood by his side on the stage during the encore, while he sang \"The Prayer\".<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/> At the invitation of [[Steven Spielberg]], Bocelli sang in Los Angeles on 15 May before Bill Clinton at an event on behalf of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]. At the end of May, he toured Portugal and Spain and sang with Portuguese [[Fado]] singer [[Dulce Pontes]]. On 27 June, he took part in the [[Michael Jackson]] benefit concert for suffering children in Munich's [[Olympic Stadium (Munich)|Olympic Stadium]].<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/>\n\nFrom 10 July to 27 August, he appeared in a guest role for seven performances of ''[[The Merry Widow]]'' at the [[Verona Arena]].<ref name=\"PBS8\"/><ref name=\"BOC1999\"/> As the \"Tenor Conte Andrea\" he performed three arias: \"[[La donna \u00e8 mobile]]\" from Verdi's ''[[Rigoletto]]''; \"Tu, che m' hai preso il cuor\" from [[Franz Leh\u00e1r]]'s ''[[Das Land Des Laechelns]]'' and \"Libiamo ne' lieti calici\" from Verdi's ''La traviata''.<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/> On 10 September, together with soprano [[Daniela Dess\u00ec]] and two Polish singers, he performed at the Great Theatre of [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]] in Poland. From 7 October to 19 November, he made his United States operatic debut in [[Jules Massenet]]'s ''[[Werther]]'' at the [[Detroit Opera House]] with the Michigan Opera Theater.<ref name=\"PBS8\"/>\n\nHe also performed at [[Rodeo Drive]] in Hollywood and gave further concerts in Detroit, [[Cleveland]] and Chicago, and made an appearance on Jay Leno's first installment of ''[[The Tonight Show]]''. Then [[Mayor of New York City]] [[Rudy Giuliani]] gave him the Crystal Apple award. His seventh album ''[[Sacred Arias (Andrea Bocelli album)|Sacred Arias]]'', which contains exclusively [[sacred music]], was released worldwide on 8 November, and two weeks later reached number one on the US [[Billboard charts|Classic Billboard charts]] \u2013 making Bocelli the first vocalist to hold all top three places on the chart, with ''Aria, the opera album'' in second place, and ''Viaggio Italiano'' in third place. The album also included the hymn of the Holy Year 2000 which was chosen as the official version by the Vatican in October.<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/> To promote ''Sacred Arias'', Bocelli recorded [[Sacred Arias: The Home Video|his second PBS concert]] at the Roman church of [[Santa Maria sopra Minerva]], in Rome, in 1999, singing most of the songs from the album. The special was nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Classical Music-Dance Program during the [[52nd Primetime Emmy Awards]].\n\nIn Italy, Bocelli sang in [[Florence]] at a meeting of the centre-left Heads of State<!--This is cryptic ... what event was this? The linking was deceptive, anyway.-->. Invited by [[Queen Elizabeth II]], he performed at the annual [[Royal Variety Performance]] in Birmingham, UK, on 29 November. On 30 November, his book ''La musica del silenzio'', an autobiographical novel, was released in Italy,<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/> and in 2017 it was turned into a movie as ''[[The Music of Silence]]'', directed by [[Michael Radford]]. From 12 to 21 December, he performed six concerts in [[Barcelona]], [[Strasbourg]], Lisbon, [[Zagreb]], [[Budapest]] and [[Messina]], some of which were broadcast on local television. He also performed on German television; ''[[Wetten, dass..?]]'' on 11 December and the [[Jos\u00e9 Carreras]] Gala in [[Leipzig]] on 17 December. On 31 December, he finished a marathon twenty-four concerts in thirty days, with a concert at the [[Nassau Veterans Memorial Coliseum]] in New York, welcoming in the new millennium.<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/>\n\n===2000\u201301: ''Verdi'' and ''Cieli di Toscana''===\nAt the [[42nd Grammy Awards]], Bocelli was nominated twice. \"The Prayer\" was nominated for [[Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals]] and for [[Best Male Pop Vocal Performance]]. Bocelli performed it with Dion at the ceremony. His \"World Tour 2000\" started on 31 March. In May, his ''Sacred Arias'' album was voted album of the year by listeners of the [[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]] radio station in the UK. His world tour continued from 12 May to 14 May with four concerts in Japan and South Korea. At the end of the [[UEFA Euro 2000|UEFA European Football Championship]], he performed with [[Valery Gergiev]] and [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]] at a concert on the [[Meuse (river)|River Maas]] in [[Rotterdam]]. On 6 July, he performed at the [[Statue of Liberty]] in New York City for his third PBS special ''American Dream: Andrea Bocelli's Statue of Liberty Concert''. The concert was a dedication to his father, who died in the beginning of 2000. He was accompanied by the New Jersey Symphony Orchestra under the direction of Maestro [[Steven Mercurio]] with special guest Soprano Ana Maria Martinez and a surprise appearance by Sarah Brightman to sing with Bocelli on \"Time to Say Goodbye.\" For the final encore, he dedicated \"Sogno\" to his late Father. On 17 August, he performed in Giuseppe Verdi's ''[[Requiem (Verdi)|Messa da Requiem]]'' at the Verona Arena in Rome.\n\nHis seventh album, ''[[Verdi (album)|Verdi]]'', was released on 11 September. In September, he performed three concerts in Australia. He received another Echo Klassik award for \"Bestseller of the year\" for ''[[Sacred Arias (Andrea Bocelli album)|Sacred Arias]]''. In November, his first complete opera recording, ''La Boh\u00e8me'', was released. In December, he received another award in Germany, the [[Goldene Europa]] for classical music.<ref name=\"BOC2000\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 2000|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle2000.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2001, Bocelli portrayed the main character in [[Pietro Mascagni|Mascagni]]'s opera ''[[L'amico Fritz]]'' at the Teatro Filarmonico in [[Verona]] and again performed the tenor part in Verdi's ''Requiem''. On 19 March, the ''Requiem'' album was released with Bocelli as tenor. From 22 March to 6 April, he toured North America accompanied by [[Cecilia Gasdia]] and the [[Hartford Symphony Orchestra]]. On 17 June, he performed at the re-opening of the [[Leaning Tower of Pisa]]. In July, he performed two concerts in [[Dublin]] with [[Ana Mar\u00eda Mart\u00ednez]] and the [[New Symphony Orchestra]]. At the [[Scuola Grande di San Rocco]] in Venice on 4 October, he presented his new album ''Cieli di Toscana'' and was recognised for having sold more than 40 million albums worldwide. In October, he opened the celebrations of the 200th anniversary of the birth of [[Sicilian people|Sicilian]] opera composer [[Vincenzo Bellini]] in [[Catania]]. On 28 October, he sang Franz Schubert's ''[[Ellens dritter Gesang]]'' (also known as \"Ave Maria\", Latin for \"Hail Mary\") as a representative of the [[Roman Catholic]] faith, during a memorial concert at [[Ground Zero]] in New York City for the victims of the [[September 11 attacks]] there. In November, he received the Platinum Europe Award for one million sales of the album ''Cieli di Toscana'', and at the [[Italian Music Awards]] he was given a special award from the [[Federation of the Italian Music Industry]] for his merits as an \"Ambassador of Italian music in the world\". He performed seven more concerts in the US accompanied by Ana Mar\u00eda Mart\u00ednez, and on 23 December, he sang the [[Italian national anthem]] as well as works of Bellini and Verdi at the traditional Christmas concert in the [[Italian Senate]], which was broadcast live on television for the first time.<ref name=\"BOC2001\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 2001|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle2001.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref>\n\n===2002\u201305: ''Sentimento'' and ''Andrea''===\n[[File:Tony Celine Bocelli.jpg|thumb|left|Bocelli with [[Celine Dion]] and [[Tony Renis]] in 2002.]]\n\nIn Berlin on 5 February, he received a [[Goldene Kamera]] award in the \"Music & Entertainment\" category. On 6 March, he received two World Music Awards in Monte Carlo: \"World best selling classical artist\" and \"Best selling Italian artist\". On 11 March, he gave a concert for peace at the [[St Mark's Basilica|Basilica di San Marco a Venezia]] in Venice, accompanied by the orchestra of the [[La Fenice|Teatro La Fenice]] and conducted by [[Lorin Maazel]]. On 15 March, he took part in the opening of [[Walt Disney Studios Park]] in [[Marne-la-Vall\u00e9e]] France. On 7 May, Bocelli and Tony Renis received a [[Telegatto]] Italian Television award for the soundtrack of the series ''[[Heart (novel)|Cuore]]''. On 23 May he received the [[Classical BRIT Awards#2002|2002 Classical BRIT Award]] for \"Outstanding Contribution to Music\".<ref name=\"BBC2005196\">{{cite news|title=Salford singer wins again|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2005196.stm|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=23 May 2002}}</ref> On 27 May, he performed at the [[Villa Madama]] in Rome in front of US president [[George W. Bush]] and Italian president [[Silvio Berlusconi]]. On 28 May, he took part in \"Pavarotti & Friends\" charity concert in [[Modena]] in aid of [[Angola]]. In June he again toured the US, then on 26 July and 3 August, he portrayed [[Lieutenant Pinkerton|Lieutenant B.F. Pinkerton]] in ''[[Madama Butterfly]]'' at the 48th Puccini Festival in Torre del Lago. On 14 October, he and Lorin Maazel presented his new album ''[[Sentimento]]'' to a worldwide audience. Further presentations took place in Milan and New York, and the album was released on 4 November, selling over two million copies in 40 days. On 24 October, he started his ''Sentimento'' tour in [[Z\u00fcrich]] which took in large arenas in several European and North American cities.<ref name=\"BOC2002\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 2002|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle2002.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2003, Bocelli performed ''Madama Butterfly'' in an exclusive Monte Carlo concert, which was attended by [[Caroline, Princess of Hanover]]. In March for the first time he appeared as a producer, at the Sanremo Festival, where the young artists Allunati and Jacqueline Ferry sang for his new record label, Clacksong.<ref name=\"BOC2003\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 2003|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle2003.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref> In May his second complete opera, ''[[Tosca]]'', was released.<ref>Giacomo Puccini, ''Tosca.'' Fiorenza Cedolins, Andrea Bocelli, Carlo Guelfi and others, Florence Maggio Musicale Orchestra, Zubin Mehta, Decca 473 710-2.</ref> It did not attract unanimous praise, though. [[Andreas Dorschel]] notices \"monochrome timbre\" and \"little dynamic variability\" in Bocelli's performance: \"Whatever is suffered by Cavaradossi \u2212 torture for instance or the prospect of execution \u2212: Bocelli does not seem to register it, but goes on in the musical equivalent of Stoic indifference.\"<ref>Andreas Dorschel, 'The World's Favourite Tenor', ''[[Lettre International]]'' no. 120 (Spring 2018), pp. 136\u2212137, p. 136.</ref> At a private benefit gala for the [[Royal National Institute of Blind People]], Bocelli sang in front of the [[British Royal Family]].<ref name=\"BOC2003\"/> A day later he received two awards for ''Sentimento'' at the [[Classical BRIT Awards#2003|2003 Classical BRIT Award]] held at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in London \u2013 \"Best selling classical album\" and \"Album of the year\".<ref name=\"BBC2931456\">{{cite news|title=Bocelli tops Classical Brits|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2931456.stm|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=23 May 2003}}</ref> On 24 May, he performed in a benefit concert for the [[Arpa Foundation for Film, Music and Art]] in the [[Piazza del Campo]] in [[Siena]], with sopranos [[Maria Luigia Borsi]] and Lucia Dessanti, [[baritone]] Soo Kyung Ahn, and violinist Ruth Rogers, accompanied by Marcello Rota and the Orchestra Citt\u00e0 di Pisa. Three days later he was again invited to perform at \"Pavarotti & Friends\" in Modena and sang a medley of [[Music of Naples|Neapolitan songs]] together with Pavarotti. In June, he continued his ''Sentimento'' tour in [[Athens]] and [[Cyprus]]. In September, he took part in a concert for the Justice ministers and Interior ministers of the European Union at the [[Parco della Musica]] in Rome. He then resumed his tour, accompanied by [[Maria Luigia Borsi]], Ruth Rogers and Marcello Rota.<ref name=\"BOC2003\"/>\n\nBocelli won the \"Favourite Specialist Performer\"  award at the UK National Music Awards in October 2003.<ref name=\"BBC3216767\">{{cite news|title=Pop Idols dominate music awards|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3216767.stm|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=27 October 2003}}</ref> In November he once again toured in the United States, this time accompanied by Ana Maria Martinez, [[Kallen Esperian]] and [[Steven Mercurio]]. In December he gave his first concert in China and at the end of the month, sang Gounod's ''Ave Maria'' at Pavarotti's wedding in Modena.<ref name=\"BOC2003\"/>\n\nIn Bologna in January, he performed as [[Werther#Principal characters|Werther]] in four performances of the opera of the same name. In April and May, he toured Asia again, visiting Manila, Hong Kong and Singapore. In May, he took part in a concert at [[Circo Massimo]] in Rome organised by [[Quincy Jones]] to launch the \"[[Quincy Jones#Social activism|We are the Future]]\" project. In June, his third complete opera ''[[Il trovatore]]'' was released. In July, he played the part of Mario Cavaradossi in ''Tosca'' at the 50th Puccini Festival in Torre del Lago, and he took part in the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) global campaign for the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] in Athens.<ref name=\"BOC2004\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 2004|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle2004.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn September, he performed his \"Once in a Lifetime\" tour in Australia with concerts in Sydney and Melbourne and one concert in Christchurch, New Zealand, where he was joined on stage by New Zealand soprano [[Hayley Westenra]].<ref name=\"BOC2004_3\">{{cite web|title=Once in a Lifetime Tour|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert/2004_3.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 October, he performed at the [[Great Hall of the People|People Conference Hall]] in Beijing, China, and on 17 October at the Great Hall in Shanghai.<ref name=\"BOC2004_4\">{{cite web|title=Asia Tour|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert/2004_4.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nDuring early 2005, Bocelli was on tour including performances in [[Madeira]], Hungary, Norway, US, UK, Italy and Germany.<ref name=\"BOC2005\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 2005|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle2005.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref> He also appeared in ''[[Sesame Street]]'' singing \"Time to Say Goodnight\" a parody of \"Time to Say Goodbye\" as a lullaby to [[Elmo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sesame Street Parody Descriptions|url=http://www.sesameworkshop.org/aboutus/pressroom/presskits/season36/parody.php|accessdate=15 December 2013|newspaper=[[Sesame Workshop]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080119132344/http://www.sesameworkshop.org/aboutus/pressroom/presskits/season36/parody.php|archivedate=19 January 2008}}</ref> On 21 March, he performed at the ''Music for Asia'' benefit concert in Rome, televised on [[Italia 1]], in aid of the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake]] appeal.<ref name=\"BOC2005_1\">{{cite web|title=Asia Tour|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live2005_1.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn June, he performed at the Deutsche Opera in Berlin. On 2 July, he performed at the Paris concert as part of the [[Live 8]] event. Also during the second part of the year, he performed in Croatia, [[Serbia]], Italy, the US, [[Dubai]], Switzerland and finally in Scandinavia.<ref name=\"BOC2005\"/> On 28 August, he performed at the [[Faenol Festival]] held in [[Vaynol]], Wales and organised by Welsh [[bass-baritone]] [[Bryn Terfel]].<ref name=\"BOC2005_1\"/> In December, his first contemporary music concert took place at a [[Lake Las Vegas]] village resort in [[Nevada]], US, which was recorded for [[PBS]] and released as the ''[[Under the Desert Sky]]'' DVD. He also took part in the Royal Christmas Show, which took place in several cities in the US in December. The album ''Werther'' was released in December.\n\n===2006\u201307: ''Amore'' and ''Vivere, Greatest hits''===\n[[File:Bocelli.jpg|thumb|Bocelli rehearsing for his ''[[Under the Desert Sky]]'' concert in [[Lake Las Vegas]], 2006.]]\n\nOn 18 February, he sang at the [[Toyota Center]] in [[Houston]] during the [[National Basketball Association]]'s (NBA) 2006 [[NBA All-Star Weekend|All-Star Weekend]], and broadcast live on the [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] Cable television network.<ref name=\"NBA060215\">{{cite news|title=John Legend and Carrie Underwood Set for All-Star Halftime Show|publisher=[[National Basketball Association|NBA]]|year=2006|url=http://www.nba.com/allstar2006/Legend_Underwood_060215.html|accessdate=20 January 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080103090303/http://www.nba.com/allstar2006/Legend_Underwood_060215.html|archivedate=3 January 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February, Bocelli sang \"Because We Believe\" from his ''Amore'' album in the Carnevale section of the [[2006 Winter Olympics closing ceremony|closing ceremony of the Torino Olympics]].<ref name=\"BOC2006\">{{cite web|title=Bocelli 2006 Chronicle|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle2006.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref> He also began another tour with a concert at the Piazza di Castello in Turin.<ref name=\"BOC2006_1\">{{cite web|title=2006 tour (1)|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2006_1.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref> In March, he was honoured by the Italian state with a [[Italian orders of merit|Grande Ufficiale Italian Order of Merit]] (Grand Officer of the Italian Republic), given to him by then President of the Italian Republic, [[Carlo Azeglio Ciampi]]. The award was presented to him at the Sanremo Festival where he performed a duet with American singer [[Christina Aguilera]] on 4 March.<ref name=\"BOC2006\"/><ref name=\"radioitalia1169\">{{cite news|title=Pausini, Bocelli e Ramazotti: Onorificenze e serata finale del festival |language=Italian |publisher=[[Radio Italia Solo Musica Italiana]] |date=22 February 2006 |url=http://www.radioitalia.dit/web/news/news.php?idNews=1169 |accessdate=21 January 2008 }}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nFrom 31 March to 2 April, he took part in the Maggio Musicale in Florence where he sang the ''Canto di pace (Canto of peace)'' by [[Marco Tutino]]<ref name=\"cultura3743\">{{cite news|title=FIRENZE \u2013 Bocelli e il canto di Pace nato alle Muse|language=Italian|publisher=cultura.marche.it|date=March 2006|url=http://www.cultura.marche.it/CMDirector.aspx?idN=3743|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref> and the tenor part from [[Gioachino Rossini]]'s ''[[Messa di Gloria (Rossini)|Messa di Gloria]]'' and in Naples where he took part in Rossini's [[Petite messe solennelle]].<ref name=\"BOC2006\"/><ref name=\"BOC2006_1\"/>\n\nIn April 2006, he featured as a guest coach on ''[[American Idol (season 5)|American Idol]]'' helping the finalists sing the week's themed songs, \"Greatest Love Songs.\" He also performed on that week's results show.<ref name=\"BG060611\">{{cite news|last=Dyer |first=Richard |title=From 'American Idol' to Boston divo |publisher=[[J. C. Penney]] |date=11 June 2006 |url=http://www.boston.com.news/globe/living/articles/2006/06/11/from_american_idol_to_boston_divo/?page=1 |accessdate=22 January 2008 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> American Idol runner-up [[Katharine McPhee]] performed at three of Bocelli's concerts in California from 9 to 11 June singing duets of ''Somos Novios'' and ''The Prayer'' with Bocelli. They also performed on ''[[J. C. Penney]] Jam: The Concert for America's Kids''<ref name=\"JCP852901\">{{cite news|title=Dr. Phil and Music Superstars Join Forces for ''JCPENNEY JAM...THE CONCERT FOR AMERICA'S KIDS'' Mega Event to Air on CBS-TV During Back to School |publisher=[[J. C. Penney]] |date=March 2006 |url=http://www.ir.jcpenney.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=70528&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=852901&highlight |accessdate=21 January 2008 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and recorded duet versions of ''Somos Novios'' for the resulting album, and also ''[[Can't Help Falling in Love]]'' on the CD of the [[Under the Desert Sky]] DVD.\n\nIn June, he sang the Italian duet version of \"[[Because We Believe]]\", \"Ama, credi e vai\", with [[Gianna Nannini]] at the \"gro\u00dfen Fan Party\" at the opening of the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], in Berlin in front of billions of worldwide television viewers.\n\nOn 1 July 2007, Bocelli performed \"[[The Music of the Night]]\" from [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]]'s ''[[The Phantom of the Opera (1986 musical)|The Phantom of the Opera]]'', in a special musicals medley during the [[Concert for Diana]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] in London, England.<ref name=\"BBC070701\">{{cite news|title=Concert for Diana Timeline: What's happened minute by minute|publisher=[[BBC Entertainment]]|date=1 July 2007|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/1/concertfordiana/timeline/|accessdate=22 January 2008}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Bocelli returned to his home town for a concert at the newly created [[Teatro del Silenzio]] in [[Lajatico]] on 5 July 2007, with guest appearance by [[Kenny G]], [[Heather Headley]], [[Lang Lang]], [[Elisa (Italian singer)|Elisa]], [[Sarah Brightman]] and [[Laura Pausini]]. The concert was later released as ''[[Vivere Live in Tuscany]]''. In September, he debuted at the [[Avery Fisher Hall]], in New York, with four concerts. October saw the release of the opera album of [[Ruggiero Leoncavallo]]'s ''[[Pagliacci]]'' with Bocelli singing the role of [[Pagliacci#Roles|Canio]]. In November, he won the \"Best Italian Artist\" and \"World's Best-selling Classical Artist\" awards at the [[World Music Awards#2006 show|World Music Awards]]. In December, he finished his 2006 tour with more concerts in North America and Europe.<ref name=\"BOC2006\"/>\n\nBocelli and Sarah Brightman's duet version of \"Con te partir\u00f2\" was used in the 2007 film ''[[Blades of Glory]]'', as an ice skating song. [[K-1]] [[mixed martial arts]] fighter [[Yoshihiro Akiyama]] started using \"Con te partir\u00f2\" as his ring entrance music. On 8 September, Bocelli sang an arrangement of Mozart's ''[[Ave verum corpus (Mozart)|Ave verum corpus]]'' at the funeral of Luciano Pavarotti in Modena, Italy.\n\nOn 21 October 2007, he sang \"Con te partir\u00f2\" on the UK television series ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'' results show, and on 30 October, he sang \"The Prayer\" during an ITV Special ''An Audience with C\u00e9line Dion''. The show was broadcast on 23 December. Alongside fellow Italian singer [[Laura Pausini]], he sang ''Vive Ya'' during the 2007 Latin Grammy Awards. The song, originally released in 1997 as a duet in Italian between Bocelli and Italian singer-songwriter Trovatto on Bocelli's ''[[Romanza]]'', was also released in English on his 2007 album, ''[[The Best of Andrea Bocelli: Vivere]]'', as ''Dare to Live''. The album, ''[[The Best of Andrea Bocelli: Vivere|Vivere]]'', sold over 3 million copies.\n\n===2008: ''Incanto'' and ''Carmen''===\nOn 20 January 2008, Bocelli received the Italian TV award [[Telegatto]] in platinum for ''Italian music in the world'', in Rome. He sang \"La voce del silenzio\" \u2013 \"The voice of silence\" \u2013 and \"Dare to Live\" during the ceremony.<ref name=\"BOC2008\">{{cite news|title=live2008|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live2008_1.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:VeronicaBerti.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Bocelli with his then fianc\u00e9e Veronica Berti in Tokyo, Japan, during his ''2008 Asian Tour''.]]\n\nTo promote the album, he performed \"[[Canto della Terra]]\" at ''[[The Alan Titchmarsh Show]]'' on the BBC in London on 1 February; was interviewed by [[Fabio Fazio]] on the Italian talk show ''[[Che tempo che fa]]'' on [[RAI 3]] in Italy; and performed \"Canto della terra\", \"A te\" and \"Besame mucho\" from the album, as well as \"[[My Way]]\" on 2 February; and made an appearance on ''[[The South Bank Show]]'' in London, where he sang the French [[aria]] \"Pour mon \u00e2me\" on 3 February. Then on 10 February, he performed \"The Prayer\" at the [[50th Grammy Awards]], held in Los Angeles, with [[Josh Groban]] in a tribute to [[Luciano Pavarotti]], and sang \"[[Vivere (Dare to Live)|Dare to Live]]\" with [[Heather Headley]] the following day on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]''.<ref name=\"BOC2008\" />\n\nIn April, he toured in Asia with performances in Tokyo, [[Taichung]], and Seoul.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert1\">\n{{cite news|title=live concert2008/1|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2008_1.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 May 2008, he sang at [[Steel Ar\u00e9na]] in [[Ko\u0161ice]], Slovakia, in front of 8,000 people.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert2\">\n{{cite news|title=live concert2008/2|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2008_2.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> Then 13 May he sang at the ''\"Teatro delle Muse\"'' in [[Ancona]], Italy, for a charity concert for \"Francesca Rava \u2013 N.P.H. Italia Onlus\", a foundation that helps poor and disabled children around the world.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert2\" />\n\nOn 23 May 2008, he sang ''The Prayer'' with [[Katharine McPhee]] in a Las Vegas tribute concert for Canadian producer and songwriter [[David Foster]]. Bocelli later praised Filipina teen-aged singer [[Charice]], whom he had first heard perform at that concert.<ref>{{cite web|author=di Paolo Giordano|url=http://www.ilgiornale.it/a.pic1?ID=264800|title=Bocelli: \"Verdi, il mio canto patriottico nell'Italia della riconciliazione\"|publisher=Ilgiornale.it|date=28 May 2008|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.charicemania.com/charicemaniacom/2008/06/in-realt-il-mon.html Charicemania \u2013 Charice Pempengco Blog : Andrea Bocelli in a Possible Duet With Charice?<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080918015918/http://www.charicemania.com/charicemaniacom/2008/06/in-realt-il-mon.html |date=18 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 2 June 2008, he performed at the [[Piazza del Duomo, Milan]] in front of 80,000 people during a concert celebrating the anniversary of the Republic of Italy's formation.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert2\" />\n\nFrom 17 to 28 June, Bocelli played the role of Don Jos\u00e9 on stage, opposite Hungarian [[mezzo-soprano]] [[Ildik\u00f3 Koml\u00f3si]] as [[Carmen]], in [[Georges Bizet]]'s opera at the [[Teatro dell'Opera di Roma]], in Rome, for four nights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moltoitaly.com/2008/05/andrea-bocelli-in-carmen-at-teatro.html|title=Andrea Bocelli in Carmen at the Teatro dell'Opera|publisher=Molto Italy|date=|accessdate=28 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828065809/http://www.moltoitaly.com/2008/05/andrea-bocelli-in-carmen-at-teatro.html|archive-date=28 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[https://archive.today/20120709231831/http://en.operaroma.it/stagione/cartellone_2008/carmen The 2008 production of ''Carmen'' at the Teatro dell'Opera di Roma], Official [[Teatro dell'Opera di Roma]] website.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/opera2008.htm|title=Live \u2013 Opera|publisher=www.bocelli.de|date=|accessdate=28 July 2013}}</ref> Bocelli released the complete opera recording of ''Carmen'' in Italy in the same year, which he recorded in 2005. [[Myung-whun Chung]] conducted the [[Orchestre Philharmonique de Radio France]] and the Ch\u0153ur de Radio France for the recording, and Welsh [[Bass-baritone]] [[Bryn Terfel]], was part of the Ensemble.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicalsource.com/db_control/db_cd_review.php?id=8390|title=Carmen \u2013 Marina Domashenko, Andrea Bocelli & Bryn Terfel|publisher=Classicalsource.com|date=24 October 2005|accessdate=28 July 2013}}</ref> The recording was not released internationally, until March 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mightyape.co.nz/product/Bizet-Carmen/4443347|title=Bizet: ''Carmen'' \u2013 Andrea Bocelli, Bryn Terfel|publisher=Mightyape.co.nz|date=8 March 2010|accessdate=28 July 2013}}</ref> ''[[Carmen: Duets & Arias]]'', a single-disc collection of some of the arias and duets of the recording, was also released in 2010.<ref name=\"Carmen: Duets & Arias on iclassics\">[http://www.iclassics.com/artist/releases/release.aspx?pid=64137&aid=108 ''Carmen: Duets & Arias'' on iclassics]{{dead link|date=June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 July, Bocelli held his third concert at the Teatro del Silenzio in [[Lajatico]], his hometown. The concert was a tribute to the [[cinema of Italy]]. Its performers included Italian composer and musician [[Nicola Piovani]], Italian ballet dancer [[Roberto Bolle]], Israeli singer [[Achinoam Nini|Noa]], and Charice.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert3\">\n{{cite news|title=live concert2008/3|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2008_3.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> Then on 31 July, he performed at a concert in [[Vingis Park]] in [[Vilnius]], [[Lithuania]], in front of more than 18,000 people.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert4\">\n{{cite news|title=live concert2008/4|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2008_4.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> Australian singer [[Tina Arena]] performed two duets with Bocelli \u2013 \"Canto Della Terra\" and \"[[The Prayer (Celine Dion and Andrea Bocelli song)|The Prayer]]\" \u2013 at the closing stages of the concert.<ref name=\"August 2008\">\n{{cite web|title=Impromptu onstage appearance|publisher=tinaarena.com|url=http://tinaarena.com/index.php?module=news&section=newsdetail&secid=86&lang=en|accessdate=24 December 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203033918/http://tinaarena.com/index.php?module=news&section=newsdetail&secid=86&lang=en|archivedate=3 February 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 August 2008, he held a benefit concert at [[Medjugorje]], [[Bosnia Herzegovina]], and was accompanied by the [[Czech National Symphony Orchestra]].<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert4\" /> Then, during the rest of August, he was on tour in Australia and New Zealand for the third time.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert4\" /> [[Tina Arena]] performed with him in all 5 concerts during the tour.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tina Joins Andrea Bocelli for His Australian Tour|url=http://tinaarena.com/index.php?module=news&section=newsdetail&secid=85&lang=en|accessdate=15 December 2013|newspaper=Tina Arena|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203033914/http://tinaarena.com/index.php?module=news&section=newsdetail&secid=85&lang=en|archivedate=3 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 September 2008, during the 2008 [[Veneto]] Festival, he held a concert in the [[Church of the Eremitani]] in [[Padova]], Italy. He was accompanied by the [[I Solisti Veneti]] orchestra, celebrating its 50th birthday and conducted by [[Claudio Scimone]], and by the [[Wiener Singakademie]] choir. The concert was a celebration of [[Giacomo Puccini]]'s 150th birthday.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert5\">\n{{cite news|title=live concert2008/5|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2008_5.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 and 11 October he performed at [[Petra]], singing \"[[Vivere (Dare to Live)|Dare to Live]]\" with [[Laura Pausini]], as well as performing \"E Lucevan le Stelle\" from ''Tosca''. On 19 October, he sang \"[['O surdato 'nnammurato]]\" and a duet of \"Non Ti Scordar Di Me\" with [[Cecilia Bartoli]], both from the ''[[Incanto]]'' album, during the [[Echo (music award)|ECHO Awards]] in Germany; and later presented the soprano with an ECHO award. On 24 October, he performed at ''[[Piazza del Plebiscito]]'' in Naples, as a tribute to the city, where he celebrated the Italian release of ''Incanto''. Performing with him were flautist Andrea Griminelli, Italian pop singer [[Massimo Ranieri]] and soprano [[Cecilia Bartoli]], with [[Steven Mercurio]] conducting the [[Czech National Symphony Orchestra]].<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert6\">\n{{cite news|title=live concert2008/6|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2008_6.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> On 31 October, he performed a solo version of \"The Prayer\", as well as \"[[Because (1902 song)|Because]]\", a song from ''Incanto'', live on [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]].<ref name=\"october 2008\">\n{{cite web|title=Live with Faith Hill & David Foster|publisher=www.oprah.com|url=http://www.oprah.com/slideshow/oprahshow/20081031_tows_fridays/9|accessdate=31 October 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206193215/http://www.oprah.com/slideshow/oprahshow/20081031_tows_fridays/9|archivedate=6 December 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 and 22 November Bocelli was amongst a quartet of soloists (soprano [[Sabina Cvilak]], [[mezzo-soprano]] [[Kate Aldrich]] and [[bass (voice type)|bass]] [[Alexander Vinogradov (bass)|Alexander Vinogradov]]) to sing Rossini's ''[[Petite messe solennelle]]'', conducted by [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], at the [[Washington National Opera]] in Washington, D.C.<ref name=\"Petite messe solennelle\">\n{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli and Pl\u00e1cido Domingo together for the first time in Petite Messe Solennelle |publisher=www.dc-opera.org |year=2008 |url=http://www.dc-opera.org/ourseason/petitemesse.asp |accessdate=24 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090125102140/http://www.dc-opera.org/ourseason/petitemesse.asp |archivedate=25 January 2009 }}</ref> Bocelli sang twice in the piece and later the two tenors sang \"[[The Pearl Fishers' Duet]]\" which would be the first [[aria]] they had ever sung together.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert7\">\n{{cite news|title=live concert2008/7|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2008_7.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> On 25 and 26 November he starred alongside soprano [[Ver\u00f3nica Villarroel]] in an opera in concert of Mascagni's [[Cavalleria rusticana]] at the ''\"Municipal Auditorium\"'' in [[San Antonio]], Texas.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert7\" /> He later held a concert at ''\"Atrio de la Catedral\"'' in [[Campeche]], Mexico, on 28 November, where he sang songs from ''Incanto'' as well as some of his Spanish hits, including ''[[B\u00e9same Mucho]]'', ''[[Somos Novios]]'', ''[[Amapola (song)|Amapola]]'' and ''[[Por ti Volare]]'' \u2013 the Spanish version of ''Con te Partiro''.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert7\" />\n\n===2009: ''My Christmas'', first holiday album===\nOn 27 May 2009, Bocelli sang \"Il Gladiatore\", from the [[Gladiator (soundtrack)|Gladiator]] soundtrack, followed by the [[UEFA Champions League Anthem]], which is based on \"[[Zadok the Priest]]\" by G.F. Handel, during the opening ceremony of the [[2009 UEFA Champions League Final]], in the [[Stadio Olimpico]], in Rome.\n\nOn 3 November, ''[[My Christmas]]'', his first [[Christmas music|Holiday album]], produced by [[David Foster]], was released and went on to become the [[List of best-selling Christmas/holiday albums in the United States#2000s|best-selling Holiday album of the year]].\n\nThe ''[[My Christmas Special|Andrea Bocelli & David Foster Christmas Special]]'', the [[PBS]] special of the album, first aired on [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving]] night in the United States, and continued to be broadcast in the United States and Canada throughout the month of December. In late November, the program was broadcast in [[Mexico]] and in the UK; it later aired, 15 and 25 December, on [[Italia 1]], in Italy, 19 December, on [[TVE2]] and [[TROS]], in Spain and the Netherlands, and Christmas Eve, on [[vtm]] and [[RTL T\u00e9l\u00e9 L\u00ebtzebuerg|RTL-TVI]], in Belgium and [[Luxembourg]].\n\n[[File:Andrea Bocelli with piano @ Premio Faraglioni 2009.JPG|thumb|Bocelli performing at the Premio Faraglioni 2009.]]\n\nOn 3 November, during the World Premiere of [[Disney]]'s ''[[A Christmas Carol (2009 film)|A Christmas Carol]]'', in [[Leicester Square]], London, following the switching on of the annual [[Oxford Street]] and [[Regent Street]] Christmas lights, Bocelli led the [[St Paul's Cathedral]] [[Choir]], and more than 14,000 people across the capital, as they broke the Official [[Guinness World Record]] for the biggest ever [[Christmas carol]] [[sing-along]], singing \"[[Silent Night]]\". He completed his performance in Leicester Square with,  \"God Bless Us Everyone\", the closing song of the movie, which he provided the vocals for in English, Italian and Spanish.<ref name=\"Bocelli - A Christmas Carol (1)\">\n{{cite web|title=Bocelli leads Christmas carol sing-along|publisher=[[Classic FM (UK)|ClassicFm]].co.uk, 3 November 2010 article|url=http://www.classicfm.co.uk/music/music-news-and-features/bocelli-leads-christmas-carol-sing-along/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20111011083648/http://www.classicfm.co.uk/music/music-news-and-features/bocelli-leads-christmas-carol-sing-along/|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 October 2011|accessdate=4 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Bocelli - A Christmas Carol (2)\">\n{{cite web|title=Record breaking night for London's Christmas Carol-themed lights switch-on|publisher=Indielondon.co.uk, 3 November 2010 article|url=http://www.indielondon.co.uk/Film-Review/record-breaking-night-for-london-s-christmas-carol-themed-lights-switch-on|accessdate=4 April 2010}}</ref> He returned to the United Kingdom, 16 December, for an appearance on ''[[The One Show]]'', broadcast live by [[BBC One]], and on ''[[The Alan Titchmarsh Show]]'' which aired 18 December, on [[ITV1]].\n\nOn 21 November, a segment of ''Leute Heute'', a German [[Tabloid television|tabloid-program]] on [[ZDF]], was about ''My Christmas'' and Bocelli's meeting in Rome with [[Pope Benedict XVI]] and 250 other artists, an event which was broadcast live earlier that day in Italy, by [[Rai Uno]]. Bocelli was also joined by the [[Piccolo Coro dell'Antoniano]], in his home in [[Forte dei Marmi]], where they sang \"Caro Ges\u00f9 Bambino\", a song from ''My Christmas'' which was [[List of songs recorded by Zecchino d'Oro|originally recorded by the choir in 1960]]. [[Rai Uno]] also broadcast the performance later that day, during the [[Zecchino d'Oro|Zecchino d'Oro Festival]]. The following day, Bocelli was among Fabio Fazio's guests, on his popular Italian talk-show, [[Che tempo che fa]], broadcast on [[Rai Tre]]. During the program Bocelli talked about his album and performed \"[[The Lord's Prayer]]\", \"[[White Christmas (song)|White Christmas]]\", and \"[[Silent Night]]\". It was also announced that Bocelli would return to the show on 20 December and give a live concert of ''My Christmas''. Bocelli also took part in the annual [[Jos\u00e9 Carreras#Humanitarian work|2009 ''Jos\u00e9 Carreras Gala'']], on 17 December, where he sang [[Adeste Fideles]], before singing \"White Christmas\" with [[Jos\u00e9 Carreras]] for the very first time; this was broadcast live, by [[Das Erste]], in Germany. He then returning to Italy, for a concert in the [[Basilica of San Francesco d'Assisi#The Upper Basilica of St. Francis|Upper Basilica of San Francesco d'Assisi]], on 19 December, which was broadcast directly after the ''[[Urbi et Orbi]]'' blessing of Pope Benedict XVI, 25 December, on [[Rai Uno]].\n\nIn North America, Bocelli gave 6 concerts. On 28 November, he performed in the [[BankAtlantic Center]], in [[Ft. Lauderdale, Florida]]. He later performed in the [[Air Canada Centre]], in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada, in the [[Izod Center]], in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]], in the [[Fresno Convention Center#Saroyan Theatre|William Saroyan Theatre]], in [[Fresno, California]] (changed from the much larger [[Save Mart Center]] due to scheduling conflicts), in the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena|MGM Grand]], in [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas]], and finally in the [[Honda Center]], in [[Anaheim, California]], on 3, 5, 8, 12 and 13 December. His last three arena concerts alone grossed a total of over 5,6 million dollars, placing him third on [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard Magazine]]'s week's Hot Tours ranking, behind the [[Trans-Siberian Orchestra]] and [[Il Divo]], who both held over 5 times more concerts worldwide, compared to Bocelli's three in the United States, explaining their better showings.<ref>{{cite news|last=Allen|first=Bob|title=Hot Tours: Trans-Siberian Orchestra, Il Divo, Andrea Bocelli|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/photos/live/960815/hot-tours-trans-siberian-orchestra-il-divo-andrea-bocelli|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=Billboard|date=5 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, Bocelli made a number of high-profile TV appearances. He first performed \"White Christmas\" at the 83rd annual [[Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade]], broadcast live on [[NBC]], 26 November. He performed the song again on 30 November during ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|The Today Show]]'' also live. His appearance on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' during her ''Holiday Music Extravaganza'', where he sang \"[[What Child Is This (Andrea Bocelli and Mary J. Blige cover)|What Child Is This]]\", with [[Mary J. Blige]], and later closed the show with [[Adeste Fideles]], was also aired the same day, and was later rebroadcast on 23 December. Bocelli also sang \"Adeste Fideles\" and was interviewed by [[Barbara Walters]] and [[Joy Behar]] on ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'', which aired 2 December, on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]. On 8 December, he performed \"[[Jingle Bells]]\" with [[The Muppets]] on ''[[The Jay Leno Show]]''. He also performed a number of songs from the album, including \"[[The Christmas Song]]\" with [[Natalie Cole]], during a dinner at [[David Foster]]'s [[mansion]] in [[Malibu, California|Malibu]], which was featured on ''[[Dr. Phil (TV series)|The Dr. Phil Show]]'', on 10 December. Bocelli also performed \"White Christmas\" and  \"[[Silent Night]]\", on the ''[[Larry King Live]]'' and ''[[Fox & Friends]]'' holiday-specials, broadcast 23 December, on [[CNN]], and 19, 24 and 25 December, on [[Fox News Channel|Fox News]].\n\nIn [[Brasil]], following the success of the South American leg of the ''Incanto tour'', where over 100,000 people attended his free concert at the [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]'s \"Parque Indipendencia\", earlier in the year,<ref>{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli Performs to 100,000 in Brazil|url=http://www.classicfm.com/artists/andrea-bocelli/news/andrea-bocelli-performs-100000-brazil/|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=[[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]]}}</ref> it was announced that Bocelli would hold another [[open-air concert|Open-Air]], entrance free, concert in [[Florian\u00f3polis]], on 28 December, where a crowd of about a million people was expected to attend. However, due to financial and political reasons, the concert was later canceled on short notice, along with all the other events scheduled for Christmas in the city.\n\n===2010: Hollywood Walk of Fame and FIFA World Cup===\nOn 31 January 2010, during the [[52nd Grammy Awards]], Bocelli, [[Mary J. Blige]] and David Foster joined forces again, singing \"[[Bridge over Troubled Water (song)|Bridge over Troubled Water]]\" as a tribute to the victims of that year's [[2010 Haiti earthquake|earthquake in Haiti]].<ref name=\"Bocelli in 2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live2010_1.htm|title=Andrea Bocelli in 2010|publisher=Bocelli.de}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1001/30/lkl.01.html|title=CNN Larry King Live Transcript \u2013 Episode 30 January 2010|publisher=CNN|date=30 January 2010|accessdate=28 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:DavidFosterMar10.jpg|right|upright|thumb|[[David Foster]] speaks at the ceremony honoring Bocelli with his star.]]\n\nOn 2 March, he was honoured with a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] for his contribution to [[Theatre|Live Theater]], at 7000 [[Hollywood Boulevard]], in front of the [[Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel|Roosevelt Hotel]].<ref name=\"Bocelli gets Star (1)\">{{cite news|title=Hollywood Walk of Fame Honors Andrea Bocelli|url=http://ireport.cnn.com/docs/DOC-415682|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=[[CNN iReport]]|date=3 March 2010}}</ref> The previous day, Bocelli, along with David Foster, were honored by ''L.A. Italia Film, Fashion and Art Fest'' during a ceremony at the [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]], in Hollywood, where ''The Story Behind The Voice'', a documentary about Bocelli's life and career was shown.<ref>{{cite news|last=Olivier|first=Ellen|title=L.A. Italia Film, Fashion and Art Fest honors tenor Andrea Bocelli and producer David Foster|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/mar/07/image/la-ig-scene-20100307|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=7 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, Bocelli made an appearance on [[Skavlan]], in [[Oslo]], Norway, to promote his upcoming [[Scandinavia|Scandinavian tour]], giving a rare interview to the show's host [[Fredrik Skavlan]], and later performing \"Voglio Vivere Cosi\", from his 2008 album ''Incanto'', with [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] [[Boys' choir]], [[S\u00f8lvguttene]].<ref name=\"Bocelli in 2010\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Hansen|first=Magne|title=Andrea Bocelli og kokken som sa nei til Obama p\u00e5 Skavlan|url=http://www.nrk.no/kultur/andrea-bocelli-til-skavlan-1.7031646|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=[[NRK]]|date=10 March 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nIn April, he returned to Scandinavia for a concert in [[Telenor Arena]] in B\u00e6rum, Norway, on 8 April, a concert in [[Forum Copenhagen]] in Copenhagen, Denmark, on 9 April, and finally a concert in the [[Ericsson Globe]], in Stockholm, Sweden, on 11 April. He was joined by [[Heather Headley]] and 120 musicians from the Stockholm Concert Orchestra, in all three concerts, and by Swedish [[mezzo-soprano]] [[Malena Ernman]] in his Swedish concert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bocelli.de/live/konzert2010_2.htm|title=Andrea Bocelli April 2010 events|publisher=Bocelli.de|date=|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bocelli \u2013 with a little help from Ernman|url=http://www.nordstjernan.com/news/sweden/2121|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=[[Nordstjernan (newspaper)|Nordstjernan]]}}</ref><ref>[http://www.kulturspegeln.se/andrea-bocelli-i-globenstockholm-concert-orchestra Andrea Bocelli i Globen Stockholm Concert Orchestra], Swedish article. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804140143/http://www.kulturspegeln.se/andrea-bocelli-i-globenstockholm-concert-orchestra |date=4 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April, Bocelli sang \"[[Nessun dorma]]\" during [[2010 Shanghai Expo opening ceremony|the opening ceremony]] of the [[Expo 2010]], in Shanghai, China.<ref>{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli on stage with Chinese girl for Shanghai Expo|url=http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90776/90883/6969737.html|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=People's Daily Online|date=30 April 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article7112559.ece Size matters at Shanghai Expo 2010], [[The Times]], 30 April 2010 article.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bodeen |first=Christopher |title=Sarkozy, other leaders in Shanghai for World Expo |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/nationworld/2011741071_apaschinaexpo.html |accessdate=10 December 2013 |newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=30 April 2010 |agency=AP |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216090812/http://seattletimes.com/html/nationworld/2011741071_apaschinaexpo.html |archivedate=16 December 2013 }}</ref> The following day, on 1 May, he held a concert, titled ''Charming China'', at [[Shanghai Stadium]].<ref>[http://cityweekend.com.cn/shanghai/events/64616 Glamour of China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305075454/http://www.cityweekend.com.cn/shanghai/events/64616 |date=5 March 2016 }}, [[City Weekend]].</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Daiqi|first=Xing|title=Expo showcases music, art and culture|url=http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90782/90872/6968222.html|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=[[People's Daily]]|date=30 April 2010}}</ref> The concert was later broadcast by [[Shanghai Television|Shanghai TV]], and by [[China Central Television|CCTV]] [[CCTV Channels|channels]] throughout [[mainland China]].\n\n[[File:Song Bocelli Lang East Meets West (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Andrea Bocelli and [[Song Zuying]] performing ''[[Con te partir\u00f2|Time to Say Goodbye]]'' at the ''East Meets West'' concert.]]\n\nThe two appearances coincided with Bocelli's Asian tour, consisting of a concert in [[Nippon Budokan|Budokan]], Tokyo, Japan, on 28 April,<ref>{{cite news|last=Grunebaum|first=Dan|title=Andrea Bocelli|url=http://metropolis.co.jp/arts/agenda/andrea-bocelli/|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=[[Metropolis (free magazine)|Metropolis]]|date=15 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eplus.jp/sys/web/s/bocelli/index.html|title=Andrea Bocelli: Live in Japan 2010|publisher=Eplus.jp|accessdate=6 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229042746/http://eplus.jp/sys/web/s/bocelli/index.html|archive-date=29 February 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> a concert in [[Jamsil Students' Gymnasium|Jamsil Gymnasium]], [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]], on 2 May,<ref>{{cite news|last=Hyo-won|first=Lee|title=Andrea Bocelli to Become One With Audience|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2010/04/135_64532.html|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=20 April 2010}}</ref> a concert in [[Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Centre]], in Hong Kong, on 4 May,<ref name=\"HK 2010 (1)\">{{cite news|last=Chen|first=Yali|title=Bocellimania to sweep music fans in a week|url=http://www.etaiwannews.com/etn/news_content.php?id=1231188&lang=eng_news|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=[[Taiwan News]]|date=20 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"HK 2010 (2)\">{{cite news|last=Chen |first=Yali |title=Bocelli to hold concerts in Hong Kong, Taipei |url=http://www.culture.tw/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1691&Itemid=235 |accessdate=12 December 2013 |newspaper=Taiwan Culture Portal |date=16 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203010601/http://www.culture.tw/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1691&Itemid=235 |archivedate= 3 December 2013 }}</ref> a concert in [[Taipei Arena]], [[Taipei]], [[Taiwan]], on 6 May,<ref name=\"HK 2010 (1)\"/><ref name=\"HK 2010 (2)\"/> and finally a free concert, organized by the [[YTL Corporation]], at the [[Singapore Botanic Gardens]], in Singapore, on 8 May, attended by over 12,000 people, picked via [[Ballot|public ballot]].<ref>[http://www.ytlconcert2010.com.sg/ YTL Concert of Celebration 2010] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401133012/http://www.ytlconcert2010.com.sg/ |date=1 April 2010 }}, Official YTL Concerts 2010 site.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=12,000 enjoy Andrea Bocelli treat|url=http://www.ytlcommunity.com/commnews/shownews.asp?newsid=53168|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=YTL Community|date=9 May 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.kl-lifestyle.com.my/2010/05/enchated-night-with-andrea-bocelli Enchated Night with Andrea Bocelli], ''KL-lifestyle.com'', 11 May 2010, article. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724055742/http://www.kl-lifestyle.com.my/2010/05/enchated-night-with-andrea-bocelli |date=24 July 2012 }}</ref> The concert was later broadcast, in its entirety, by [[Channel NewsAsia]], on 28 and 29 May, and by [[Okto]], on 30 May, in Singapore. An [[Orchidaceae|orchid]] in the [[Singapore Botanic Gardens|Botanic Gardens']] [[National Orchid Garden]] was also named after Bocelli in response to the concert.<ref>{{cite web|author=ria tan|url=http://wildsingaporenews.blogspot.com/2010/05/nparks-to-introduce-more-orchid-species.html|title=Singapore Botanic Gardens: Orchid named after Andrea Bocelli|publisher=Wildsingaporenews.blogspot.com|date=15 May 2010|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> Australian pop singer [[Delta Goodrem]] performed again with Bocelli in all five concerts, after supporting him in his United States [[My Christmas|My Christmas 2009 winter tour]].<ref>[http://www.accessallareas.net.au/music_news/EkVAEplpuZihJNFJqK.php Delta Goodrem to support Andrea Bocelli in the US] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902022733/http://www.accessallareas.net.au/music_news/EkVAEplpuZihJNFJqK.php |date=2 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May, during the [[2010 World Music Awards]], Bocelli performed \"Un Amore Cosi Grande\" from his 2008 album, ''Incanto'', and received his seventh [[World Music Awards|World Music Award]], for \"Best Classical Artist\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Sheridan|first=Emily|title=Jennifer Lopez shows her wild side in two animal-print dresses at the World Music Awards|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1279581/World-Music-Awards-Jennifer-Lopez-shows-wild-animal-print-dresses.html|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=Mail Online|date=19 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldmusicawards.com|title=World Music Awards Official Site|publisher=Worldmusicawards.com|date=|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 July, Bocelli gave a concert at the opening of the [[Khan Shatyr Entertainment Center]], in [[Astana]], on the occasion of [[Kazakhstan]]'s [[List of leaders of Kazakhstan|president]] [[Nursultan Nazarbayev]]'s 70th birthday.<ref>{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli books gig in Kazakhstan|url=http://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/Music/2010/06/15/Andrea-Bocelli-books-gig-in-Kazakhstan/UPI-60551276624467|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=[[United Press International]]|date=15 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Orange|first=Richard|title=Giant indoor park opened for Kazakh president's birthday|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/kazakhstan/7873035/Giant-indoor-park-opened-for-Kazakh-presidents-birthday.html|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=5 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 July, Bocelli headlined the \"Celebrate Africa: The Grand Finale\" Concert at the [[Coca-Cola Dome]], in [[Johannesburg]], South Africa, to mark the end of the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]], two days before the [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final|final]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bocelli, Bryan Adams To Headline 'Grand Finale' Concert at World Cup|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/958430/bocelli-bryan-adams-to-headline-grand-finale-concert-at-world-cup|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=Billboard|date=29 April 2010|agency=AP}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/Bryan+Adams+Bocelli+sing+World+finale/2966918/story.html |title=Bryan Adams, Bocelli to sing at World Cup finale |newspaper=[[The Vancouver Sun]] |date=29 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100502160540/http://www.vancouversun.com/entertainment/Bryan%2BAdams%2BBocelli%2Bsing%2BWorld%2Bfinale/2966918/story.html |archivedate= 2 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn 13 July, [[Statehood Day (Montenegro)|Montenegrin Statehood Day]], Bocelli gave a concert at the seaside resort of [[Sveti Stefan]], in western [[Montenegro]], to mark the [[Golden Jubilee]] of the [[Aman Resorts#Locations|Sveti Stefan Hotel]].<ref name=\"Bocelli in Montenegro\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20100723144407/http://www.traveldailynews.com/pages/show_page/38032-The-anniversary-of-the-Sveti-Stefan-Hotel-marked-by-a-concert-by-Andrea-Bocelli The anniversary of the Sveti Stefan Hotel marked by a concert by Andrea Bocelli], 20 July 2010 article.</ref>\n\nOn 14 July, Bocelli gave a concert at the [[European Parliament]]'s [[Espace L\u00e9opold]], in [[Brussels]], Belgium, during \"Rome in the heart of the future\", an event hosted by the [[Vice President of the European Parliament]] for the [[seventh European Parliament|seventh parliament]], [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]], [[Roberta Angelilli]].<ref name=\"Bocelli: Euro Parliament 2010\">[http://eppgroup.eu/press/showPR.asp?PRControlDocTypeID=1&PRControlID=9563&PRContentID=16367&PRContentLg=en Rome in the heart of the future: Invitation by Vice-President of the European Parliament, Roberta Angelilli MEP] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720160223/http://eppgroup.eu/press/showPR.asp?PRControlDocTypeID=1&PRControlID=9563&PRContentID=16367&PRContentLg=en |date=20 July 2011 }}, [[European People's Party (European Parliament group)|EPP Group]], 13 July 2010 article.</ref><ref>[http://gary-brusselsblog.blogspot.com/2010/07/lunchtime-with-andrea-bocelli.html Lunchtime with Andrea Bocelli], 14 July 2010 article.</ref> A screening of the film ''Homage to Rome'', directed by [[Franco Zeffirelli]], who was present during the event, and starring Bocelli, in his [[Film|cinematographic]] debut, was shown prior to the special concert.<ref name=\"Bocelli: Euro Parliament 2010\"/><ref>[http://www.iltempo.it/cronaca_locale/roma/2010/07/12/1179014-bocelli_cantera_bruxelles.shtml?refresh_ce Bocelli canter\u00e0 a Bruxelles] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928121826/http://www.iltempo.it/cronaca_locale/roma/2010/07/12/1179014-bocelli_cantera_bruxelles.shtml?refresh_ce |date=28 September 2012 }}, [[Il Tempo]], 12 July 2010 article.</ref>\n\nOn 25 July, Bocelli held the fifth and final edition of the [[Teatro del Silenzio]], in his hometown of [[Lajatico]], Tuscany. Bocelli's guests included Spanish [[Catalonia|Catalan]] tenor [[Jos\u00e9 Carreras]], and Italian rock singer [[Zucchero]]. Sculptures by Swiss artist [[Kurt Laurenz Metzler]], who attended the concert, were exhibited during this year's edition. Bocelli was also awarded the ''Pisano Doc'', during the dress rehearsal for the concert, on 24 July, and received the 2010 ''Premio Lunezia nel mondo'', during a private ceremony held on 21 July, for \"the musical-literary quality of his songs.\"\n\nIn September 2010, Bocelli held a concert at the [[Odeon of Herodes Atticus]], in [[Athens]], Greece. All proceeds were donated to help cure cancer. Bocelli also gave concerts in [[Cairo]], Egypt, in front of the pyramids and the [[Great Sphinx of Giza]], as well as a fundraising concert inside the [[Duomo di Milano]] to benefit victims of the [[2010 Haiti earthquake]].\n\nAs part of the 2010 leg of the [[My Christmas Tour]], Bocelli gave two concerts in [[The O2 Arena]], in London, and the [[Manchester Arena]], in [[Manchester]], and a concert at [[3Arena|The O2]], in [[Dublin]], in late November 2010.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sweeting|first=Adam|title=Andrea Bocelli, O2 Arena, review|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/classicalconcertreviews/8134168/Andrea-Bocelli-O2-Arena-review.html|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=15 November 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.citylife.co.uk/news_and_reviews/reviews/10018833_review__andrea_bocelli___men_arena Andrea Bocelli concert review] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323005306/http://www.citylife.co.uk/news_and_reviews/reviews/10018833_review__andrea_bocelli___men_arena |date=23 March 2012 }}, [[City Life (magazine)|citylife]].co.uk, 26 November 2010 article.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bandsintown.com/event/3289068-andrea-bocelli-dublin-ireland-live-at-the-o2-dublin-on-november-22-2010|title=Andrea Bocelli live in Dublin, Ireland|publisher=Bandsintown.com|date=12 November 2010|accessdate=6 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309142827/http://www.bandsintown.com/event/3289068-andrea-bocelli-dublin-ireland-live-at-the-o2-dublin-on-november-22-2010|archive-date=9 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> His sold-out concert at the O2 in London, was the most attended show in the venue's history, with 16,500 people attending the event.<ref>[http://www.classicfm.co.uk/music/latest-music-news/andrea-bocelli-makes-history-o2 Andrea Bocelli makes history at O2], [[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]], 16 November 2010 article.</ref> In early December, Bocelli gave 6 concerts in the United States. He performed in [[Madison Square Garden]], in New York City, [[Prudential Center]], in [[Newark, New Jersey]], [[TD Garden]], in [[Boston]], Toyota Center, in Houston, [[Staples Center]], in Los Angeles, and the [[MGM Grand Las Vegas|MGM Grand]]'s [[MGM Grand Garden Arena|Garden Arena]], in the [[Las Vegas Strip]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Kel|url=http://www.clickitticket.com/blog/post/Andrea-Bocelli-Brings-His-Christmas-to-the-US.aspx|title=Andrea Bocelli Brings His Christmas to the US|publisher=Clickitticket.com|date=|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nBocelli also took part in the [[Christmas in Washington]] special on 12 December.<ref name=\"Obama\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tnt.tv/christmasinwashington/display/?contentId=77664|title=Andrea Bocelli on TNT's Official Website|publisher=Tnt.tv|accessdate=6 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302080921/http://www.tnt.tv/christmasinwashington/display/?contentId=77664|archivedate=2 March 2012}}</ref> On 19 December, Bocelli gave a concert, conducted by [[Claudio Scimone]], in the [[Italian Senate]].<ref>[http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2010_11.htm Bocelli concert at Italian Senate], Bocelli.de.</ref>\n\n===2011: Metropolitan Opera recital, and Central Park Concert===\nIn January, Bocelli gave three concerts in Germany. The concerts in [[Munich]], Berlin, and [[Hamburg]] were all part of the [[Notte Illuminata|Notte Illuminata Tour]], launched in [[Pisa]], at the Teatro Verdi, December 2010. In February, Bocelli performed a recital on the stage of the [[Metropolitan Opera]] house as part of the tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metoperafamily.org/metopera/news/press/detail.aspx?id=12376 |title=Andrea Bocelli to Make Met Recital Debut |publisher=Metoperafamily.org |accessdate=6 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415070627/http://www.metoperafamily.org/metopera/news/press/detail.aspx?id=12376 |archivedate=15 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn late March, early April, as part of the 2011 Latin Leg of his Incanto Tour, Bocelli gave concerts in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Bogot\u00e1]], and [[Panama City]].\n\nIn May 2011, Bocelli held 5 concerts in East and Southeast Asia, and was joined by New Zealand soprano [[Hayley Westenra]] during the tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/ShowNews/WebNews_Detail.aspx?Type=aALL&ID=201104140022 |title=Hayley Westenra to perform at Bocelli concerts in Taipei |publisher=focustaiwan.tw |accessdate=28 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119075224/http://focustaiwan.tw/ShowNews/WebNews_Detail.aspx?Type=aALL&ID=201104140022 |archivedate=19 January 2012 }}</ref> He first gave a concert in [[Jakarta]], Indonesia.<ref>[http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/lifeandtimes/andrea-bocelli-gives-stirring-performance-for-gilded-crowd/441267 Andrea Bocelli Gives Stirring Performance for Gilded Crowd] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925114259/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/lifeandtimes/andrea-bocelli-gives-stirring-performance-for-gilded-crowd/441267 |date=25 September 2012 }}, [[Jakarta Globe]], 16 May 2011 article.</ref> Bocelli held two other concerts in [[Taipei]], and two concerts in [[Beijing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fashion.ce.cn/news/music/201104/14/t20110414_22364090.shtml |title=2011 Asian Tour |publisher=Fashion.ce.cn |accessdate=6 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814011002/http://fashion.ce.cn/news/music/201104/14/t20110414_22364090.shtml |archivedate=14 August 2011 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/cndy/2011-05/17/content_12521354.htm Bocelli shares the love with Beijing concerts], ''[[China Daily]]''.</ref>\n\nIn June and July, Bocelli gave two [[open-air concert]]s at historic sites, the first at [[Masada]], in [[Israel]],<ref>[http://www.opera-masada.com/en/Bocelli-Masada Andrea Bocelli at Masada] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425161536/http://www.opera-masada.com/en/Bocelli-Masada |date=25 April 2012 }} Official ''Opera Masada'' website</ref> with all proceeds dedicated to support the residents of the Israeli regions of [[Galilee]] and [[Negev]],<ref>[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4008376,00.html Andrea Bocelli to sing at Masada \u2013 Famed Italian tenor to take part in one time performance in June. All proceeds dedicated to support of Galilee, Negev residents] [[Ynetnews]]</ref> and the second at [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]]'s [[Theatre of ancient Greece|ancient Greek theatre]], in [[Sicily]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.italymag.co.uk/italy/greek-theatre-syracuse/andrea-bocelli-greek-theatre-syracuse|title=Andrea Bocelli at the Greek Theatre of Syracuse|publisher=Italymag.co.uk|date=27 June 2011|accessdate=6 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805033820/http://italymag.co.uk/italy/greek-theatre-syracuse/andrea-bocelli-greek-theatre-syracuse|archive-date=5 August 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with all proceeds donated to the ''Fiamme di Solidariet\u00e0'' (Flames of Solidarity) organization, to raise awareness of issues concerning the poorest and most marginalized in Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiammedisolidarieta.it|title=Fiamme di Solidarieta \u2013 Official Benefit concert website|publisher=Fiammedisolidarieta.it|accessdate=6 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425162236/http://www.fiammedisolidarieta.it//|archive-date=25 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBocelli gave a free concert on 15 September, on the [[Great Lawn and Turtle Pond|Great Lawn]] of [[Central Park]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|author=Scozzese Design |url=http://bocellicentralpark.com/news/detail/andrea_bocelli_gifts_new_york_city_with_a_once_in_a_lifetime_musical |title=Andrea Bocelli Gifts New York City with a Once in a Lifetime Musical |publisher=Bocellicentralpark.com |accessdate=6 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402132548/http://bocellicentralpark.com/news/detail/andrea_bocelli_gifts_new_york_city_with_a_once_in_a_lifetime_musical |archivedate=2 April 2012 }}</ref> He was accompanied by the [[New York Philharmonic]], conducted by its music director [[Alan Gilbert (conductor)|Alan Gilbert]], and the [[Westminster Choir College|Westminster Symphonic Choir]].<ref name=\"Central Park Guests\">{{cite web|author=Scozzese Design |url=http://bocellicentralpark.com/news/detail/celine_dion_tony_bennett |title=C\u00e9line Dion, Tony Bennett Among Those To Celebrate With Andrea Bocelli on Central Park's Great Lawn |publisher=Bocellicentralpark.com |accessdate=6 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402132620/http://bocellicentralpark.com/news/detail/celine_dion_tony_bennett |archivedate=2 April 2012 }}</ref> The concert was broadcast throughout the United States and Canada, by [[PBS]], and in Italy, by [[Rai 1]]. ''[[Concerto: One Night in Central Park]]'', the [[live album]] and the [[DVD-Video|DVD]] were released 15 November.\n\nOn 25 September, Bocelli led ''[[Songs of Praise]]'''s 50th anniversary celebration, alongside [[LeAnn Rimes]] and [[Katherine Jenkins]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli leads Songs of Praise 50th celebrations|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-14358591|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=31 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 October, Bocelli performed again for [[Pope Benedict XVI]] and a crowd of 8,000 people in [[Vatican City|Vatican]]'s [[Paul VI Audience Hall|Audience Hall]].<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/photos/italian-tenor-andrea-bocelli-performed-pope-benedict-xvi-photo-200156948.html Italian tenor Andrea Bocelli performs for Pope Benedict XVI]{{dead link|date=June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 November, he gave an open-air free concert at [[Pra\u00e7a Rui Barbosa]] in [[Belo Horizonte]], [[Brazil]], to an audience of between 80,000 and 150,000 people.<ref>[https://archive.today/20120906212615/http://www.portalcwb.com/fiat-35-anos-andrea-bocelli-faz-show-emocionante-para-81-mil-pessoas.html FIAT 35 ANOS: Andrea Bocelli faz show emocionante para 81 mil pessoas] (Portuguese)</ref><ref>[http://musica.uol.com.br/ultnot/2011/11/06/pela-1-vez-em-bh-andrea-bocelli-mescla-erudito-ao-pop-e-emociona-em-duetos-com-sandy.jhtm Pela 1\u00aa vez em BH, Andrea Bocelli mescla erudito ao pop e emociona em duetos com Sandy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106142546/http://musica.uol.com.br/ultnot/2011/11/06/pela-1-vez-em-bh-andrea-bocelli-mescla-erudito-ao-pop-e-emociona-em-duetos-com-sandy.jhtm |date=6 January 2016 }} (Portuguese)</ref><ref>[http://www.nhenhenhem.com/noticias/sandy-e-o-tenor-italiano-andrea-bocelli-cantam-para-mais-de-150-mil-pessoas-em-belo-horizonte-2498.html Sandy e o tenor italiano Andrea Bocelli cantam para mais de 150 mil pessoas em Belo Horizonte] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106142546/http://www.nhenhenhem.com/noticias/sandy-e-o-tenor-italiano-andrea-bocelli-cantam-para-mais-de-150-mil-pessoas-em-belo-horizonte-2498.html |date=6 January 2016 }} (Portuguese)</ref>\n\nOn 17 November, he performed at the Children in Need Rocks Manchester concert, gaining critical acclaim for receiving a standing ovation from a crowd of pop and indie music fans.\n\n===2012\u20132014: ''Rom\u00e9o et Juliette'' and ''Passione''===\nBocelli played the role of [[Romeo]] in [[Charles Gounod]]'s opera ''[[Rom\u00e9o et Juliette]]'', at the [[Teatro Carlo Felice]], for two performances in February 2012. He cancelled a third performance with [[pharyngitis]] after suffering vocal strain throughout.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pisatoday.it/cronaca/andrea-bocelli-annullato-romeo-juliette-genova-28-febbraio-2012.html | title=Salta \"Romeo et Juliette\" a Genova: Andrea Bocelli non ce la fa | work=Pisa Today | date=28 February 2012 |accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April, Bocelli gave an open-air concert at [[Yerevan]]'s [[Freedom Square, Yerevan|Liberty Square]], in [[Armenia]], dedicated to the proclamation of Yerevan as the 2012 [[World Book Capital]]; he was accompanied by the [[Armenian Philharmonic Orchestra]] conducted by Marcello Rota.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mher Margaryan |url=http://www.armradio.am/eng/news/?part=cult&id=22627 |title=Andrea Bocelli performs at Yerevan's Liberty Square |publisher=Armradio.am |date=23 April 2012 |accessdate=6 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722081608/http://www.armradio.am/eng/news/?part=cult |archivedate=22 July 2012 }}</ref> On 19 November, he performed for [[Queen Elizabeth II]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], at the [[Royal Albert Hall]], during the 100th anniversary of the [[Royal Variety Performance]].<ref>[https://archive.today/20130209204918/http://news.yahoo.com/photos/britains-queen-elizabeth-greets-tenor-andrea-bocelli-royal-photo-230411001.html Britain's Queen Elizabeth greets tenor Andrea Bocelli after the Royal Variety Performance] [[Yahoo! News]]</ref>\n\nA new studio album entitled ''[[Passione (Andrea Bocelli album)|Passione]]'', featuring duets with [[Jennifer Lopez]] and [[Nelly Furtado]], was released on 29 January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andreabocelli.com/en/#!/career-2012_1001|title=Andrea Bocelli Official Website|publisher=Andreabocelli.com|date=|accessdate=18 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019065145/http://www.andreabocelli.com/en/#!/career-2012_1001|archive-date=19 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 7 February, Bocelli was an honorary guest at the 61st Annual [[National Prayer Breakfast]], held at the [[Washington Hilton]], where he performed \"[[Ombra mai fu]]\" and [[Franz Schubert]]'s \"[[Ave Maria (Schubert)|Ave Maria]]\" in the presence of President [[Barack Obama]], First Lady [[Michelle Obama]], Vice Present [[Joe Biden]], as well as other political leaders.<ref>[http://www.music-news.com/shownews.asp?H=Andrea-Bocelli-plays-for-Barak-Obama&nItemID=62744 Andrea Bocelli plays for Barack Obama]</ref><ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/obama-urges-humility-national-prayer-breakfast-article-1.1257904 President Obama speaks about faith and 'humility' at National Prayer Breakfast] [[New York Daily News]]</ref> On 20 February, he performed at the concert in Moscow [[Kremlin]] dedicated to 20th anniversary of [[Gazprom]].\n\nOn 1 June, Bocelli performed with [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]] at the [[Arena di Verona]], celebrating the 100th anniversary of the opera festival.<ref>[http://www.geticket.it/default/biglietteria/?id=9946 Arena Di Verona 2013 \u2013 1 Giugno] (Italian)</ref>\n\n===2015\u2013present: ''Cinema'', collaborations, and ''S\u00ec''===\n[[File:Bocelli & Son.jpg|thumb|left|Bocelli and his son Matteo performing in New York at the presentation of the album ''[[S\u00ec (Andrea Bocelli album)|S\u00ec]]'' in 2018.]]\nBocelli released his fifteenth [[studio album]] ''[[Cinema (Andrea Bocelli album)|Cinema]]'' on 23 October 2015. It contains renditions of classic [[film soundtrack]]s and [[Film score|scores]], featuring duets with [[Ariana Grande]], [[Nicole Scherzinger]] and his wife Veronica Berti. The album received a nomination for [[Best Traditional Pop Vocal Album]] at the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards]]; the Spanish-language version was nominated for [[Latin Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] at the [[17th Annual Latin Grammy Awards]].\n\nOn 15 December 2017, [[Ed Sheeran]] released a collaboration with Bocelli titled \"[[Perfect Symphony]]\". The song is a duet version of Sheeran's song \"[[Perfect (Ed Sheeran song)|Perfect]]\", with many of the original English lyrics sung in Italian.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ed Sheeran and Andrea Bocelli collaborate on new Perfect remix |url=http://www.music-news.com/news/UK/109833/Ed-Sheeran-reveals-Andrea-Bocelli-as-surprise-collaborator-on-new-Perfect-remix |website=Music-News.com |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Bocelli released the single \"If Only\", his first after fourteen years.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mauro |first1=J-P |title=Andrea Bocelli's first original single in 14 years: \"If Only\" |url=https://aleteia.org/2018/06/18/andrea-bocellis-first-original-single-in-14-years-if-only/ |website=Aleteia \u2014 Catholic Spirituality, Lifestyle, World News, and Culture |accessdate=21 September 2018 |date=18 June 2018}}</ref>\nOn 20 September 2018, Bocelli released the single \"Fall On Me\" which features vocals from his son Matteo. The two performed the song on the 22 October episode of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing With the Stars]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boedeker |first1=Hal |title='Dancing With the Stars': Disney Night enlists Andrea Bocelli |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/tv/tv-guy/os-et-s2-dancing-with-the-stars-two-disney-nights-20181018-story.html |website=OrlandoSentinel.com |accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref> An English version of the song was released in October and was featured in the [[Walt Disney Pictures]] film ''[[The Nutcracker and the Four Realms]]'' as the end credit song. Both songs appear on Bocelli's album ''[[S\u00ec (Andrea Bocelli album)|S\u00ec]]'', released on 26 October 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaufman |first1=Gil |title=Andrea Bocelli 'Si' Album to Feature Duets With Dua Lipa, Ed Sheeran & More |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8476077/andrea-bocelli-si-album-duets-dua-lipa-ed-sheeran-josh-groban |website=Billboard |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Concierto Andrea Bocelli (48720880436).jpg|thumb|Andrea Bocelli concert in Gibraltar, September 2019.]]\n\nOn 12 October 2018, at the request of his close friend [[Sarah, Duchess of York]], Bocelli performed two songs at the [[wedding of Princess Eugenie and Jack Brooksbank|royal wedding]] of her daughter [[Princess Eugenie]], the [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]]/[[Charles Gounod|Gounod]] ''[[Hail Mary|Ave Maria]]'', and ''[[Panis angelicus]]'' by [[C\u00e9sar Franck]].<ref name=\"CNN-music\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/06/uk/uk-princess-eugenie-wedding-details/index.html|title=Opera, trumpets and red velvet cake for royal wedding of Britain's Princess Eugenie|publisher=CNN|first=Melissa|last=Gray|date=7 October 2018|accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Order-Service\">{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/sites/default/files/media/order_of_service_0.pdf|title=The Marriage of Her Royal Highness Princess Eugenie of York with Mr. Jack Brooksbank|publisher=The Royal Family|accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 2019, Bocelli performed a sold-out concert in [[Winter at Tantora Festival|'Winter at Tantora' festival]] running at [[Al-`Ula|Al-Ula]] for the first time in [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1445566/saudi-arabia|title=Opera star Andrea Bocelli regales music lovers at Saudi Arabia's Tantora Winter Festival|date=2019-02-01|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 July 2019 Bocelli performed at the opening ceremony of the [[2019 Summer Universiade]] in [[Naples]] with three songs includes \"Fall On Me\" with his son Matteo.\n\nOn 12 April 2020, Easter Sunday, Bocelli performed \"Music For Hope - Live From Duomo di Milano\" from an empty [[Milan Cathedral]], accompanied by cathedral organist Emanuele Vianelli.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/news/andrea-bocelli-sings-from-empty-duomo-cathedral-in-italy-for-special-live-easter-concert/ar-BB12wAln|title=Andrea Bocelli Sings From Empty Duomo Cathedral in Italy for Special Live Easter Concert|date=2020-04-12|website=MSN|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> The performance was streamed live over YouTube, where it continues to be available for replay.<ref>{{cite web |title=Andrea Bocelli: Music For Hope - Live From Duomo di Milano |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=huTUOek4LgU |website=YouTube |publisher=Andrea Bocelli |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>  About 5 million people tuned in for the livestream performance and, by April 13, 2020, over 32 million views were logged on the archived video. <ref>{{cite news |last1=Willman |first1=Chris |title=How Andrea Bocelli\u2019s Easter Live-Stream Became an Unexpected Global Blockbuster |url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/andrea-bocelli-easter-live-stream-global-phenomenon-1234579205/ |work=Variety |date=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Voice==\nItalian [[spinto]] tenor [[Franco Corelli]] praised Bocelli's voice after hearing it for the first time during a [[master class]] in 1986, in [[Turin]], and he later gave Bocelli private lessons.<ref name=\"Bocelli fans\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/classicalmusic/3668298/Andrea-Bocelli-Some-voices-have-tears-inside.html Andrea Bocelli: 'Some voices have tears inside'], [[The Daily Telegraph]], 4 October 2007 article.</ref><ref name=\"Bocelli Cieli di Toscana\"/><ref name=\"2009 Bocelli Interview\">[http://living.scotsman.com/features/Interview-Andrea-Bocelli-opera-singer.5762157.jp Interview: Andrea Bocelli, opera singer], [[The Scotsman]], 27 October 2009 article.</ref>\n\n[[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] soprano [[Ana Mar\u00eda Mart\u00ednez]], who regularly performs with Bocelli, said, \"More than anything, Andrea has something that is unique in that he brings this light that is always around him. And this purity of heart and beauty of sound just touches the listener. It can't be described.\"<ref name=\"Bocelli Cieli di Toscana\">[http://www.bluecoupe.com/classical/andreatoscana.html Andrea Bocelli's ''Cieli di Toscana'' review] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106142546/http://www.bluecoupe.com/classical/andreatoscana.html |date=6 January 2016 }}, ''bluecoupe.com'', 2001 article.</ref>\n\n[[Celine Dion]] said while introducing him during her Christmas Special for ''[[These Are Special Times]]'', in 1998, that \"if God would have a singing voice, he must sound a lot like Andrea Bocelli,\"<ref name=\"Decca\"/><ref name=\"2009 Bocelli Interview\"/> and [[David Foster]], a producer of the album, often describes Bocelli's voice as the most beautiful in the world. Similarly, [[jazz]] singer [[Al Jarreau]], who performed with Bocelli on the \"[[Night of the Proms]]\" tour in Europe in 1995, described him as \"the most beautiful voice in the world,\"<ref name=\"Bocelli - People 1997 \">[http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20123691,00.html Blind Ambition] [[People (magazine)|People Magazine]] 10 November 1997 issue.</ref> and American talk show host [[Oprah Winfrey]] commented on [[The Oprah Winfrey Show|her talk show]] that, \"when I hear Andrea sing, I burst into tears.\"<ref name=\"Bocelli fans\"/><ref name=\"Bocelli Cieli di Toscana\"/> After attending Bocelli's concert at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] in 2009, British-American actress [[Elizabeth Taylor]] said, \"My mind, my soul were transported by his beauty, his voice, his inner being. God has kissed this man and I thank God for it.\"<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/Movies/06/09/liz.taylor.outing/index.html Elizabeth Taylor makes first outing 'in months], [[CNN]], 9 June 2009 article.</ref> Taylor had been a passionate fan of Bocelli's since the beginning of his music career in the mid-1990s.<ref>[http://articles.sfgate.com/1999-01-13/entertainment/17677176_1_sling-blade-elizabeth-taylor-roddy-mcdowall Taylor Among Bocelli's Fans / Actress pushing 'The Prayer' for Oscar], [[San Francisco Chronicle|SFGate.com]], 23 January 1999 article.</ref> Other fans include [[Albert II, Prince of Monaco]], who invited the tenor to sing at [[Wedding of Albert II, Prince of Monaco, and Charlene Wittstock|his wedding]], as well as [[Sarah, Duchess of York]], and actress [[Isabella Rossellini]].<ref name=\"Bocelli - People 1997 \"/>\n\n==Recognition==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Andrea Bocelli}}\n\n===Honors===\n* Grand Officer of the [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] (''Grande Ufficiale Ordine al Merito della Repubblica Italiana'') awarded in Rome, on 4 March 2006.<ref name=\"BOC2006\"/><ref name=\"radioitalia1169\"/>\n* Grand Officer of the [[Order of Merit of Duarte, Sanchez and Mella]] by the President of the [[Dominican Republic]], [[Leonel Fern\u00e1ndez]] in 2009, for his contributions to International art and culture.<ref>[http://dominicanosHOY.com/articulos/articulo/gobierno-condecora-a-andrea-bocelli Bocelli honored by the Dominican government]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016023643/http://dominicanoshoy.com/articulos/articulo/gobierno-condecora-a-andrea-bocelli |date=16 October 2014 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/594822.html Andrea Bocelli, decorated in Dominican], [[El Universal (Mexico City)]] 2009 article</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Global Foundation for Democracy and Development \u2013 Dominican Republic|url=http://www.dominicanaonline.org/portal/espanol/cpo_noti1587.asp|title=Decoration of Italian artist Andrea Bocelli|publisher=Dominicanaonline.org|accessdate=6 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730131106/http://www.dominicanaonline.org/portal/espanol/cpo_noti1587.asp|archive-date=30 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], for his contribution to [[Theatre|live theater]], at 7000 [[Hollywood Boulevard]], in 2010.<ref name=\"Bocelli gets Star (1)\"/>\n\n===Selected awards===\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Andrea Bocelli}}\n* Winner of the 1994 Newcomers section of the [[Sanremo Music Festival]].<ref name=\"BOC1994\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 1992\u20131994|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle1992.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref>\n* [[ECHO (music award)|ECHO]] music award for \"[[ECHO (music award)#Single of the Year (National)|Best Single of the Year]]\" for \"[[Con te partir\u00f2|Time to Say Goodbye]]\", in 1997.<ref name=\"BOC1995\"/>\n* [[ECHO (music award)|ECHO Klassik]] \"Best seller of the year\" award for his album, ''[[Viaggio Italiano]]'' in 1997.<ref name=\"BOC1995\"/><ref name=\"echo1997\"/>\n* [[Bambi Award]] in 1997.<ref name=\"BOC1995\"/>\n* Two [[World Music Awards]], one in the category \"Best Italian Singer\", and one for \"Best Classical Interpretation\" in 1998.<ref name=\"BOC1998\"/><ref name=\"IHT6768960\"/>\n* [[ECHO (music award)|ECHO Klassik]], for \"Best selling classical album\" with ''[[Aria: The Opera Album]]'' in 1998.<ref name=\"BOC1998\" />\n* [[ECHO (music award)|ECHO Klassik]] for \"Bestseller of the year\" for ''[[Sacred Arias (Andrea Bocelli album)|Sacred Arias]]'' in 2000.<ref name=\"BOC2000\"/>\n* Two [[Classical BRIT Awards#2000|2000 Classical BRIT Awards]] for \"Best selling classical album\" and \"Album of the year\" for ''[[Sacred Arias (Andrea Bocelli album)|Sacred Arias]]'' in 2000.<ref name=\"BOC2000\"/>\n* [[Goldene Europa]] for classical music in 2000.<ref name=\"BOC2000\"/>\n* [[Goldene Kamera]] award in the \"Music & Entertainment\" category 2002.<ref name=\"BOC2002\"/>\n* Two [[World Music Awards]], for \"World best selling classical artist\" and for \"Best selling Italian artist\" in 2002.<ref name=\"BOC2002\"/>\n* [[Telegatto| Telegatto award]] for the soundtrack of the series ''[[Heart (novel)|Cuore]]'' in 2002.<ref name=\"BOC2002\"/>\n* [[Classical BRIT Awards#2002|2002 Classical BRIT Award]] for \"[[Brit Award for Outstanding Contribution to Music|Outstanding Contribution to Music]]\" in 2002.<ref name=\"BOC2002\"/>\n* Two [[Classical BRIT Awards#2003|2003 Classical BRIT Awards]] for \"Best selling classical album\" and \"Album of the year\" for ''[[Sentimento]]'' in 2003.<ref name=\"BBC2931456\"/>\n* Two [[2006 World Music Awards|World Music Awards]] for \"Best Italian Artist\" and \"World's Best-selling Classical Artist\" in 2006.<ref name=\"BOC2006\"/>\n* [[Telegatto| Telegatto award]] in platinum for ''Italian music in the world'' in 2008.<ref name=\"BOC2008\" />\n* [[2010 World Music Awards|World Music Awards]] for \"World's Best-selling Classical Artist\" in 2010.\n* \"America Award\" of the [[Italy\u2013USA Foundation]] in 2012.\n* \"International Artist of the Year in association with Raymond Weil\" of the [[Classic Brit Awards]] 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicbrits.co.uk/winners/|title=The Classic BRIT Awards 2012 with MasterCard \u2013 Winners|publisher=classicbrits.co.uk|date=2 October 2012|accessdate=3 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005054520/http://www.classicbrits.co.uk/winners/|archive-date=5 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* The [[Billboard Latin Music Lifetime Achievement Award]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cobo|first1=Leila|last2=Cantor-Navas|first2=Judy|title=Marc Anthony's Salsa Revival Sweeps Billboard Latin Music Awards|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/record-labels/6069821/marc-anthonys-salsa-revival-sweeps-billboard-latin-music|website=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=7 December 2017|date=24 April 2014}}</ref>\n* \"[[Art, Science and Peace Prize]]\" 2015 from PIER FRANCO MARCENARO founder of \"Man Center\" and \"School of Spirituality\" for Andrea Bocelli art which elevates the spirit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.schoolofspirituality.org/Award_2015_ENG.html|title=PIER FRANCO MARCENARO Awards 2015|date=5 December 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106142546/http://www.schoolofspirituality.org/Award_2015_ENG.html|archivedate=6 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:AndreaBocelliVeronicaBertiMar10.jpg|thumb|right|Bocelli with his wife Veronica Berti in March 2010.]]\n\nBocelli met his first wife, Enrica Cenzatti,<ref>[http://www.fanpix.net/picture-gallery/enrica-bocelli-picture-10544745.htm Wedding photo of Enrica Cenzatti and Andrea Bocelli]</ref> while singing at piano bars early in his career.<ref name=\"chronicle\"/> They were married on 27 June 1992, and had two children.<ref name=\"BOC1992\"/> Their first child, Amos, was born in February 1995. Their second son, Matteo, was born in October 1997.<ref name=\"BOC1995\"/> The couple separated in 2002.<ref name=\"BOC2002\"/> Bocelli lives with his second wife and manager, Veronica Berti. They met in 2002. In September 2011, the couple announced that Berti was expecting her first and Bocelli's third child, a daughter,<ref>{{cite news|title=Bocelli's fiancee expecting his first daughter|url=http://uk.omg.yahoo.com/news/bocellis-fiancee-expecting-first-daughter-220000639.html|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=Yahoo omg! UK|date=14 November 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203145944/http://uk.omg.yahoo.com/news/bocellis-fiancee-expecting-first-daughter-220000639.html|archivedate=3 December 2013}}</ref> in the spring.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bright|first=Spencer|title=Andrea Bocelli joins stars in celebrating 50th anniversary of Songs of Praise|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2040696/Andrea-Bocelli-joins-stars-celebrating-50th-anniversary-Songs-Of-Praise.html|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=Mail Online|date=23 September 2011}}</ref> His daughter Virginia was born 21 March 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Virginia arriva con la primavera Fiocco rosa in casa Bocelli|url=http://www.lanazione.it/massa_carrara/cronaca/2012/03/21/684764-bocelli-virginia-parto.shtml|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=[[La Nazione]]|language=Italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Magrath|first=Andrea|title=Andrea Bocelli and fianc\u00e9e Veronica welcome a baby girl named Virginia|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2121063/Andrea-Bocelli-fianc-e-Veronica-welcome-baby-girl-named-Virginia.html|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=Mail Online|date=27 March 2012}}</ref> The couple live in a spacious [[villa]] in [[Forte dei Marmi]] on the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]. Bocelli's first wife and two sons live in the couple's previous residence in the same [[comune]], in [[Versilia]].<ref name=\"Bocelli fans\"/> Bocelli married Veronica Berti on 21 March 2014 at the Sanctuary of Montenero in the coastal town of Livorno, Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/andrea-bocelli-marries-veronica-berti/|title=Andrea Bocelli Marries Veronica Berti|website=PEOPLE.com|language=EN|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April 2000, Bocelli's father, Alessandro Bocelli, died. His mother encouraged him to honor his commitments, and so he sang for [[Pope John Paul II]], in Rome, on 1 May, and immediately returned home for the funeral. At his 5 July performance, filmed for PBS as ''American Dream\u2014Andrea Bocelli's [[Statue of Liberty]] Concert'', Bocelli dedicated the encore ''Sogno'' (Dream), from his 1999 album ''[[Sogno]]'', to the memory of his father.<ref name=\"BOC2000\"/>\n\nAlthough he is blind, Bocelli has enjoyed [[horseback riding]] for much of his life.<ref>Interview segment with [[Gayle King]] for ''[[CBS This Morning]]'' (broadcast several times during 2018).</ref>\n\nA section of the beach in [[Jesolo]], on the Italian [[Adriatic coast]], was named after Bocelli on 11 August 2003.<ref name=\"BOC2003\"/>\n\nIn October 2013 Bocelli bought a second home in [[North Miami Beach]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://miami.cbslocal.com/2013/10/21/one-on-one-with-andrea-bocelli/|title=One-On-One With Andrea Bocelli|publisher=CBS News|date=21 October 2013|accessdate=23 January 2014|author=Petrillo, Lisa}}</ref>\n\nBocelli is a self-declared passionate fan of Italian football club [[Inter Milan]]. In an interview in Pisa, he claimed to a group of Inter fans that \"My passion for Inter started during my college years, when Inter was winning everything in Italy and the world. When Inter won the Champions League in 2010, I was with my friends and I was listening to the game on the radio, and everything was a little bit in advance so I was celebrating before them. That night I was also brought to tears of joy. The treble is a feeling no one in Italy will be able to equal\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrea Bocelli is a fan of Inter|url=http://www.fcinternews.it/news/bocelli-interista-dagli-anni-del-collegio-il-triplete-gioia-ineguagliabile-la-sera-di-madrid-esultai-prima-perche-266762|website=fcinternews.it}}</ref>\n\n===Teatro del Silenzio===\n{{Main|Teatro del Silenzio}}\nIn 2006, Bocelli convinced the municipality of his hometown [[Lajatico]] to build an outdoor theatre, the \"[[Teatro del Silenzio]]\".<ref name=\"BBCdoc\">{{cite video|title=Andrea Bocelli: The Story Behind the Voice|medium=television documentary|publisher=BBC|date=25 December 2007}}</ref> He serves as its honorary president and performs for one night only, every July; the rest of the year, the theatre remains silent.\n\nSince its opening in 2006, Bocelli has held 12 concerts, every July, with guests including [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[Jos\u00e9 Carreras]], [[Sarah Brightman]], [[Katherine Jenkins]], [[Zucchero]], [[Laura Pausini]], and [[Elisa (Italian singer)|Elisa]]. Bocelli's guests have also included instrumentalists [[Lang Lang]], [[Chris Botti]], and [[Kenny G]]. The 2007 concert was [[Vivere Live in Tuscany|released on CD and DVD]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vivere: Andrea Bocelli Live in Tuscany|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/gperf/episodes/vivere-andrea-bocelli-live-in-tuscany/introduction/128/|work=[[PBS]]|publisher=Educational Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Andrea Bocelli discography}}\n<!-- Do not add any album chart positions or sales records here, keep this list as short as possible. -->\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* 1994: ''[[Il Mare Calmo della Sera]]''\n* 1995: ''[[Bocelli (album)|Bocelli]]''\n* 1996\u201397: ''[[Viaggio Italiano]]''\n* 1998: ''[[Aria: The Opera Album]]''\n* 1999: ''[[Sogno]]''\n* 1999: ''[[Sacred Arias (Andrea Bocelli album)|Sacred Arias]]''\n* 2000: ''[[Verdi (album)|Verdi]]''\n* 2001: ''[[Cieli di Toscana]]''\n* 2002: ''[[Sentimento]]''\n* 2004: ''[[Andrea (Andrea Bocelli album)|Andrea]]''\n* 2006: ''[[Amore (Andrea Bocelli album)|Amore]]''\n* 2008: ''[[Incanto]]''\n* 2009: ''[[My Christmas]]''\n* 2013: ''[[Passione (Andrea Bocelli album)|Passione]]''\n* 2015: ''[[Cinema (Andrea Bocelli album)|Cinema]]''\n* 2018: ''[[S\u00ec (Andrea Bocelli album)|S\u00ec]]''\n\n===Compilation albums===\n* 1997: ''[[Romanza]]''\n* 2007: ''[[The Best of Andrea Bocelli: Vivere]]''\n* 2012: ''[[Opera (Andrea Bocelli album)|Opera]]''\n* 2016: ''[[Romanza|Romanza (20th Anniversary Edition)]]''\n\n===Live albums===\n* 2006: ''[[Under the Desert Sky]]''\n* 2008: ''[[Vivere Live in Tuscany]]''\n* 2011: ''[[Concerto, One Night in Central Park]]''\n* 2013: ''Love in Portofino''\n\n===Extended plays===\n* 2012: ''iTunes Festival: London 2012''\n\n===Digital albums===\n* 2011: ''[[Notte Illuminata]]''\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Collaborative albums===\n* 1997: ''A Hymn for the World''\n* 1998: ''A Hymn for the World 2'' (''Voices From Heaven'')\n* 2000: ''[[Requiem (Verdi)|Verdi's Requiem]]''\n* 2010: ''[[Carmen: Duets & Arias]]''\n\n===Complete opera recordings===\n* 2000: ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]''\n* 2001: ''[[Requiem (Verdi)|Requiem]]''\n* 2002: ''[[Madama Butterfly]]''\n* 2003: ''[[Tosca]]''\n* 2004: ''[[Il trovatore]]''\n* 2005: ''[[Werther]]''\n* 2006: ''[[Pagliacci]]''\n* 2007: ''[[Cavalleria rusticana]]''\n* 2008/2010: ''[[Carmen]]''\n* 2010: ''[[Andrea Ch\u00e9nier]]''\n* 2012: ''[[Rom\u00e9o et Juliette]]''\n* 2014: ''[[Manon Lescaut]]''\n* 2015: ''[[Turandot]]''\n* 2016: ''[[Aida]]''\n\n===Video albums===\n* 1998: ''[[A Night in Tuscany]]''\n* 2000: ''[[Sacred Arias: The Home Video]]''\n* 2002: ''[[Tuscan Skies (film)|Tuscan Skies]]''\n* 2006: ''[[Credo: John Paul II]]''\n* 2006: ''[[Under the Desert Sky]]''\n* 2008: ''[[Vivere Live in Tuscany]]''\n* 2008: ''[[Incanto| Incanto The Documentary]]''\n* 2009: ''[[My Christmas Special]]''\n* 2011: ''[[Concerto: One Night in Central Park]]''\n* 2013: ''Love in Portofino''<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrea Bocelli Love In Portofino|url=https://bia4music.ir/%d8%af%d8%a7%d9%86%d9%84%d9%88%d8%af-%d8%a2%d9%87%d9%86%da%af-love-in-portofino/|publisher=bia4music|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n* 2016: ''Cinema''\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Bibliography==\nBocelli is the author, and co-author, of numerous works available in Italian, English, and other languages.  Some books are available in Braille and others in large print.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=au%3Aandrea+bocelli&qt=advanced&dblist=638|title=Search results for 'au:andrea bocelli'|author=WorldCat|accessdate=11 October 2012}}</ref> The list below is limited to his English language books which are widely available.\n\n* {{cite book|title=The music of silence: a memoir by Andrea Bocelli|last=Bocelli|first=A.|origyear=1999|year=2002|publisher=HarperCollins|location=New York|oclc=54699002}} Braille edition, ISBN not available.\n* {{cite book|title=The music of silence: a memoir|last=Bocelli|first=A.|year=2002|publisher=Thorndike Press|location=Waterville, ME|isbn=9780786239009|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780786239009}} Large print edition.\n* {{cite book|title=Andrea Bocelli \u2013 Amore.|last=Bocelli|first=A.|year=2007|publisher=Hal Leonard Corp|location=Milwaukee, WI|isbn=9788850709922}}\n* {{cite book|title=The music of silence: a memoir|last=Bocelli|first=A.|year=2001|publisher=HarperEntertainment|location=New York|isbn=9780066212869|url=https://archive.org/details/musicofsilence00andr}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Music of Silence; New Edition.|last=Bocelli|first=A.|year=2011|publisher=Hal Leonard Corp|location=Milwaukee, WI|isbn=9781574671971}}\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of best-selling music artists#50 million to 74 million records|List of best-selling music artists]]\n* [[Italian estimated best-selling music artists]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{commons category|Andrea Bocelli}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.andreabocelli.com/}}\n* {{Discogs artist}}\n* {{IMDb person}}\n* {{AllMovie person}}\n\n{{Andrea Bocelli}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bocelli, Andrea}}\n[[Category:Andrea Bocelli| ]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Blind musicians]]\n[[Category:Blind classical musicians]]\n[[Category:Blind people from Italy]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism from atheism or agnosticism]]\n[[Category:Crooners]]\n[[Category:Decca Records artists]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from Italy]]\n[[Category:French-language singers of Italy]]\n[[Category:German-language singers]]\n[[Category:Italian drummers]]\n[[Category:Male drummers]]\n[[Category:Italian flautists]]\n[[Category:Italian guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Italian keyboardists]]\n[[Category:Italian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Italian male singers]]\n[[Category:Italian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Italian pianists]]\n[[Category:Italian pop singers]]\n[[Category:Italian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Italian saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Italian singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Italian operatic tenors]]\n[[Category:Italian trombonists]]\n[[Category:Italian trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Male trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Italian-language singers]]\n[[Category:Latin-language singers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Multi-instrumentalists]]\n[[Category:Opera crossover singers]]\n[[Category:Order of Merit of Duarte, S\u00e1nchez and Mella]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Pisa]]\n[[Category:Portuguese-language singers]]\n[[Category:Sanremo Music Festival winners of the newcomers section]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language singers of Italy]]\n[[Category:Torch singers]]\n[[Category:Traditional pop music singers]]\n[[Category:Universal Music Group artists]]\n[[Category:University of Pisa alumni]]\n[[Category:World Music Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Italian male pianists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Bocelli|his second album|Bocelli (album)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name               = Andrea Bocelli\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|OMRI]] [[Order of Merit of Duarte, S\u00e1nchez and Mella|OMDSM]]\n| image              = \n| caption            = Bocelli receiving a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], 2010\n| background         = solo_singer\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age |df=y|1958|9|22}}\n| birth_place        = [[Lajatico]], Italy\n| genre              = {{hlist|[[Opera music|Opera]]|[[Operatic pop]]|[[Crossover music#Classical crossover|Classical crossover]]|[[Easy listening]]|[[Latin pop]]|[[Traditional pop]]}}\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Opera singer ([[tenor]]) |Songwriter|Multi-instrumentalist|Record producer}}\n| instrument         = {{hlist|Vocals|piano|[[flute]]|[[fiddle]]}}\n}}\n'''Andrea Angel Bocelli''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|OMRI]] [[Order of Merit of Duarte, Sanchez and Mella|OMDSM]]}} ({{IPA-it|an\u02c8dre\u02d0a bo\u02c8t\u0283\u025blli}}; born 22 September 1958) is an Italian singer, songwriter, and record producer.<ref name=\"Decca\">{{cite web|title=Andrea Bocelli|url=http://www.decca.com/artists/andrea-bocelli-192|work=[[Decca Records]]|publisher=Universal Music|accessdate=10 December 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430171029/http://www.decca.com/artists/andrea-bocelli-192|archivedate=30 April 2011}}</ref><ref>http://www.classicalbrits.co.uk/artist/andrea-bocelli{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Celine Dion]] has said that \"if God would have a singing voice, he must sound a lot like Andrea Bocelli\",<ref name=\"Decca\"/><ref name=\"2009 Bocelli Interview\"/> and record producer [[David Foster]] has often described Bocelli's voice as the most beautiful in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andreabocelli.com/|title=Andrea Bocelli - Sito Ufficiale - Tour, discografia e opere}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andreabocelli.com/en/|title=En Aranjuez con tu amor - Andrea Bocelli|access-date=4 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019065145/http://www.andreabocelli.com/en/|archive-date=19 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n \nBocelli was diagnosed with [[Primary juvenile glaucoma|congenital glaucoma]] at 5 months old, and became completely blind at age 12, following a [[Association football|football]] accident. Since 1982, Bocelli has recorded 15 solo studio albums of both pop and classical music, three greatest hits albums, and nine complete operas, selling over 90 million records worldwide.<ref name=\"BillboardMastersofAlbums\">{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli to Receive Master's Degree|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5763005/andrea-bocelli-to-receive-masters-degree|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=18 October 2013|agency=AP}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli to receive Classic Brit honour|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-19508008|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=6 September 2012}}</ref> He has had success as a crossover performer, bringing classical music to the top of international pop charts.<ref name=\"Decca\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Bearn|first=Emily|title=Operation Bocelli: the making of a superstar|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/02/25/1046064026608.html|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Age]]|date=26 February 2003}}</ref><ref name=\"Obama\">{{cite news|last=Malitz|first=David|title='Christmas in Washington' sticks to the classics|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/12/12/AR2010121204423.html|accessdate=27 July 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=12 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Bocelli was named one of ''People'' magazine's [[People (magazine)#100 Most Beautiful People|50 Most Beautiful People]].<ref name=\"People1998\">{{cite journal|title=Andrea Bocelli: Singer|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20125222,00.html|journal=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=11 May 1998|volume=49|issue=18|accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> In 1999, he was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]] at the [[Grammy Award]]s. \"[[The Prayer (Celine Dion and Andrea Bocelli song)|The Prayer]]\" is his duet with [[Celine Dion]] for the animated film ''[[Quest for Camelot]]'' which won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]] and was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]].<ref name=\"Decca\"/> He captured a listing in the ''[[Guinness World Records|Guinness Book of World Records]]'' with the release of his classical album ''[[Sacred Arias (Andrea Bocelli album)|Sacred Arias]]'', as he simultaneously held the top three positions on the US Classical Albums charts.<ref name=\"Decca\"/>\n\nBocelli was made a Grand Officer of the [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] in 2006 and was honored with a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] on 2 March 2010 for his contribution to Live Theater.\n\n==Early life==\nBocelli was born to Alessandro and Edi Bocelli.<ref name=\"BlindAmbition\">{{cite news|last1=Day|first1=Carol|title=Blind Ambition|url=http://people.com/archive/blind-ambition-vol-48-no-19/|work=People|accessdate=22 July 2017|date=10 November 1997|quote=Bocelli's parents, Alessandro, 68, and Edi, 59, sold farm equipment and produced wine in tiny Lajatico, in Tuscany about 20 miles from Pisa.}}</ref> Doctors had advised the couple to abort him, as they predicted that the child would be born with a disability. It was evident at birth that Bocelli had numerous problems with his sight, and he was eventually diagnosed with [[congenital glaucoma]].<ref name=\"TelegraphGordon\"/> He has stated that his mother's decision to give birth to him and overrule the doctor's advice was the inspiration for him to oppose abortion.<ref name=\"TelegraphGordon\">{{cite news|author=Bryony Gordon|title=Andrea Bocelli: The truth about my friend \u2013 the strong-willed, kind and intelligent Silvio Berlusconi|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/classicalmusic/8884646/Andrea-Bocelli-The-truth-about-my-friend-the-strong-willed-kind-and-intelligent-Silvio-Berlusconi.html|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=14 November 2011|author-link=Bryony Gordon}}</ref>\n\nBocelli grew up on his family's farm where they sold farm machinery and made wine in the small village of [[La Sterza]], a ''[[frazione]]'' of [[Lajatico]], Tuscany, Italy, about {{convert|40|km|abbr=on}} south of [[Pisa]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Sodomka|first=Dennis|title=Wine Time: Bocelli Prosecco NV, Italy|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/things-do/applause/2013-10-08/wine-time-bocelli-prosecco-nv-italy|accessdate=14 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Augusta Chronicle]]|date=8 October 2013}}</ref> His mother and younger brother Alberto still live in the family home; his father died in 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Interview: Andrea Bocelli, opera singer|url=http://www.scotsman.com/what-s-on/music/interview-andrea-bocelli-opera-singer-1-471747|accessdate=14 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|date=23 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nBocelli showed a great passion for music as a young boy. His mother has said that music was the only thing that would comfort him. He started piano lessons at age 6 and later learned to play the flute, saxophone, trumpet, trombone, guitar, and drums.<ref name=\"BlindAmbition\"/> His nanny Oriana gave him the first record of [[Franco Corelli]], and he began to show interest in pursuing the career of a tenor.<ref name=\"Ability\">{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli \u2013 Singing to the Top|url=http://abilitymagazine.com/andrea-bocelli.html|accessdate=25 October 2013|newspaper=[[Ability (magazine)|Ability]]|date=October\u2013November 2013}}</ref> By age 7, he was able to recognize the famous voices of the time and tried to emulate the great singers.<ref name=\"Ability\"/>\n\nAt age 12, Bocelli lost his sight completely following an accident during an [[association football]] game.<ref name=\"People1998\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Hooper|first=John|title=Tenor's story acclaimed by anti-abortion campaigners|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jun/10/andrea-bocelli-abortion-italy|accessdate=28 July 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=10 June 2010}}</ref> He was hit in the eye playing goalkeeper during a match and suffered a brain hemorrhage. Doctors resorted to [[leech]]es in a last-ditch effort to save his sight, but they were unsuccessful and he remained blind.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pisa|first=Nick|title=Doctors tried to cure Andrea Bocelli's blindness with leeches|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/8100281/Doctors-tried-to-cure-Andrea-Bocellis-blindness-with-leeches.html|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=31 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nBocelli also spent time singing during his childhood.<ref name=\"chronicle\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 1958\u20131991|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle.htm|accessdate=20 January 2008}}</ref> He gave his first concert in a small village not far from where he was born.<ref name=\"Ability\"/> He won his first song competition at age 14 with \"[['O sole mio]]\" at the Margherita d'Oro in [[Viareggio]].<ref name=\"chronicle\"/> He finished secondary school in 1980, and then studied law at the [[University of Pisa]].<ref name=\"BillboardMastersofAlbums\" /><ref name=\"BlindAmbition\"/> To earn money, he performed evenings in piano bars, and it was there that he met his future wife Enrica in 1987.<ref name=\"BlindAmbition\"/> He completed law school and spent one year as a court-appointed lawyer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rogers|first=Paul|title=Andrea Bocelli at the MGM Grand|url=https://www.latimes.com/custompublishing/vegas/la-ss-andrea-bocelli-at-the-mgm-grand-20130904-dto,0,3390210.story|accessdate=21 December 2013|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=5 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===1992\u201394: Sanremo and ''Il mare calmo della sera''===\nIn 1992, Italian rock star [[Zucchero]] held auditions for tenors to make a [[Demo (music)|demo tape]] of his song \"Miserere\", to send to Italian tenor [[Luciano Pavarotti]]. After hearing Bocelli on tape, Pavarotti urged Zucchero to use Bocelli instead of him.  Zucchero eventually persuaded Pavarotti to record the song with Bocelli, and it became a hit throughout Europe. In Zucchero's European concert tour in 1993, Bocelli accompanied him to sing the duet, and he was also given solo sets in the concerts, singing \"[[Nessun dorma]]\" from [[Giacomo Puccini]]'s opera ''[[Turandot]]''.<ref name=\"BOC1992\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 1991\u20131994|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle1992.htm|accessdate=20 January 2008}}</ref> Bocelli signed with the [[Sugar Music]] label in [[Milan]] after Caterina Caselli heard Bocelli sing \"Miserere\" and \"Nessun Dorma\" at a birthday party for Zucchero.\n\nIn December, Bocelli entered the preliminary round of the [[Sanremo Music Festival]] in the category of Giovani, performing \"Miserere\". He won the preliminary competition with the highest marks ever recorded in the newcomers section. On 28 December, he debuted in the classical world in a concert at the [[Teatro Romolo Valli]] in [[Reggio Emilia]].<ref name=\"BOC1992\"/> In February 1994, he entered the main Sanremo Festival competition with \"[[Il mare calmo della sera (song)|Il mare calmo della sera]]\", and he won the newcomers section, again with a record score. Following his win, Bocelli released his debut album [[Il Mare Calmo della Sera|of the same name]] in April, and it entered the Italian Top Ten, being certified [[Music recording sales certification|platinum]] within weeks.<ref name=\"BOC1992\"/>\n\nIn May 1994, he toured with pop singer [[Gerardina Trovato]].<ref name=\"BOC1992\"/> In September, he sang at Pavarotti's annual Charity Gala concert, ''Pavarotti International'' in [[Modena]], where he sang [[Ruggiero Leoncavallo]]'s \"Mattinata\" and sang a duet with Pavarotti, Maurizio Morante's \"Notte e Piscatore\".<ref name=\"BOC1992\"/> In September, he made his opera debut as [[Macduff (Macbeth)|Macduff]] in Verdi's ''[[Macbeth (opera)|Macbeth]]'' at the Teatro Verdi in Pisa.<ref name=\"PBS8\">{{cite web|last=Ardoin|first=John|authorlink=John Ardoin|title=Bocelli and Chung|publisher=[[PBS]]|year=2007|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/gperf/shows/andreabocelli/essay3.html|accessdate=20 January 2008}}</ref> Bocelli had been an agnostic, but around 1994, partly as a result of immersing himself in the works of Russian author [[Leo Tolstoy]], he returned to the practice of the Catholic faith.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bocelli, l' inno per il Papa nasce a Lourdes|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1999/settembre/21/Bocelli_inno_per_Papa_nasce_co_0_9909214577.shtml|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=Corriere Della Sera|date=21 September 1999|language=Italian}}</ref> He performed the hymn \"[[Adeste Fideles]]\" in Rome before [[Pope John Paul II]] in [[St. Peter's Basilica]] at Christmas.<ref name=\"BOC1992\"/>\n\n===1995\u201397: ''Bocelli'' and ''Romanza''===\nAs winner of the newcomers section at the 1994 Sanremo Festival, Bocelli was invited to return the following year. He entered the main competition with \"[[Con te partir\u00f2]]\" and finished in fourth place.<ref name=\"BOC1995\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 1995\u20131997|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle1995.htm|accessdate=20 January 2008}}</ref> The song was included on his second album, ''[[Bocelli (album)|Bocelli]]'', produced by [[Mauro Malavasi]] and released in November 1995. In Belgium, \"Con te partir\u00f2\" became the best-selling single of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bocellionline.com/Bio.html |title=Andrea Bocelli Online Biography |publisher=Bocellionline.com |accessdate=6 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827214958/http://www.bocellionline.com/Bio.html |archivedate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nHis third album, ''[[Viaggio Italiano]]'', was released in Italy in 1996.<ref name=\"BOC1995\"/> He was invited to sing a duet with English soprano [[Sarah Brightman]] at the final bout of German [[boxer]] [[Henry Maske]]. Brightman had approached Bocelli after she heard him singing \"Con te partir\u00f2\" whilst she was dining in a restaurant. Changing the title lyric of the song to \"[[Con te partir\u00f2|Time to Say Goodbye]]\", they re-recorded it as a duet with members of the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] and sang it as a farewell for Maske.<ref name=\"Liebergen2008\">{{cite book|last=Liebergen|first=Patrick M.|title=Singer's Library of Arias: 15 Vocal Masterworks from the Baroque Era Through the Twenty-First Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VnS5WNme3skC&pg=PA81|accessdate=29 January 2018|date=July 2008|publisher=Alfred Music Publishing|isbn=978-0-7390-5142-9|page=81}}</ref> The single debuted atop the German charts, where it stayed for fourteen weeks. With sales nearing three million copies, and a sextuple platinum award, \"Time to Say Goodbye\" eclipsed the previous best-selling single by more than one million copies.<ref name=\"BOC1995\"/> He topped the Spanish singles chart in 1996 with a duet with [[Marta S\u00e1nchez]], \"Vivo Por Ella\", the Spanish version of \"[[Vivo per lei]]\", recorded with Giorgia for his 1997 compilation album, ''[[Romanza]]''. He also recorded a Portuguese version of the song with Brazilian singer [[Sandy (singer)|Sandy]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nThe same year, Bocelli recorded \"Je vis pour elle\", the French version of \"Vivo per lei\", as a duet with French singer [[H\u00e9l\u00e8ne S\u00e9gara]]. Released in December 1997, the song became a hit in Belgium (Wallonia) and France, where it reached No. 1 on the charts. To date, it is the best-selling single for S\u00e9gara, and the second for Bocelli after \"Time to Say Goodbye\". On 3 March, he appeared in [[Hamburg]], Germany, with Sarah Brightman to receive the ECHO music award for \"[[Echo (music award)#Single of the Year (National)|Best Single of the Year]]\".<ref name=\"BOC1995\"/>\n\nIn the summer of 1997 he gave 22 open-air concerts in Germany, and an indoor concert in [[Oberhausen]] on 31 August. In September, he performed in concert at the [[Piazza dei Cavalieri]] in Pisa for the home video ''[[A Night in Tuscany]]'' ({{lang-it|una notte nella Toscana}}) with guests [[Nuccia Focile]], Sarah Brightman and Zucchero. The concert was also Bocelli's first concert to air on PBS part of the ''In The Spotlight'' series. It also marked as Bocelli's debut to the American audiences. On 14 September, in [[Munich]], Germany, he received an [[ECHO Klassik]] Best Seller of the Year award for his album, ''Viaggio Italiano''.<ref name=\"BOC1995\" /><ref name=\"echo1997\">{{cite news|title=ECHO Klassik 1997 winners |language=German |publisher=[[Echo (music award)|ECHO]] |url=http://www.echo-deutscher-musikpreis.de/echo/echo_klassik_1997_gewinner.htm |accessdate=20 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107235337/http://www.echo-deutscher-musikpreis.de/echo/echo_klassik_1997_gewinner.htm |archivedate=7 January 2009 }}</ref>\n\nBack in Italy in Bologna on 27 September, he sang at the [[International Eucharistic Congress]]. On 19 October, he sang at the [[TeleFood]] benefit concert held in the [[Vatican City]] to raise awareness about world hunger. On 25 October, he received a [[Bambi Award]] in the Klassik category in Cologne, Germany.<ref name=\"BOC1995\" />\n\n===1998\u201399: ''Aria: The Opera Album'', ''Sogno'' and ''Sacred Arias''===\nBocelli made his debut in a major operatic role in 1998 when he played Rodolfo in a production of ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' at the Teatro Comunale in [[Cagliari]] from 18 to 25 February.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Berger|first1=Kevin|title=Beyond the criticism: Deconstructing Andrea Bocelli's voice|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2010/12/beyond-the-criticisms-deconstructing-andrea-bocellis-voice.html|accessdate=29 January 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=8 December 2010}}</ref> His fifth album ''[[Aria: The Opera Album]]'' was released in March.<ref name=\"BOC1998\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 1998|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle1998.htm|accessdate=20 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 April, Bocelli made his United States debut with a concert at the [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts]] in Washington, D.C., followed the next day by a reception at the [[White House]] with then US President [[Bill Clinton]].<ref name=\"BOC1998\"/> On 5 May, he appeared in [[Monte Carlo]], winning two [[World Music Awards]], one in the category \"Best Italian Singer\", and one for \"Best Classical Interpretation\".<ref name=\"BOC1998\"/><ref name=\"IHT6768960\">\n{{cite news|title=People|work=[[International Herald Tribune]]|date=8 May 1998|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-6768960.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103051442/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-6768960.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 November 2012|accessdate=20 January 2008}}</ref> He was also named one of [[People Magazine's 50 Most Beautiful People|''People'' magazine's 50 Most Beautiful People]] of 1998.<ref name=\"People1998\"/>\n\nFrom June to August, he toured North and South America. In September, he received his second Echo Klassik award, this time for Best Selling Classical Album with ''Aria: The Opera Album''.<ref name=\"BOC1998\" /> On Thanksgiving Eve, Bocelli was a guest on [[C\u00e9line Dion]]'s television special ''These Are Special Times'' in which he joined Dion to sing \"[[The Prayer (Celine Dion and Andrea Bocelli song)|The Prayer]]\" and he also sang \"[[Ave Maria (Vavilov)|Ave Maria]]\" solo. The duet was included on Dion's album ''[[These Are Special Times]]'' (1998) and was re-issued with the DVD of the TV special in 2007. The song also appeared on the ''[[Quest for Camelot]]'' soundtrack in 1998 and on Bocelli's album, ''[[Sogno]]'', the following year.\n\nIn the New Year, he performed two concerts at the [[Bellagio (resort)|Bellagio]] hotel in Las Vegas. At the [[56th Golden Globe Awards]] held on 24 January, \"The Prayer\" won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song#1990s|Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]] from the film ''Quest for Camelot''.<ref name=\"BOC1999\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 1999|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle1999.htm|accessdate=20 January 2008}}</ref> At the [[41st Grammy Awards]] ceremony on 24 February, Bocelli was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist#1990s|Best New Artist]], which was won by [[Lauryn Hill]].<ref name=\"Decca\"/> Bocelli and Dion sang \"The Prayer\" at the ceremony.<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/> The song was also nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] and performed by Bocelli and Dion at the ceremony held at the [[Los Angeles Music Center]] on 21 March.<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/>\n\nFrom 11 to 24 April, he toured the West Coast of North America, from [[San Diego]] to [[Vancouver]], with a final performance at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] in Los Angeles. Actress [[Elizabeth Taylor]] stood by his side on the stage during the encore, while he sang \"The Prayer\".<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/> At the invitation of [[Steven Spielberg]], Bocelli sang in Los Angeles on 15 May before Bill Clinton at an event on behalf of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]. At the end of May, he toured Portugal and Spain and sang with Portuguese [[Fado]] singer [[Dulce Pontes]]. On 27 June, he took part in the [[Michael Jackson]] benefit concert for suffering children in Munich's [[Olympic Stadium (Munich)|Olympic Stadium]].<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/>\n\nFrom 10 July to 27 August, he appeared in a guest role for seven performances of ''[[The Merry Widow]]'' at the [[Verona Arena]].<ref name=\"PBS8\"/><ref name=\"BOC1999\"/> As the \"Tenor Conte Andrea\" he performed three arias: \"[[La donna \u00e8 mobile]]\" from Verdi's ''[[Rigoletto]]''; \"Tu, che m' hai preso il cuor\" from [[Franz Leh\u00e1r]]'s ''[[Das Land Des Laechelns]]'' and \"Libiamo ne' lieti calici\" from Verdi's ''La traviata''.<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/> On 10 September, together with soprano [[Daniela Dess\u00ec]] and two Polish singers, he performed at the Great Theatre of [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]] in Poland. From 7 October to 19 November, he made his United States operatic debut in [[Jules Massenet]]'s ''[[Werther]]'' at the [[Detroit Opera House]] with the Michigan Opera Theater.<ref name=\"PBS8\"/>\n\nHe also performed at [[Rodeo Drive]] in Hollywood and gave further concerts in Detroit, [[Cleveland]] and Chicago, and made an appearance on Jay Leno's first installment of ''[[The Tonight Show]]''. Then [[Mayor of New York City]] [[Rudy Giuliani]] gave him the Crystal Apple award. His seventh album ''[[Sacred Arias (Andrea Bocelli album)|Sacred Arias]]'', which contains exclusively [[sacred music]], was released worldwide on 8 November, and two weeks later reached number one on the US [[Billboard charts|Classic Billboard charts]] \u2013 making Bocelli the first vocalist to hold all top three places on the chart, with ''Aria, the opera album'' in second place, and ''Viaggio Italiano'' in third place. The album also included the hymn of the Holy Year 2000 which was chosen as the official version by the Vatican in October.<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/> To promote ''Sacred Arias'', Bocelli recorded [[Sacred Arias: The Home Video|his second PBS concert]] at the Roman church of [[Santa Maria sopra Minerva]], in Rome, in 1999, singing most of the songs from the album. The special was nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Classical Music-Dance Program during the [[52nd Primetime Emmy Awards]].\n\nIn Italy, Bocelli sang in [[Florence]] at a meeting of the centre-left Heads of State<!--This is cryptic ... what event was this? The linking was deceptive, anyway.-->. Invited by [[Queen Elizabeth II]], he performed at the annual [[Royal Variety Performance]] in Birmingham, UK, on 29 November. On 30 November, his book ''La musica del silenzio'', an autobiographical novel, was released in Italy,<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/> and in 2017 it was turned into a movie as ''[[The Music of Silence]]'', directed by [[Michael Radford]]. From 12 to 21 December, he performed six concerts in [[Barcelona]], [[Strasbourg]], Lisbon, [[Zagreb]], [[Budapest]] and [[Messina]], some of which were broadcast on local television. He also performed on German television; ''[[Wetten, dass..?]]'' on 11 December and the [[Jos\u00e9 Carreras]] Gala in [[Leipzig]] on 17 December. On 31 December, he finished a marathon twenty-four concerts in thirty days, with a concert at the [[Nassau Veterans Memorial Coliseum]] in New York, welcoming in the new millennium.<ref name=\"BOC1999\"/>\n\n===2000\u201301: ''Verdi'' and ''Cieli di Toscana''===\nAt the [[42nd Grammy Awards]], Bocelli was nominated twice. \"The Prayer\" was nominated for [[Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals]] and for [[Best Male Pop Vocal Performance]]. Bocelli performed it with Dion at the ceremony. His \"World Tour 2000\" started on 31 March. In May, his ''Sacred Arias'' album was voted album of the year by listeners of the [[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]] radio station in the UK. His world tour continued from 12 May to 14 May with four concerts in Japan and South Korea. At the end of the [[UEFA Euro 2000|UEFA European Football Championship]], he performed with [[Valery Gergiev]] and [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]] at a concert on the [[Meuse (river)|River Maas]] in [[Rotterdam]]. On 6 July, he performed at the [[Statue of Liberty]] in New York City for his third PBS special ''American Dream: Andrea Bocelli's Statue of Liberty Concert''. The concert was a dedication to his father, who died in the beginning of 2000. He was accompanied by the New Jersey Symphony Orchestra under the direction of Maestro [[Steven Mercurio]] with special guest Soprano Ana Maria Martinez and a surprise appearance by Sarah Brightman to sing with Bocelli on \"Time to Say Goodbye.\" For the final encore, he dedicated \"Sogno\" to his late Father. On 17 August, he performed in Giuseppe Verdi's ''[[Requiem (Verdi)|Messa da Requiem]]'' at the Verona Arena in Rome.\n\nHis seventh album, ''[[Verdi (album)|Verdi]]'', was released on 11 September. In September, he performed three concerts in Australia. He received another Echo Klassik award for \"Bestseller of the year\" for ''[[Sacred Arias (Andrea Bocelli album)|Sacred Arias]]''. In November, his first complete opera recording, ''La Boh\u00e8me'', was released. In December, he received another award in Germany, the [[Goldene Europa]] for classical music.<ref name=\"BOC2000\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 2000|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle2000.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2001, Bocelli portrayed the main character in [[Pietro Mascagni|Mascagni]]'s opera ''[[L'amico Fritz]]'' at the Teatro Filarmonico in [[Verona]] and again performed the tenor part in Verdi's ''Requiem''. On 19 March, the ''Requiem'' album was released with Bocelli as tenor. From 22 March to 6 April, he toured North America accompanied by [[Cecilia Gasdia]] and the [[Hartford Symphony Orchestra]]. On 17 June, he performed at the re-opening of the [[Leaning Tower of Pisa]]. In July, he performed two concerts in [[Dublin]] with [[Ana Mar\u00eda Mart\u00ednez]] and the [[New Symphony Orchestra]]. At the [[Scuola Grande di San Rocco]] in Venice on 4 October, he presented his new album ''Cieli di Toscana'' and was recognised for having sold more than 40 million albums worldwide. In October, he opened the celebrations of the 200th anniversary of the birth of [[Sicilian people|Sicilian]] opera composer [[Vincenzo Bellini]] in [[Catania]]. On 28 October, he sang Franz Schubert's ''[[Ellens dritter Gesang]]'' (also known as \"Ave Maria\", Latin for \"Hail Mary\") as a representative of the [[Roman Catholic]] faith, during a memorial concert at [[Ground Zero]] in New York City for the victims of the [[September 11 attacks]] there. In November, he received the Platinum Europe Award for one million sales of the album ''Cieli di Toscana'', and at the [[Italian Music Awards]] he was given a special award from the [[Federation of the Italian Music Industry]] for his merits as an \"Ambassador of Italian music in the world\". He performed seven more concerts in the US accompanied by Ana Mar\u00eda Mart\u00ednez, and on 23 December, he sang the [[Italian national anthem]] as well as works of Bellini and Verdi at the traditional Christmas concert in the [[Italian Senate]], which was broadcast live on television for the first time.<ref name=\"BOC2001\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 2001|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle2001.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref>\n\n===2002\u201305: ''Sentimento'' and ''Andrea''===\n[[File:Tony Celine Bocelli.jpg|thumb|left|Bocelli with [[Celine Dion]] and [[Tony Renis]] in 2002.]]\n\nIn Berlin on 5 February, he received a [[Goldene Kamera]] award in the \"Music & Entertainment\" category. On 6 March, he received two World Music Awards in Monte Carlo: \"World best selling classical artist\" and \"Best selling Italian artist\". On 11 March, he gave a concert for peace at the [[St Mark's Basilica|Basilica di San Marco a Venezia]] in Venice, accompanied by the orchestra of the [[La Fenice|Teatro La Fenice]] and conducted by [[Lorin Maazel]]. On 15 March, he took part in the opening of [[Walt Disney Studios Park]] in [[Marne-la-Vall\u00e9e]] France. On 7 May, Bocelli and Tony Renis received a [[Telegatto]] Italian Television award for the soundtrack of the series ''[[Heart (novel)|Cuore]]''. On 23 May he received the [[Classical BRIT Awards#2002|2002 Classical BRIT Award]] for \"Outstanding Contribution to Music\".<ref name=\"BBC2005196\">{{cite news|title=Salford singer wins again|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2005196.stm|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=23 May 2002}}</ref> On 27 May, he performed at the [[Villa Madama]] in Rome in front of US president [[George W. Bush]] and Italian president [[Silvio Berlusconi]]. On 28 May, he took part in \"Pavarotti & Friends\" charity concert in [[Modena]] in aid of [[Angola]]. In June he again toured the US, then on 26 July and 3 August, he portrayed [[Lieutenant Pinkerton|Lieutenant B.F. Pinkerton]] in ''[[Madama Butterfly]]'' at the 48th Puccini Festival in Torre del Lago. On 14 October, he and Lorin Maazel presented his new album ''[[Sentimento]]'' to a worldwide audience. Further presentations took place in Milan and New York, and the album was released on 4 November, selling over two million copies in 40 days. On 24 October, he started his ''Sentimento'' tour in [[Z\u00fcrich]] which took in large arenas in several European and North American cities.<ref name=\"BOC2002\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 2002|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle2002.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2003, Bocelli performed ''Madama Butterfly'' in an exclusive Monte Carlo concert, which was attended by [[Caroline, Princess of Hanover]]. In March for the first time he appeared as a producer, at the Sanremo Festival, where the young artists Allunati and Jacqueline Ferry sang for his new record label, Clacksong.<ref name=\"BOC2003\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 2003|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle2003.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref> In May his second complete opera, ''[[Tosca]]'', was released.<ref>Giacomo Puccini, ''Tosca.'' Fiorenza Cedolins, Andrea Bocelli, Carlo Guelfi and others, Florence Maggio Musicale Orchestra, Zubin Mehta, Decca 473 710-2.</ref> It did not attract unanimous praise, though. [[Andreas Dorschel]] notices \"monochrome timbre\" and \"little dynamic variability\" in Bocelli's performance: \"Whatever is suffered by Cavaradossi \u2212 torture for instance or the prospect of execution \u2212: Bocelli does not seem to register it, but goes on in the musical equivalent of Stoic indifference.\"<ref>Andreas Dorschel, 'The World's Favourite Tenor', ''[[Lettre International]]'' no. 120 (Spring 2018), pp. 136\u2212137, p. 136.</ref> At a private benefit gala for the [[Royal National Institute of Blind People]], Bocelli sang in front of the [[British Royal Family]].<ref name=\"BOC2003\"/> A day later he received two awards for ''Sentimento'' at the [[Classical BRIT Awards#2003|2003 Classical BRIT Award]] held at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in London \u2013 \"Best selling classical album\" and \"Album of the year\".<ref name=\"BBC2931456\">{{cite news|title=Bocelli tops Classical Brits|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2931456.stm|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=23 May 2003}}</ref> On 24 May, he performed in a benefit concert for the [[Arpa Foundation for Film, Music and Art]] in the [[Piazza del Campo]] in [[Siena]], with sopranos [[Maria Luigia Borsi]] and Lucia Dessanti, [[baritone]] Soo Kyung Ahn, and violinist Ruth Rogers, accompanied by Marcello Rota and the Orchestra Citt\u00e0 di Pisa. Three days later he was again invited to perform at \"Pavarotti & Friends\" in Modena and sang a medley of [[Music of Naples|Neapolitan songs]] together with Pavarotti. In June, he continued his ''Sentimento'' tour in [[Athens]] and [[Cyprus]]. In September, he took part in a concert for the Justice ministers and Interior ministers of the European Union at the [[Parco della Musica]] in Rome. He then resumed his tour, accompanied by [[Maria Luigia Borsi]], Ruth Rogers and Marcello Rota.<ref name=\"BOC2003\"/>\n\nBocelli won the \"Favourite Specialist Performer\"  award at the UK National Music Awards in October 2003.<ref name=\"BBC3216767\">{{cite news|title=Pop Idols dominate music awards|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3216767.stm|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=27 October 2003}}</ref> In November he once again toured in the United States, this time accompanied by Ana Maria Martinez, [[Kallen Esperian]] and [[Steven Mercurio]]. In December he gave his first concert in China and at the end of the month, sang Gounod's ''Ave Maria'' at Pavarotti's wedding in Modena.<ref name=\"BOC2003\"/>\n\nIn Bologna in January, he performed as [[Werther#Principal characters|Werther]] in four performances of the opera of the same name. In April and May, he toured Asia again, visiting Manila, Hong Kong and Singapore. In May, he took part in a concert at [[Circo Massimo]] in Rome organised by [[Quincy Jones]] to launch the \"[[Quincy Jones#Social activism|We are the Future]]\" project. In June, his third complete opera ''[[Il trovatore]]'' was released. In July, he played the part of Mario Cavaradossi in ''Tosca'' at the 50th Puccini Festival in Torre del Lago, and he took part in the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) global campaign for the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] in Athens.<ref name=\"BOC2004\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 2004|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle2004.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn September, he performed his \"Once in a Lifetime\" tour in Australia with concerts in Sydney and Melbourne and one concert in Christchurch, New Zealand, where he was joined on stage by New Zealand soprano [[Hayley Westenra]].<ref name=\"BOC2004_3\">{{cite web|title=Once in a Lifetime Tour|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert/2004_3.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 October, he performed at the [[Great Hall of the People|People Conference Hall]] in Beijing, China, and on 17 October at the Great Hall in Shanghai.<ref name=\"BOC2004_4\">{{cite web|title=Asia Tour|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert/2004_4.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nDuring early 2005, Bocelli was on tour including performances in [[Madeira]], Hungary, Norway, US, UK, Italy and Germany.<ref name=\"BOC2005\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 2005|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle2005.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref> He also appeared in ''[[Sesame Street]]'' singing \"Time to Say Goodnight\" a parody of \"Time to Say Goodbye\" as a lullaby to [[Elmo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sesame Street Parody Descriptions|url=http://www.sesameworkshop.org/aboutus/pressroom/presskits/season36/parody.php|accessdate=15 December 2013|newspaper=[[Sesame Workshop]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080119132344/http://www.sesameworkshop.org/aboutus/pressroom/presskits/season36/parody.php|archivedate=19 January 2008}}</ref> On 21 March, he performed at the ''Music for Asia'' benefit concert in Rome, televised on [[Italia 1]], in aid of the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake]] appeal.<ref name=\"BOC2005_1\">{{cite web|title=Asia Tour|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live2005_1.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn June, he performed at the Deutsche Opera in Berlin. On 2 July, he performed at the Paris concert as part of the [[Live 8]] event. Also during the second part of the year, he performed in Croatia, [[Serbia]], Italy, the US, [[Dubai]], Switzerland and finally in Scandinavia.<ref name=\"BOC2005\"/> On 28 August, he performed at the [[Faenol Festival]] held in [[Vaynol]], Wales and organised by Welsh [[bass-baritone]] [[Bryn Terfel]].<ref name=\"BOC2005_1\"/> In December, his first contemporary music concert took place at a [[Lake Las Vegas]] village resort in [[Nevada]], US, which was recorded for [[PBS]] and released as the ''[[Under the Desert Sky]]'' DVD. He also took part in the Royal Christmas Show, which took place in several cities in the US in December. The album ''Werther'' was released in December.\n\n===2006\u201307: ''Amore'' and ''Vivere, Greatest hits''===\n[[File:Bocelli.jpg|thumb|Bocelli rehearsing for his ''[[Under the Desert Sky]]'' concert in [[Lake Las Vegas]], 2006.]]\n\nOn 18 February, he sang at the [[Toyota Center]] in [[Houston]] during the [[National Basketball Association]]'s (NBA) 2006 [[NBA All-Star Weekend|All-Star Weekend]], and broadcast live on the [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] Cable television network.<ref name=\"NBA060215\">{{cite news|title=John Legend and Carrie Underwood Set for All-Star Halftime Show|publisher=[[National Basketball Association|NBA]]|year=2006|url=http://www.nba.com/allstar2006/Legend_Underwood_060215.html|accessdate=20 January 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080103090303/http://www.nba.com/allstar2006/Legend_Underwood_060215.html|archivedate=3 January 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February, Bocelli sang \"Because We Believe\" from his ''Amore'' album in the Carnevale section of the [[2006 Winter Olympics closing ceremony|closing ceremony of the Torino Olympics]].<ref name=\"BOC2006\">{{cite web|title=Bocelli 2006 Chronicle|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle2006.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref> He also began another tour with a concert at the Piazza di Castello in Turin.<ref name=\"BOC2006_1\">{{cite web|title=2006 tour (1)|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2006_1.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref> In March, he was honoured by the Italian state with a [[Italian orders of merit|Grande Ufficiale Italian Order of Merit]] (Grand Officer of the Italian Republic), given to him by then President of the Italian Republic, [[Carlo Azeglio Ciampi]]. The award was presented to him at the Sanremo Festival where he performed a duet with American singer [[Christina Aguilera]] on 4 March.<ref name=\"BOC2006\"/><ref name=\"radioitalia1169\">{{cite news|title=Pausini, Bocelli e Ramazotti: Onorificenze e serata finale del festival |language=Italian |publisher=[[Radio Italia Solo Musica Italiana]] |date=22 February 2006 |url=http://www.radioitalia.dit/web/news/news.php?idNews=1169 |accessdate=21 January 2008 }}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nFrom 31 March to 2 April, he took part in the Maggio Musicale in Florence where he sang the ''Canto di pace (Canto of peace)'' by [[Marco Tutino]]<ref name=\"cultura3743\">{{cite news|title=FIRENZE \u2013 Bocelli e il canto di Pace nato alle Muse|language=Italian|publisher=cultura.marche.it|date=March 2006|url=http://www.cultura.marche.it/CMDirector.aspx?idN=3743|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref> and the tenor part from [[Gioachino Rossini]]'s ''[[Messa di Gloria (Rossini)|Messa di Gloria]]'' and in Naples where he took part in Rossini's [[Petite messe solennelle]].<ref name=\"BOC2006\"/><ref name=\"BOC2006_1\"/>\n\nIn April 2006, he featured as a guest coach on ''[[American Idol (season 5)|American Idol]]'' helping the finalists sing the week's themed songs, \"Greatest Love Songs.\" He also performed on that week's results show.<ref name=\"BG060611\">{{cite news|last=Dyer |first=Richard |title=From 'American Idol' to Boston divo |publisher=[[J. C. Penney]] |date=11 June 2006 |url=http://www.boston.com.news/globe/living/articles/2006/06/11/from_american_idol_to_boston_divo/?page=1 |accessdate=22 January 2008 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> American Idol runner-up [[Katharine McPhee]] performed at three of Bocelli's concerts in California from 9 to 11 June singing duets of ''Somos Novios'' and ''The Prayer'' with Bocelli. They also performed on ''[[J. C. Penney]] Jam: The Concert for America's Kids''<ref name=\"JCP852901\">{{cite news|title=Dr. Phil and Music Superstars Join Forces for ''JCPENNEY JAM...THE CONCERT FOR AMERICA'S KIDS'' Mega Event to Air on CBS-TV During Back to School |publisher=[[J. C. Penney]] |date=March 2006 |url=http://www.ir.jcpenney.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=70528&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=852901&highlight |accessdate=21 January 2008 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and recorded duet versions of ''Somos Novios'' for the resulting album, and also ''[[Can't Help Falling in Love]]'' on the CD of the [[Under the Desert Sky]] DVD.\n\nIn June, he sang the Italian duet version of \"[[Because We Believe]]\", \"Ama, credi e vai\", with [[Gianna Nannini]] at the \"gro\u00dfen Fan Party\" at the opening of the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], in Berlin in front of billions of worldwide television viewers.\n\nOn 1 July 2007, Bocelli performed \"[[The Music of the Night]]\" from [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]]'s ''[[The Phantom of the Opera (1986 musical)|The Phantom of the Opera]]'', in a special musicals medley during the [[Concert for Diana]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] in London, England.<ref name=\"BBC070701\">{{cite news|title=Concert for Diana Timeline: What's happened minute by minute|publisher=[[BBC Entertainment]]|date=1 July 2007|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/1/concertfordiana/timeline/|accessdate=22 January 2008}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Bocelli returned to his home town for a concert at the newly created [[Teatro del Silenzio]] in [[Lajatico]] on 5 July 2007, with guest appearance by [[Kenny G]], [[Heather Headley]], [[Lang Lang]], [[Elisa (Italian singer)|Elisa]], [[Sarah Brightman]] and [[Laura Pausini]]. The concert was later released as ''[[Vivere Live in Tuscany]]''. In September, he debuted at the [[Avery Fisher Hall]], in New York, with four concerts. October saw the release of the opera album of [[Ruggiero Leoncavallo]]'s ''[[Pagliacci]]'' with Bocelli singing the role of [[Pagliacci#Roles|Canio]]. In November, he won the \"Best Italian Artist\" and \"World's Best-selling Classical Artist\" awards at the [[World Music Awards#2006 show|World Music Awards]]. In December, he finished his 2006 tour with more concerts in North America and Europe.<ref name=\"BOC2006\"/>\n\nBocelli and Sarah Brightman's duet version of \"Con te partir\u00f2\" was used in the 2007 film ''[[Blades of Glory]]'', as an ice skating song. [[K-1]] [[mixed martial arts]] fighter [[Yoshihiro Akiyama]] started using \"Con te partir\u00f2\" as his ring entrance music. On 8 September, Bocelli sang an arrangement of Mozart's ''[[Ave verum corpus (Mozart)|Ave verum corpus]]'' at the funeral of Luciano Pavarotti in Modena, Italy.\n\nOn 21 October 2007, he sang \"Con te partir\u00f2\" on the UK television series ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'' results show, and on 30 October, he sang \"The Prayer\" during an ITV Special ''An Audience with C\u00e9line Dion''. The show was broadcast on 23 December. Alongside fellow Italian singer [[Laura Pausini]], he sang ''Vive Ya'' during the 2007 Latin Grammy Awards. The song, originally released in 1997 as a duet in Italian between Bocelli and Italian singer-songwriter Trovatto on Bocelli's ''[[Romanza]]'', was also released in English on his 2007 album, ''[[The Best of Andrea Bocelli: Vivere]]'', as ''Dare to Live''. The album, ''[[The Best of Andrea Bocelli: Vivere|Vivere]]'', sold over 3 million copies.\n\n===2008: ''Incanto'' and ''Carmen''===\nOn 20 January 2008, Bocelli received the Italian TV award [[Telegatto]] in platinum for ''Italian music in the world'', in Rome. He sang \"La voce del silenzio\" \u2013 \"The voice of silence\" \u2013 and \"Dare to Live\" during the ceremony.<ref name=\"BOC2008\">{{cite news|title=live2008|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live2008_1.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:VeronicaBerti.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Bocelli with his then fianc\u00e9e Veronica Berti in Tokyo, Japan, during his ''2008 Asian Tour''.]]\n\nTo promote the album, he performed \"[[Canto della Terra]]\" at ''[[The Alan Titchmarsh Show]]'' on the BBC in London on 1 February; was interviewed by [[Fabio Fazio]] on the Italian talk show ''[[Che tempo che fa]]'' on [[RAI 3]] in Italy; and performed \"Canto della terra\", \"A te\" and \"Besame mucho\" from the album, as well as \"[[My Way]]\" on 2 February; and made an appearance on ''[[The South Bank Show]]'' in London, where he sang the French [[aria]] \"Pour mon \u00e2me\" on 3 February. Then on 10 February, he performed \"The Prayer\" at the [[50th Grammy Awards]], held in Los Angeles, with [[Josh Groban]] in a tribute to [[Luciano Pavarotti]], and sang \"[[Vivere (Dare to Live)|Dare to Live]]\" with [[Heather Headley]] the following day on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]''.<ref name=\"BOC2008\" />\n\nIn April, he toured in Asia with performances in Tokyo, [[Taichung]], and Seoul.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert1\">\n{{cite news|title=live concert2008/1|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2008_1.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 May 2008, he sang at [[Steel Ar\u00e9na]] in [[Ko\u0161ice]], Slovakia, in front of 8,000 people.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert2\">\n{{cite news|title=live concert2008/2|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2008_2.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> Then 13 May he sang at the ''\"Teatro delle Muse\"'' in [[Ancona]], Italy, for a charity concert for \"Francesca Rava \u2013 N.P.H. Italia Onlus\", a foundation that helps poor and disabled children around the world.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert2\" />\n\nOn 23 May 2008, he sang ''The Prayer'' with [[Katharine McPhee]] in a Las Vegas tribute concert for Canadian producer and songwriter [[David Foster]]. Bocelli later praised Filipina teen-aged singer [[Charice]], whom he had first heard perform at that concert.<ref>{{cite web|author=di Paolo Giordano|url=http://www.ilgiornale.it/a.pic1?ID=264800|title=Bocelli: \"Verdi, il mio canto patriottico nell'Italia della riconciliazione\"|publisher=Ilgiornale.it|date=28 May 2008|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.charicemania.com/charicemaniacom/2008/06/in-realt-il-mon.html Charicemania \u2013 Charice Pempengco Blog : Andrea Bocelli in a Possible Duet With Charice?<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080918015918/http://www.charicemania.com/charicemaniacom/2008/06/in-realt-il-mon.html |date=18 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 2 June 2008, he performed at the [[Piazza del Duomo, Milan]] in front of 80,000 people during a concert celebrating the anniversary of the Republic of Italy's formation.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert2\" />\n\nFrom 17 to 28 June, Bocelli played the role of Don Jos\u00e9 on stage, opposite Hungarian [[mezzo-soprano]] [[Ildik\u00f3 Koml\u00f3si]] as [[Carmen]], in [[Georges Bizet]]'s opera at the [[Teatro dell'Opera di Roma]], in Rome, for four nights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moltoitaly.com/2008/05/andrea-bocelli-in-carmen-at-teatro.html|title=Andrea Bocelli in Carmen at the Teatro dell'Opera|publisher=Molto Italy|date=|accessdate=28 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828065809/http://www.moltoitaly.com/2008/05/andrea-bocelli-in-carmen-at-teatro.html|archive-date=28 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[https://archive.today/20120709231831/http://en.operaroma.it/stagione/cartellone_2008/carmen The 2008 production of ''Carmen'' at the Teatro dell'Opera di Roma], Official [[Teatro dell'Opera di Roma]] website.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/opera2008.htm|title=Live \u2013 Opera|publisher=www.bocelli.de|date=|accessdate=28 July 2013}}</ref> Bocelli released the complete opera recording of ''Carmen'' in Italy in the same year, which he recorded in 2005. [[Myung-whun Chung]] conducted the [[Orchestre Philharmonique de Radio France]] and the Ch\u0153ur de Radio France for the recording, and Welsh [[Bass-baritone]] [[Bryn Terfel]], was part of the Ensemble.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicalsource.com/db_control/db_cd_review.php?id=8390|title=Carmen \u2013 Marina Domashenko, Andrea Bocelli & Bryn Terfel|publisher=Classicalsource.com|date=24 October 2005|accessdate=28 July 2013}}</ref> The recording was not released internationally, until March 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mightyape.co.nz/product/Bizet-Carmen/4443347|title=Bizet: ''Carmen'' \u2013 Andrea Bocelli, Bryn Terfel|publisher=Mightyape.co.nz|date=8 March 2010|accessdate=28 July 2013}}</ref> ''[[Carmen: Duets & Arias]]'', a single-disc collection of some of the arias and duets of the recording, was also released in 2010.<ref name=\"Carmen: Duets & Arias on iclassics\">[http://www.iclassics.com/artist/releases/release.aspx?pid=64137&aid=108 ''Carmen: Duets & Arias'' on iclassics]{{dead link|date=June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 July, Bocelli held his third concert at the Teatro del Silenzio in [[Lajatico]], his hometown. The concert was a tribute to the [[cinema of Italy]]. Its performers included Italian composer and musician [[Nicola Piovani]], Italian ballet dancer [[Roberto Bolle]], Israeli singer [[Achinoam Nini|Noa]], and Charice.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert3\">\n{{cite news|title=live concert2008/3|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2008_3.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> Then on 31 July, he performed at a concert in [[Vingis Park]] in [[Vilnius]], [[Lithuania]], in front of more than 18,000 people.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert4\">\n{{cite news|title=live concert2008/4|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2008_4.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> Australian singer [[Tina Arena]] performed two duets with Bocelli \u2013 \"Canto Della Terra\" and \"[[The Prayer (Celine Dion and Andrea Bocelli song)|The Prayer]]\" \u2013 at the closing stages of the concert.<ref name=\"August 2008\">\n{{cite web|title=Impromptu onstage appearance|publisher=tinaarena.com|url=http://tinaarena.com/index.php?module=news&section=newsdetail&secid=86&lang=en|accessdate=24 December 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203033918/http://tinaarena.com/index.php?module=news&section=newsdetail&secid=86&lang=en|archivedate=3 February 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 August 2008, he held a benefit concert at [[Medjugorje]], [[Bosnia Herzegovina]], and was accompanied by the [[Czech National Symphony Orchestra]].<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert4\" /> Then, during the rest of August, he was on tour in Australia and New Zealand for the third time.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert4\" /> [[Tina Arena]] performed with him in all 5 concerts during the tour.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tina Joins Andrea Bocelli for His Australian Tour|url=http://tinaarena.com/index.php?module=news&section=newsdetail&secid=85&lang=en|accessdate=15 December 2013|newspaper=Tina Arena|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203033914/http://tinaarena.com/index.php?module=news&section=newsdetail&secid=85&lang=en|archivedate=3 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 September 2008, during the 2008 [[Veneto]] Festival, he held a concert in the [[Church of the Eremitani]] in [[Padova]], Italy. He was accompanied by the [[I Solisti Veneti]] orchestra, celebrating its 50th birthday and conducted by [[Claudio Scimone]], and by the [[Wiener Singakademie]] choir. The concert was a celebration of [[Giacomo Puccini]]'s 150th birthday.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert5\">\n{{cite news|title=live concert2008/5|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2008_5.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 and 11 October he performed at [[Petra]], singing \"[[Vivere (Dare to Live)|Dare to Live]]\" with [[Laura Pausini]], as well as performing \"E Lucevan le Stelle\" from ''Tosca''. On 19 October, he sang \"[['O surdato 'nnammurato]]\" and a duet of \"Non Ti Scordar Di Me\" with [[Cecilia Bartoli]], both from the ''[[Incanto]]'' album, during the [[Echo (music award)|ECHO Awards]] in Germany; and later presented the soprano with an ECHO award. On 24 October, he performed at ''[[Piazza del Plebiscito]]'' in Naples, as a tribute to the city, where he celebrated the Italian release of ''Incanto''. Performing with him were flautist Andrea Griminelli, Italian pop singer [[Massimo Ranieri]] and soprano [[Cecilia Bartoli]], with [[Steven Mercurio]] conducting the [[Czech National Symphony Orchestra]].<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert6\">\n{{cite news|title=live concert2008/6|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2008_6.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> On 31 October, he performed a solo version of \"The Prayer\", as well as \"[[Because (1902 song)|Because]]\", a song from ''Incanto'', live on [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]].<ref name=\"october 2008\">\n{{cite web|title=Live with Faith Hill & David Foster|publisher=www.oprah.com|url=http://www.oprah.com/slideshow/oprahshow/20081031_tows_fridays/9|accessdate=31 October 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206193215/http://www.oprah.com/slideshow/oprahshow/20081031_tows_fridays/9|archivedate=6 December 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 and 22 November Bocelli was amongst a quartet of soloists (soprano [[Sabina Cvilak]], [[mezzo-soprano]] [[Kate Aldrich]] and [[bass (voice type)|bass]] [[Alexander Vinogradov (bass)|Alexander Vinogradov]]) to sing Rossini's ''[[Petite messe solennelle]]'', conducted by [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], at the [[Washington National Opera]] in Washington, D.C.<ref name=\"Petite messe solennelle\">\n{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli and Pl\u00e1cido Domingo together for the first time in Petite Messe Solennelle |publisher=www.dc-opera.org |year=2008 |url=http://www.dc-opera.org/ourseason/petitemesse.asp |accessdate=24 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090125102140/http://www.dc-opera.org/ourseason/petitemesse.asp |archivedate=25 January 2009 }}</ref> Bocelli sang twice in the piece and later the two tenors sang \"[[The Pearl Fishers' Duet]]\" which would be the first [[aria]] they had ever sung together.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert7\">\n{{cite news|title=live concert2008/7|publisher=Bocelli.de|year=2008|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2008_7.htm|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> On 25 and 26 November he starred alongside soprano [[Ver\u00f3nica Villarroel]] in an opera in concert of Mascagni's [[Cavalleria rusticana]] at the ''\"Municipal Auditorium\"'' in [[San Antonio]], Texas.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert7\" /> He later held a concert at ''\"Atrio de la Catedral\"'' in [[Campeche]], Mexico, on 28 November, where he sang songs from ''Incanto'' as well as some of his Spanish hits, including ''[[B\u00e9same Mucho]]'', ''[[Somos Novios]]'', ''[[Amapola (song)|Amapola]]'' and ''[[Por ti Volare]]'' \u2013 the Spanish version of ''Con te Partiro''.<ref name=\"BOC2008 concert7\" />\n\n===2009: ''My Christmas'', first holiday album===\nOn 27 May 2009, Bocelli sang \"Il Gladiatore\", from the [[Gladiator (soundtrack)|Gladiator]] soundtrack, followed by the [[UEFA Champions League Anthem]], which is based on \"[[Zadok the Priest]]\" by G.F. Handel, during the opening ceremony of the [[2009 UEFA Champions League Final]], in the [[Stadio Olimpico]], in Rome.\n\nOn 3 November, ''[[My Christmas]]'', his first [[Christmas music|Holiday album]], produced by [[David Foster]], was released and went on to become the [[List of best-selling Christmas/holiday albums in the United States#2000s|best-selling Holiday album of the year]].\n\nThe ''[[My Christmas Special|Andrea Bocelli & David Foster Christmas Special]]'', the [[PBS]] special of the album, first aired on [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving]] night in the United States, and continued to be broadcast in the United States and Canada throughout the month of December. In late November, the program was broadcast in [[Mexico]] and in the UK; it later aired, 15 and 25 December, on [[Italia 1]], in Italy, 19 December, on [[TVE2]] and [[TROS]], in Spain and the Netherlands, and Christmas Eve, on [[vtm]] and [[RTL T\u00e9l\u00e9 L\u00ebtzebuerg|RTL-TVI]], in Belgium and [[Luxembourg]].\n\n[[File:Andrea Bocelli with piano @ Premio Faraglioni 2009.JPG|thumb|Bocelli performing at the Premio Faraglioni 2009.]]\n\nOn 3 November, during the World Premiere of [[Disney]]'s ''[[A Christmas Carol (2009 film)|A Christmas Carol]]'', in [[Leicester Square]], London, following the switching on of the annual [[Oxford Street]] and [[Regent Street]] Christmas lights, Bocelli led the [[St Paul's Cathedral]] [[Choir]], and more than 14,000 people across the capital, as they broke the Official [[Guinness World Record]] for the biggest ever [[Christmas carol]] [[sing-along]], singing \"[[Silent Night]]\". He completed his performance in Leicester Square with,  \"God Bless Us Everyone\", the closing song of the movie, which he provided the vocals for in English, Italian and Spanish.<ref name=\"Bocelli - A Christmas Carol (1)\">\n{{cite web|title=Bocelli leads Christmas carol sing-along|publisher=[[Classic FM (UK)|ClassicFm]].co.uk, 3 November 2010 article|url=http://www.classicfm.co.uk/music/music-news-and-features/bocelli-leads-christmas-carol-sing-along/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20111011083648/http://www.classicfm.co.uk/music/music-news-and-features/bocelli-leads-christmas-carol-sing-along/|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 October 2011|accessdate=4 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Bocelli - A Christmas Carol (2)\">\n{{cite web|title=Record breaking night for London's Christmas Carol-themed lights switch-on|publisher=Indielondon.co.uk, 3 November 2010 article|url=http://www.indielondon.co.uk/Film-Review/record-breaking-night-for-london-s-christmas-carol-themed-lights-switch-on|accessdate=4 April 2010}}</ref> He returned to the United Kingdom, 16 December, for an appearance on ''[[The One Show]]'', broadcast live by [[BBC One]], and on ''[[The Alan Titchmarsh Show]]'' which aired 18 December, on [[ITV1]].\n\nOn 21 November, a segment of ''Leute Heute'', a German [[Tabloid television|tabloid-program]] on [[ZDF]], was about ''My Christmas'' and Bocelli's meeting in Rome with [[Pope Benedict XVI]] and 250 other artists, an event which was broadcast live earlier that day in Italy, by [[Rai Uno]]. Bocelli was also joined by the [[Piccolo Coro dell'Antoniano]], in his home in [[Forte dei Marmi]], where they sang \"Caro Ges\u00f9 Bambino\", a song from ''My Christmas'' which was [[List of songs recorded by Zecchino d'Oro|originally recorded by the choir in 1960]]. [[Rai Uno]] also broadcast the performance later that day, during the [[Zecchino d'Oro|Zecchino d'Oro Festival]]. The following day, Bocelli was among Fabio Fazio's guests, on his popular Italian talk-show, [[Che tempo che fa]], broadcast on [[Rai Tre]]. During the program Bocelli talked about his album and performed \"[[The Lord's Prayer]]\", \"[[White Christmas (song)|White Christmas]]\", and \"[[Silent Night]]\". It was also announced that Bocelli would return to the show on 20 December and give a live concert of ''My Christmas''. Bocelli also took part in the annual [[Jos\u00e9 Carreras#Humanitarian work|2009 ''Jos\u00e9 Carreras Gala'']], on 17 December, where he sang [[Adeste Fideles]], before singing \"White Christmas\" with [[Jos\u00e9 Carreras]] for the very first time; this was broadcast live, by [[Das Erste]], in Germany. He then returning to Italy, for a concert in the [[Basilica of San Francesco d'Assisi#The Upper Basilica of St. Francis|Upper Basilica of San Francesco d'Assisi]], on 19 December, which was broadcast directly after the ''[[Urbi et Orbi]]'' blessing of Pope Benedict XVI, 25 December, on [[Rai Uno]].\n\nIn North America, Bocelli gave 6 concerts. On 28 November, he performed in the [[BankAtlantic Center]], in [[Ft. Lauderdale, Florida]]. He later performed in the [[Air Canada Centre]], in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada, in the [[Izod Center]], in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]], in the [[Fresno Convention Center#Saroyan Theatre|William Saroyan Theatre]], in [[Fresno, California]] (changed from the much larger [[Save Mart Center]] due to scheduling conflicts), in the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena|MGM Grand]], in [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas]], and finally in the [[Honda Center]], in [[Anaheim, California]], on 3, 5, 8, 12 and 13 December. His last three arena concerts alone grossed a total of over 5,6 million dollars, placing him third on [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard Magazine]]'s week's Hot Tours ranking, behind the [[Trans-Siberian Orchestra]] and [[Il Divo]], who both held over 5 times more concerts worldwide, compared to Bocelli's three in the United States, explaining their better showings.<ref>{{cite news|last=Allen|first=Bob|title=Hot Tours: Trans-Siberian Orchestra, Il Divo, Andrea Bocelli|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/photos/live/960815/hot-tours-trans-siberian-orchestra-il-divo-andrea-bocelli|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=Billboard|date=5 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, Bocelli made a number of high-profile TV appearances. He first performed \"White Christmas\" at the 83rd annual [[Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade]], broadcast live on [[NBC]], 26 November. He performed the song again on 30 November during ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|The Today Show]]'' also live. His appearance on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' during her ''Holiday Music Extravaganza'', where he sang \"[[What Child Is This (Andrea Bocelli and Mary J. Blige cover)|What Child Is This]]\", with [[Mary J. Blige]], and later closed the show with [[Adeste Fideles]], was also aired the same day, and was later rebroadcast on 23 December. Bocelli also sang \"Adeste Fideles\" and was interviewed by [[Barbara Walters]] and [[Joy Behar]] on ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'', which aired 2 December, on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]. On 8 December, he performed \"[[Jingle Bells]]\" with [[The Muppets]] on ''[[The Jay Leno Show]]''. He also performed a number of songs from the album, including \"[[The Christmas Song]]\" with [[Natalie Cole]], during a dinner at [[David Foster]]'s [[mansion]] in [[Malibu, California|Malibu]], which was featured on ''[[Dr. Phil (TV series)|The Dr. Phil Show]]'', on 10 December. Bocelli also performed \"White Christmas\" and  \"[[Silent Night]]\", on the ''[[Larry King Live]]'' and ''[[Fox & Friends]]'' holiday-specials, broadcast 23 December, on [[CNN]], and 19, 24 and 25 December, on [[Fox News Channel|Fox News]].\n\nIn [[Brasil]], following the success of the South American leg of the ''Incanto tour'', where over 100,000 people attended his free concert at the [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]'s \"Parque Indipendencia\", earlier in the year,<ref>{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli Performs to 100,000 in Brazil|url=http://www.classicfm.com/artists/andrea-bocelli/news/andrea-bocelli-performs-100000-brazil/|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=[[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]]}}</ref> it was announced that Bocelli would hold another [[open-air concert|Open-Air]], entrance free, concert in [[Florian\u00f3polis]], on 28 December, where a crowd of about a million people was expected to attend. However, due to financial and political reasons, the concert was later canceled on short notice, along with all the other events scheduled for Christmas in the city.\n\n===2010: Hollywood Walk of Fame and FIFA World Cup===\nOn 31 January 2010, during the [[52nd Grammy Awards]], Bocelli, [[Mary J. Blige]] and David Foster joined forces again, singing \"[[Bridge over Troubled Water (song)|Bridge over Troubled Water]]\" as a tribute to the victims of that year's [[2010 Haiti earthquake|earthquake in Haiti]].<ref name=\"Bocelli in 2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/live2010_1.htm|title=Andrea Bocelli in 2010|publisher=Bocelli.de}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1001/30/lkl.01.html|title=CNN Larry King Live Transcript \u2013 Episode 30 January 2010|publisher=CNN|date=30 January 2010|accessdate=28 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:DavidFosterMar10.jpg|right|upright|thumb|[[David Foster]] speaks at the ceremony honoring Bocelli with his star.]]\n\nOn 2 March, he was honoured with a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] for his contribution to [[Theatre|Live Theater]], at 7000 [[Hollywood Boulevard]], in front of the [[Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel|Roosevelt Hotel]].<ref name=\"Bocelli gets Star (1)\">{{cite news|title=Hollywood Walk of Fame Honors Andrea Bocelli|url=http://ireport.cnn.com/docs/DOC-415682|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=[[CNN iReport]]|date=3 March 2010}}</ref> The previous day, Bocelli, along with David Foster, were honored by ''L.A. Italia Film, Fashion and Art Fest'' during a ceremony at the [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]], in Hollywood, where ''The Story Behind The Voice'', a documentary about Bocelli's life and career was shown.<ref>{{cite news|last=Olivier|first=Ellen|title=L.A. Italia Film, Fashion and Art Fest honors tenor Andrea Bocelli and producer David Foster|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/mar/07/image/la-ig-scene-20100307|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=7 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, Bocelli made an appearance on [[Skavlan]], in [[Oslo]], Norway, to promote his upcoming [[Scandinavia|Scandinavian tour]], giving a rare interview to the show's host [[Fredrik Skavlan]], and later performing \"Voglio Vivere Cosi\", from his 2008 album ''Incanto'', with [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] [[Boys' choir]], [[S\u00f8lvguttene]].<ref name=\"Bocelli in 2010\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Hansen|first=Magne|title=Andrea Bocelli og kokken som sa nei til Obama p\u00e5 Skavlan|url=http://www.nrk.no/kultur/andrea-bocelli-til-skavlan-1.7031646|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=[[NRK]]|date=10 March 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nIn April, he returned to Scandinavia for a concert in [[Telenor Arena]] in B\u00e6rum, Norway, on 8 April, a concert in [[Forum Copenhagen]] in Copenhagen, Denmark, on 9 April, and finally a concert in the [[Ericsson Globe]], in Stockholm, Sweden, on 11 April. He was joined by [[Heather Headley]] and 120 musicians from the Stockholm Concert Orchestra, in all three concerts, and by Swedish [[mezzo-soprano]] [[Malena Ernman]] in his Swedish concert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bocelli.de/live/konzert2010_2.htm|title=Andrea Bocelli April 2010 events|publisher=Bocelli.de|date=|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bocelli \u2013 with a little help from Ernman|url=http://www.nordstjernan.com/news/sweden/2121|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=[[Nordstjernan (newspaper)|Nordstjernan]]}}</ref><ref>[http://www.kulturspegeln.se/andrea-bocelli-i-globenstockholm-concert-orchestra Andrea Bocelli i Globen Stockholm Concert Orchestra], Swedish article. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804140143/http://www.kulturspegeln.se/andrea-bocelli-i-globenstockholm-concert-orchestra |date=4 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April, Bocelli sang \"[[Nessun dorma]]\" during [[2010 Shanghai Expo opening ceremony|the opening ceremony]] of the [[Expo 2010]], in Shanghai, China.<ref>{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli on stage with Chinese girl for Shanghai Expo|url=http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90776/90883/6969737.html|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=People's Daily Online|date=30 April 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article7112559.ece Size matters at Shanghai Expo 2010], [[The Times]], 30 April 2010 article.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bodeen |first=Christopher |title=Sarkozy, other leaders in Shanghai for World Expo |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/nationworld/2011741071_apaschinaexpo.html |accessdate=10 December 2013 |newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=30 April 2010 |agency=AP |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216090812/http://seattletimes.com/html/nationworld/2011741071_apaschinaexpo.html |archivedate=16 December 2013 }}</ref> The following day, on 1 May, he held a concert, titled ''Charming China'', at [[Shanghai Stadium]].<ref>[http://cityweekend.com.cn/shanghai/events/64616 Glamour of China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305075454/http://www.cityweekend.com.cn/shanghai/events/64616 |date=5 March 2016 }}, [[City Weekend]].</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Daiqi|first=Xing|title=Expo showcases music, art and culture|url=http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90782/90872/6968222.html|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=[[People's Daily]]|date=30 April 2010}}</ref> The concert was later broadcast by [[Shanghai Television|Shanghai TV]], and by [[China Central Television|CCTV]] [[CCTV Channels|channels]] throughout [[mainland China]].\n\n[[File:Song Bocelli Lang East Meets West (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Andrea Bocelli and [[Song Zuying]] performing ''[[Con te partir\u00f2|Time to Say Goodbye]]'' at the ''East Meets West'' concert.]]\n\nThe two appearances coincided with Bocelli's Asian tour, consisting of a concert in [[Nippon Budokan|Budokan]], Tokyo, Japan, on 28 April,<ref>{{cite news|last=Grunebaum|first=Dan|title=Andrea Bocelli|url=http://metropolis.co.jp/arts/agenda/andrea-bocelli/|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=[[Metropolis (free magazine)|Metropolis]]|date=15 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eplus.jp/sys/web/s/bocelli/index.html|title=Andrea Bocelli: Live in Japan 2010|publisher=Eplus.jp|accessdate=6 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229042746/http://eplus.jp/sys/web/s/bocelli/index.html|archive-date=29 February 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> a concert in [[Jamsil Students' Gymnasium|Jamsil Gymnasium]], [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]], on 2 May,<ref>{{cite news|last=Hyo-won|first=Lee|title=Andrea Bocelli to Become One With Audience|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2010/04/135_64532.html|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=20 April 2010}}</ref> a concert in [[Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Centre]], in Hong Kong, on 4 May,<ref name=\"HK 2010 (1)\">{{cite news|last=Chen|first=Yali|title=Bocellimania to sweep music fans in a week|url=http://www.etaiwannews.com/etn/news_content.php?id=1231188&lang=eng_news|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=[[Taiwan News]]|date=20 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"HK 2010 (2)\">{{cite news|last=Chen |first=Yali |title=Bocelli to hold concerts in Hong Kong, Taipei |url=http://www.culture.tw/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1691&Itemid=235 |accessdate=12 December 2013 |newspaper=Taiwan Culture Portal |date=16 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203010601/http://www.culture.tw/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1691&Itemid=235 |archivedate= 3 December 2013 }}</ref> a concert in [[Taipei Arena]], [[Taipei]], [[Taiwan]], on 6 May,<ref name=\"HK 2010 (1)\"/><ref name=\"HK 2010 (2)\"/> and finally a free concert, organized by the [[YTL Corporation]], at the [[Singapore Botanic Gardens]], in Singapore, on 8 May, attended by over 12,000 people, picked via [[Ballot|public ballot]].<ref>[http://www.ytlconcert2010.com.sg/ YTL Concert of Celebration 2010] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401133012/http://www.ytlconcert2010.com.sg/ |date=1 April 2010 }}, Official YTL Concerts 2010 site.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=12,000 enjoy Andrea Bocelli treat|url=http://www.ytlcommunity.com/commnews/shownews.asp?newsid=53168|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=YTL Community|date=9 May 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.kl-lifestyle.com.my/2010/05/enchated-night-with-andrea-bocelli Enchated Night with Andrea Bocelli], ''KL-lifestyle.com'', 11 May 2010, article. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724055742/http://www.kl-lifestyle.com.my/2010/05/enchated-night-with-andrea-bocelli |date=24 July 2012 }}</ref> The concert was later broadcast, in its entirety, by [[Channel NewsAsia]], on 28 and 29 May, and by [[Okto]], on 30 May, in Singapore. An [[Orchidaceae|orchid]] in the [[Singapore Botanic Gardens|Botanic Gardens']] [[National Orchid Garden]] was also named after Bocelli in response to the concert.<ref>{{cite web|author=ria tan|url=http://wildsingaporenews.blogspot.com/2010/05/nparks-to-introduce-more-orchid-species.html|title=Singapore Botanic Gardens: Orchid named after Andrea Bocelli|publisher=Wildsingaporenews.blogspot.com|date=15 May 2010|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> Australian pop singer [[Delta Goodrem]] performed again with Bocelli in all five concerts, after supporting him in his United States [[My Christmas|My Christmas 2009 winter tour]].<ref>[http://www.accessallareas.net.au/music_news/EkVAEplpuZihJNFJqK.php Delta Goodrem to support Andrea Bocelli in the US] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902022733/http://www.accessallareas.net.au/music_news/EkVAEplpuZihJNFJqK.php |date=2 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May, during the [[2010 World Music Awards]], Bocelli performed \"Un Amore Cosi Grande\" from his 2008 album, ''Incanto'', and received his seventh [[World Music Awards|World Music Award]], for \"Best Classical Artist\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Sheridan|first=Emily|title=Jennifer Lopez shows her wild side in two animal-print dresses at the World Music Awards|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1279581/World-Music-Awards-Jennifer-Lopez-shows-wild-animal-print-dresses.html|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=Mail Online|date=19 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldmusicawards.com|title=World Music Awards Official Site|publisher=Worldmusicawards.com|date=|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 July, Bocelli gave a concert at the opening of the [[Khan Shatyr Entertainment Center]], in [[Astana]], on the occasion of [[Kazakhstan]]'s [[List of leaders of Kazakhstan|president]] [[Nursultan Nazarbayev]]'s 70th birthday.<ref>{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli books gig in Kazakhstan|url=http://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/Music/2010/06/15/Andrea-Bocelli-books-gig-in-Kazakhstan/UPI-60551276624467|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=[[United Press International]]|date=15 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Orange|first=Richard|title=Giant indoor park opened for Kazakh president's birthday|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/kazakhstan/7873035/Giant-indoor-park-opened-for-Kazakh-presidents-birthday.html|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=5 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 July, Bocelli headlined the \"Celebrate Africa: The Grand Finale\" Concert at the [[Coca-Cola Dome]], in [[Johannesburg]], South Africa, to mark the end of the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]], two days before the [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final|final]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bocelli, Bryan Adams To Headline 'Grand Finale' Concert at World Cup|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/958430/bocelli-bryan-adams-to-headline-grand-finale-concert-at-world-cup|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=Billboard|date=29 April 2010|agency=AP}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/Bryan+Adams+Bocelli+sing+World+finale/2966918/story.html |title=Bryan Adams, Bocelli to sing at World Cup finale |newspaper=[[The Vancouver Sun]] |date=29 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100502160540/http://www.vancouversun.com/entertainment/Bryan%2BAdams%2BBocelli%2Bsing%2BWorld%2Bfinale/2966918/story.html |archivedate= 2 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn 13 July, [[Statehood Day (Montenegro)|Montenegrin Statehood Day]], Bocelli gave a concert at the seaside resort of [[Sveti Stefan]], in western [[Montenegro]], to mark the [[Golden Jubilee]] of the [[Aman Resorts#Locations|Sveti Stefan Hotel]].<ref name=\"Bocelli in Montenegro\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20100723144407/http://www.traveldailynews.com/pages/show_page/38032-The-anniversary-of-the-Sveti-Stefan-Hotel-marked-by-a-concert-by-Andrea-Bocelli The anniversary of the Sveti Stefan Hotel marked by a concert by Andrea Bocelli], 20 July 2010 article.</ref>\n\nOn 14 July, Bocelli gave a concert at the [[European Parliament]]'s [[Espace L\u00e9opold]], in [[Brussels]], Belgium, during \"Rome in the heart of the future\", an event hosted by the [[Vice President of the European Parliament]] for the [[seventh European Parliament|seventh parliament]], [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]], [[Roberta Angelilli]].<ref name=\"Bocelli: Euro Parliament 2010\">[http://eppgroup.eu/press/showPR.asp?PRControlDocTypeID=1&PRControlID=9563&PRContentID=16367&PRContentLg=en Rome in the heart of the future: Invitation by Vice-President of the European Parliament, Roberta Angelilli MEP] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720160223/http://eppgroup.eu/press/showPR.asp?PRControlDocTypeID=1&PRControlID=9563&PRContentID=16367&PRContentLg=en |date=20 July 2011 }}, [[European People's Party (European Parliament group)|EPP Group]], 13 July 2010 article.</ref><ref>[http://gary-brusselsblog.blogspot.com/2010/07/lunchtime-with-andrea-bocelli.html Lunchtime with Andrea Bocelli], 14 July 2010 article.</ref> A screening of the film ''Homage to Rome'', directed by [[Franco Zeffirelli]], who was present during the event, and starring Bocelli, in his [[Film|cinematographic]] debut, was shown prior to the special concert.<ref name=\"Bocelli: Euro Parliament 2010\"/><ref>[http://www.iltempo.it/cronaca_locale/roma/2010/07/12/1179014-bocelli_cantera_bruxelles.shtml?refresh_ce Bocelli canter\u00e0 a Bruxelles] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928121826/http://www.iltempo.it/cronaca_locale/roma/2010/07/12/1179014-bocelli_cantera_bruxelles.shtml?refresh_ce |date=28 September 2012 }}, [[Il Tempo]], 12 July 2010 article.</ref>\n\nOn 25 July, Bocelli held the fifth and final edition of the [[Teatro del Silenzio]], in his hometown of [[Lajatico]], Tuscany. Bocelli's guests included Spanish [[Catalonia|Catalan]] tenor [[Jos\u00e9 Carreras]], and Italian rock singer [[Zucchero]]. Sculptures by Swiss artist [[Kurt Laurenz Metzler]], who attended the concert, were exhibited during this year's edition. Bocelli was also awarded the ''Pisano Doc'', during the dress rehearsal for the concert, on 24 July, and received the 2010 ''Premio Lunezia nel mondo'', during a private ceremony held on 21 July, for \"the musical-literary quality of his songs.\"\n\nIn September 2010, Bocelli held a concert at the [[Odeon of Herodes Atticus]], in [[Athens]], Greece. All proceeds were donated to help cure cancer. Bocelli also gave concerts in [[Cairo]], Egypt, in front of the pyramids and the [[Great Sphinx of Giza]], as well as a fundraising concert inside the [[Duomo di Milano]] to benefit victims of the [[2010 Haiti earthquake]].\n\nAs part of the 2010 leg of the [[My Christmas Tour]], Bocelli gave two concerts in [[The O2 Arena]], in London, and the [[Manchester Arena]], in [[Manchester]], and a concert at [[3Arena|The O2]], in [[Dublin]], in late November 2010.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sweeting|first=Adam|title=Andrea Bocelli, O2 Arena, review|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/classicalconcertreviews/8134168/Andrea-Bocelli-O2-Arena-review.html|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=15 November 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.citylife.co.uk/news_and_reviews/reviews/10018833_review__andrea_bocelli___men_arena Andrea Bocelli concert review] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323005306/http://www.citylife.co.uk/news_and_reviews/reviews/10018833_review__andrea_bocelli___men_arena |date=23 March 2012 }}, [[City Life (magazine)|citylife]].co.uk, 26 November 2010 article.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bandsintown.com/event/3289068-andrea-bocelli-dublin-ireland-live-at-the-o2-dublin-on-november-22-2010|title=Andrea Bocelli live in Dublin, Ireland|publisher=Bandsintown.com|date=12 November 2010|accessdate=6 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309142827/http://www.bandsintown.com/event/3289068-andrea-bocelli-dublin-ireland-live-at-the-o2-dublin-on-november-22-2010|archive-date=9 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> His sold-out concert at the O2 in London, was the most attended show in the venue's history, with 16,500 people attending the event.<ref>[http://www.classicfm.co.uk/music/latest-music-news/andrea-bocelli-makes-history-o2 Andrea Bocelli makes history at O2], [[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]], 16 November 2010 article.</ref> In early December, Bocelli gave 6 concerts in the United States. He performed in [[Madison Square Garden]], in New York City, [[Prudential Center]], in [[Newark, New Jersey]], [[TD Garden]], in [[Boston]], Toyota Center, in Houston, [[Staples Center]], in Los Angeles, and the [[MGM Grand Las Vegas|MGM Grand]]'s [[MGM Grand Garden Arena|Garden Arena]], in the [[Las Vegas Strip]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Kel|url=http://www.clickitticket.com/blog/post/Andrea-Bocelli-Brings-His-Christmas-to-the-US.aspx|title=Andrea Bocelli Brings His Christmas to the US|publisher=Clickitticket.com|date=|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nBocelli also took part in the [[Christmas in Washington]] special on 12 December.<ref name=\"Obama\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tnt.tv/christmasinwashington/display/?contentId=77664|title=Andrea Bocelli on TNT's Official Website|publisher=Tnt.tv|accessdate=6 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302080921/http://www.tnt.tv/christmasinwashington/display/?contentId=77664|archivedate=2 March 2012}}</ref> On 19 December, Bocelli gave a concert, conducted by [[Claudio Scimone]], in the [[Italian Senate]].<ref>[http://www.bocelli.de/en/live/concert2010_11.htm Bocelli concert at Italian Senate], Bocelli.de.</ref>\n\n===2011: Metropolitan Opera recital, and Central Park Concert===\nIn January, Bocelli gave three concerts in Germany. The concerts in [[Munich]], Berlin, and [[Hamburg]] were all part of the [[Notte Illuminata|Notte Illuminata Tour]], launched in [[Pisa]], at the Teatro Verdi, December 2010. In February, Bocelli performed a recital on the stage of the [[Metropolitan Opera]] house as part of the tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metoperafamily.org/metopera/news/press/detail.aspx?id=12376 |title=Andrea Bocelli to Make Met Recital Debut |publisher=Metoperafamily.org |accessdate=6 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415070627/http://www.metoperafamily.org/metopera/news/press/detail.aspx?id=12376 |archivedate=15 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn late March, early April, as part of the 2011 Latin Leg of his Incanto Tour, Bocelli gave concerts in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Bogot\u00e1]], and [[Panama City]].\n\nIn May 2011, Bocelli held 5 concerts in East and Southeast Asia, and was joined by New Zealand soprano [[Hayley Westenra]] during the tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/ShowNews/WebNews_Detail.aspx?Type=aALL&ID=201104140022 |title=Hayley Westenra to perform at Bocelli concerts in Taipei |publisher=focustaiwan.tw |accessdate=28 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119075224/http://focustaiwan.tw/ShowNews/WebNews_Detail.aspx?Type=aALL&ID=201104140022 |archivedate=19 January 2012 }}</ref> He first gave a concert in [[Jakarta]], Indonesia.<ref>[http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/lifeandtimes/andrea-bocelli-gives-stirring-performance-for-gilded-crowd/441267 Andrea Bocelli Gives Stirring Performance for Gilded Crowd] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925114259/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/lifeandtimes/andrea-bocelli-gives-stirring-performance-for-gilded-crowd/441267 |date=25 September 2012 }}, [[Jakarta Globe]], 16 May 2011 article.</ref> Bocelli held two other concerts in [[Taipei]], and two concerts in [[Beijing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fashion.ce.cn/news/music/201104/14/t20110414_22364090.shtml |title=2011 Asian Tour |publisher=Fashion.ce.cn |accessdate=6 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814011002/http://fashion.ce.cn/news/music/201104/14/t20110414_22364090.shtml |archivedate=14 August 2011 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/cndy/2011-05/17/content_12521354.htm Bocelli shares the love with Beijing concerts], ''[[China Daily]]''.</ref>\n\nIn June and July, Bocelli gave two [[open-air concert]]s at historic sites, the first at [[Masada]], in [[Israel]],<ref>[http://www.opera-masada.com/en/Bocelli-Masada Andrea Bocelli at Masada] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425161536/http://www.opera-masada.com/en/Bocelli-Masada |date=25 April 2012 }} Official ''Opera Masada'' website</ref> with all proceeds dedicated to support the residents of the Israeli regions of [[Galilee]] and [[Negev]],<ref>[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4008376,00.html Andrea Bocelli to sing at Masada \u2013 Famed Italian tenor to take part in one time performance in June. All proceeds dedicated to support of Galilee, Negev residents] [[Ynetnews]]</ref> and the second at [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]]'s [[Theatre of ancient Greece|ancient Greek theatre]], in [[Sicily]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.italymag.co.uk/italy/greek-theatre-syracuse/andrea-bocelli-greek-theatre-syracuse|title=Andrea Bocelli at the Greek Theatre of Syracuse|publisher=Italymag.co.uk|date=27 June 2011|accessdate=6 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805033820/http://italymag.co.uk/italy/greek-theatre-syracuse/andrea-bocelli-greek-theatre-syracuse|archive-date=5 August 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with all proceeds donated to the ''Fiamme di Solidariet\u00e0'' (Flames of Solidarity) organization, to raise awareness of issues concerning the poorest and most marginalized in Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiammedisolidarieta.it|title=Fiamme di Solidarieta \u2013 Official Benefit concert website|publisher=Fiammedisolidarieta.it|accessdate=6 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425162236/http://www.fiammedisolidarieta.it//|archive-date=25 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBocelli gave a free concert on 15 September, on the [[Great Lawn and Turtle Pond|Great Lawn]] of [[Central Park]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|author=Scozzese Design |url=http://bocellicentralpark.com/news/detail/andrea_bocelli_gifts_new_york_city_with_a_once_in_a_lifetime_musical |title=Andrea Bocelli Gifts New York City with a Once in a Lifetime Musical |publisher=Bocellicentralpark.com |accessdate=6 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402132548/http://bocellicentralpark.com/news/detail/andrea_bocelli_gifts_new_york_city_with_a_once_in_a_lifetime_musical |archivedate=2 April 2012 }}</ref> He was accompanied by the [[New York Philharmonic]], conducted by its music director [[Alan Gilbert (conductor)|Alan Gilbert]], and the [[Westminster Choir College|Westminster Symphonic Choir]].<ref name=\"Central Park Guests\">{{cite web|author=Scozzese Design |url=http://bocellicentralpark.com/news/detail/celine_dion_tony_bennett |title=C\u00e9line Dion, Tony Bennett Among Those To Celebrate With Andrea Bocelli on Central Park's Great Lawn |publisher=Bocellicentralpark.com |accessdate=6 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402132620/http://bocellicentralpark.com/news/detail/celine_dion_tony_bennett |archivedate=2 April 2012 }}</ref> The concert was broadcast throughout the United States and Canada, by [[PBS]], and in Italy, by [[Rai 1]]. ''[[Concerto: One Night in Central Park]]'', the [[live album]] and the [[DVD-Video|DVD]] were released 15 November.\n\nOn 25 September, Bocelli led ''[[Songs of Praise]]'''s 50th anniversary celebration, alongside [[LeAnn Rimes]] and [[Katherine Jenkins]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Andrea Bocelli leads Songs of Praise 50th celebrations|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-14358591|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=31 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 October, Bocelli performed again for [[Pope Benedict XVI]] and a crowd of 8,000 people in [[Vatican City|Vatican]]'s [[Paul VI Audience Hall|Audience Hall]].<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/photos/italian-tenor-andrea-bocelli-performed-pope-benedict-xvi-photo-200156948.html Italian tenor Andrea Bocelli performs for Pope Benedict XVI]{{dead link|date=June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 November, he gave an open-air free concert at [[Pra\u00e7a Rui Barbosa]] in [[Belo Horizonte]], [[Brazil]], to an audience of between 80,000 and 150,000 people.<ref>[https://archive.today/20120906212615/http://www.portalcwb.com/fiat-35-anos-andrea-bocelli-faz-show-emocionante-para-81-mil-pessoas.html FIAT 35 ANOS: Andrea Bocelli faz show emocionante para 81 mil pessoas] (Portuguese)</ref><ref>[http://musica.uol.com.br/ultnot/2011/11/06/pela-1-vez-em-bh-andrea-bocelli-mescla-erudito-ao-pop-e-emociona-em-duetos-com-sandy.jhtm Pela 1\u00aa vez em BH, Andrea Bocelli mescla erudito ao pop e emociona em duetos com Sandy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106142546/http://musica.uol.com.br/ultnot/2011/11/06/pela-1-vez-em-bh-andrea-bocelli-mescla-erudito-ao-pop-e-emociona-em-duetos-com-sandy.jhtm |date=6 January 2016 }} (Portuguese)</ref><ref>[http://www.nhenhenhem.com/noticias/sandy-e-o-tenor-italiano-andrea-bocelli-cantam-para-mais-de-150-mil-pessoas-em-belo-horizonte-2498.html Sandy e o tenor italiano Andrea Bocelli cantam para mais de 150 mil pessoas em Belo Horizonte] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106142546/http://www.nhenhenhem.com/noticias/sandy-e-o-tenor-italiano-andrea-bocelli-cantam-para-mais-de-150-mil-pessoas-em-belo-horizonte-2498.html |date=6 January 2016 }} (Portuguese)</ref>\n\nOn 17 November, he performed at the Children in Need Rocks Manchester concert, gaining critical acclaim for receiving a standing ovation from a crowd of pop and indie music fans.\n\n===2012\u20132014: ''Rom\u00e9o et Juliette'' and ''Passione''===\nBocelli played the role of [[Romeo]] in [[Charles Gounod]]'s opera ''[[Rom\u00e9o et Juliette]]'', at the [[Teatro Carlo Felice]], for two performances in February 2012. He cancelled a third performance with [[pharyngitis]] after suffering vocal strain throughout.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pisatoday.it/cronaca/andrea-bocelli-annullato-romeo-juliette-genova-28-febbraio-2012.html | title=Salta \"Romeo et Juliette\" a Genova: Andrea Bocelli non ce la fa | work=Pisa Today | date=28 February 2012 |accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April, Bocelli gave an open-air concert at [[Yerevan]]'s [[Freedom Square, Yerevan|Liberty Square]], in [[Armenia]], dedicated to the proclamation of Yerevan as the 2012 [[World Book Capital]]; he was accompanied by the [[Armenian Philharmonic Orchestra]] conducted by Marcello Rota.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mher Margaryan |url=http://www.armradio.am/eng/news/?part=cult&id=22627 |title=Andrea Bocelli performs at Yerevan's Liberty Square |publisher=Armradio.am |date=23 April 2012 |accessdate=6 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722081608/http://www.armradio.am/eng/news/?part=cult |archivedate=22 July 2012 }}</ref> On 19 November, he performed for [[Queen Elizabeth II]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], at the [[Royal Albert Hall]], during the 100th anniversary of the [[Royal Variety Performance]].<ref>[https://archive.today/20130209204918/http://news.yahoo.com/photos/britains-queen-elizabeth-greets-tenor-andrea-bocelli-royal-photo-230411001.html Britain's Queen Elizabeth greets tenor Andrea Bocelli after the Royal Variety Performance] [[Yahoo! News]]</ref>\n\nA new studio album entitled ''[[Passione (Andrea Bocelli album)|Passione]]'', featuring duets with [[Jennifer Lopez]] and [[Nelly Furtado]], was released on 29 January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andreabocelli.com/en/#!/career-2012_1001|title=Andrea Bocelli Official Website|publisher=Andreabocelli.com|date=|accessdate=18 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019065145/http://www.andreabocelli.com/en/#!/career-2012_1001|archive-date=19 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 7 February, Bocelli was an honorary guest at the 61st Annual [[National Prayer Breakfast]], held at the [[Washington Hilton]], where he performed \"[[Ombra mai fu]]\" and [[Franz Schubert]]'s \"[[Ave Maria (Schubert)|Ave Maria]]\" in the presence of President [[Barack Obama]], First Lady [[Michelle Obama]], Vice Present [[Joe Biden]], as well as other political leaders.<ref>[http://www.music-news.com/shownews.asp?H=Andrea-Bocelli-plays-for-Barak-Obama&nItemID=62744 Andrea Bocelli plays for Barack Obama]</ref><ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/obama-urges-humility-national-prayer-breakfast-article-1.1257904 President Obama speaks about faith and 'humility' at National Prayer Breakfast] [[New York Daily News]]</ref> On 20 February, he performed at the concert in Moscow [[Kremlin]] dedicated to 20th anniversary of [[Gazprom]].\n\nOn 1 June, Bocelli performed with [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]] at the [[Arena di Verona]], celebrating the 100th anniversary of the opera festival.<ref>[http://www.geticket.it/default/biglietteria/?id=9946 Arena Di Verona 2013 \u2013 1 Giugno] (Italian)</ref>\n\n===2015\u2013present: ''Cinema'', collaborations, and ''S\u00ec''===\n[[File:Bocelli & Son.jpg|thumb|left|Bocelli and his son Matteo performing in New York at the presentation of the album ''[[S\u00ec (Andrea Bocelli album)|S\u00ec]]'' in 2018.]]\nBocelli released his fifteenth [[studio album]] ''[[Cinema (Andrea Bocelli album)|Cinema]]'' on 23 October 2015. It contains renditions of classic [[film soundtrack]]s and [[Film score|scores]], featuring duets with [[Ariana Grande]], [[Nicole Scherzinger]] and his wife Veronica Berti. The album received a nomination for [[Best Traditional Pop Vocal Album]] at the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards]]; the Spanish-language version was nominated for [[Latin Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] at the [[17th Annual Latin Grammy Awards]].\n\nOn 15 December 2017, [[Ed Sheeran]] released a collaboration with Bocelli titled \"[[Perfect Symphony]]\". The song is a duet version of Sheeran's song \"[[Perfect (Ed Sheeran song)|Perfect]]\", with many of the original English lyrics sung in Italian.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ed Sheeran and Andrea Bocelli collaborate on new Perfect remix |url=http://www.music-news.com/news/UK/109833/Ed-Sheeran-reveals-Andrea-Bocelli-as-surprise-collaborator-on-new-Perfect-remix |website=Music-News.com |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Bocelli released the single \"If Only\", his first after fourteen years.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mauro |first1=J-P |title=Andrea Bocelli's first original single in 14 years: \"If Only\" |url=https://aleteia.org/2018/06/18/andrea-bocellis-first-original-single-in-14-years-if-only/ |website=Aleteia \u2014 Catholic Spirituality, Lifestyle, World News, and Culture |accessdate=21 September 2018 |date=18 June 2018}}</ref>\nOn 20 September 2018, Bocelli released the single \"Fall On Me\" which features vocals from his son Matteo. The two performed the song on the 22 October episode of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing With the Stars]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boedeker |first1=Hal |title='Dancing With the Stars': Disney Night enlists Andrea Bocelli |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/tv/tv-guy/os-et-s2-dancing-with-the-stars-two-disney-nights-20181018-story.html |website=OrlandoSentinel.com |accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref> An English version of the song was released in October and was featured in the [[Walt Disney Pictures]] film ''[[The Nutcracker and the Four Realms]]'' as the end credit song. Both songs appear on Bocelli's album ''[[S\u00ec (Andrea Bocelli album)|S\u00ec]]'', released on 26 October 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaufman |first1=Gil |title=Andrea Bocelli 'Si' Album to Feature Duets With Dua Lipa, Ed Sheeran & More |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8476077/andrea-bocelli-si-album-duets-dua-lipa-ed-sheeran-josh-groban |website=Billboard |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Concierto Andrea Bocelli (48720880436).jpg|thumb|Andrea Bocelli concert in Gibraltar, September 2019.]]\n\nOn 12 October 2018, at the request of his close friend [[Sarah, Duchess of York]], Bocelli performed two songs at the [[wedding of Princess Eugenie and Jack Brooksbank|royal wedding]] of her daughter [[Princess Eugenie]], the [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]]/[[Charles Gounod|Gounod]] ''[[Hail Mary|Ave Maria]]'', and ''[[Panis angelicus]]'' by [[C\u00e9sar Franck]].<ref name=\"CNN-music\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/06/uk/uk-princess-eugenie-wedding-details/index.html|title=Opera, trumpets and red velvet cake for royal wedding of Britain's Princess Eugenie|publisher=CNN|first=Melissa|last=Gray|date=7 October 2018|accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Order-Service\">{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/sites/default/files/media/order_of_service_0.pdf|title=The Marriage of Her Royal Highness Princess Eugenie of York with Mr. Jack Brooksbank|publisher=The Royal Family|accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 2019, Bocelli performed a sold-out concert in [[Winter at Tantora Festival|'Winter at Tantora' festival]] running at [[Al-`Ula|Al-Ula]] for the first time in [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1445566/saudi-arabia|title=Opera star Andrea Bocelli regales music lovers at Saudi Arabia's Tantora Winter Festival|date=2019-02-01|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 July 2019 Bocelli performed at the opening ceremony of the [[2019 Summer Universiade]] in [[Naples]] with three songs includes \"Fall On Me\" with his son Matteo.\n\nOn 12 April 2020, Easter Sunday, Bocelli performed \"Music For Hope - Live From Duomo di Milano\" from an empty [[Milan Cathedral]], accompanied by cathedral organist Emanuele Vianelli.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/news/andrea-bocelli-sings-from-empty-duomo-cathedral-in-italy-for-special-live-easter-concert/ar-BB12wAln|title=Andrea Bocelli Sings From Empty Duomo Cathedral in Italy for Special Live Easter Concert|date=2020-04-12|website=MSN|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> The performance was streamed live over YouTube, where it continues to be available for replay.<ref>{{cite web |title=Andrea Bocelli: Music For Hope - Live From Duomo di Milano |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=huTUOek4LgU |website=YouTube |publisher=Andrea Bocelli |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>  About 5 million people tuned in for the livestream performance and, by April 13, 2020, over 32 million views were logged on the archived video. <ref>{{cite news |last1=Willman |first1=Chris |title=How Andrea Bocelli\u2019s Easter Live-Stream Became an Unexpected Global Blockbuster |url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/andrea-bocelli-easter-live-stream-global-phenomenon-1234579205/ |work=Variety |date=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Voice==\nItalian [[spinto]] tenor [[Franco Corelli]] praised Bocelli's voice after hearing it for the first time during a [[master class]] in 1986, in [[Turin]], and he later gave Bocelli private lessons.<ref name=\"Bocelli fans\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/classicalmusic/3668298/Andrea-Bocelli-Some-voices-have-tears-inside.html Andrea Bocelli: 'Some voices have tears inside'], [[The Daily Telegraph]], 4 October 2007 article.</ref><ref name=\"Bocelli Cieli di Toscana\"/><ref name=\"2009 Bocelli Interview\">[http://living.scotsman.com/features/Interview-Andrea-Bocelli-opera-singer.5762157.jp Interview: Andrea Bocelli, opera singer], [[The Scotsman]], 27 October 2009 article.</ref>\n\n[[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] soprano [[Ana Mar\u00eda Mart\u00ednez]], who regularly performs with Bocelli, said, \"More than anything, Andrea has something that is unique in that he brings this light that is always around him. And this purity of heart and beauty of sound just touches the listener. It can't be described.\"<ref name=\"Bocelli Cieli di Toscana\">[http://www.bluecoupe.com/classical/andreatoscana.html Andrea Bocelli's ''Cieli di Toscana'' review] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106142546/http://www.bluecoupe.com/classical/andreatoscana.html |date=6 January 2016 }}, ''bluecoupe.com'', 2001 article.</ref>\n\n[[Celine Dion]] said while introducing him during her Christmas Special for ''[[These Are Special Times]]'', in 1998, that \"if God would have a singing voice, he must sound a lot like Andrea Bocelli,\"<ref name=\"Decca\"/><ref name=\"2009 Bocelli Interview\"/> and [[David Foster]], a producer of the album, often describes Bocelli's voice as the most beautiful in the world. Similarly, [[jazz]] singer [[Al Jarreau]], who performed with Bocelli on the \"[[Night of the Proms]]\" tour in Europe in 1995, described him as \"the most beautiful voice in the world,\"<ref name=\"Bocelli - People 1997 \">[http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20123691,00.html Blind Ambition] [[People (magazine)|People Magazine]] 10 November 1997 issue.</ref> and American talk show host [[Oprah Winfrey]] commented on [[The Oprah Winfrey Show|her talk show]] that, \"when I hear Andrea sing, I burst into tears.\"<ref name=\"Bocelli fans\"/><ref name=\"Bocelli Cieli di Toscana\"/> After attending Bocelli's concert at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] in 2009, British-American actress [[Elizabeth Taylor]] said, \"My mind, my soul were transported by his beauty, his voice, his inner being. God has kissed this man and I thank God for it.\"<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/Movies/06/09/liz.taylor.outing/index.html Elizabeth Taylor makes first outing 'in months], [[CNN]], 9 June 2009 article.</ref> Taylor had been a passionate fan of Bocelli's since the beginning of his music career in the mid-1990s.<ref>[http://articles.sfgate.com/1999-01-13/entertainment/17677176_1_sling-blade-elizabeth-taylor-roddy-mcdowall Taylor Among Bocelli's Fans / Actress pushing 'The Prayer' for Oscar], [[San Francisco Chronicle|SFGate.com]], 23 January 1999 article.</ref> Other fans include [[Albert II, Prince of Monaco]], who invited the tenor to sing at [[Wedding of Albert II, Prince of Monaco, and Charlene Wittstock|his wedding]], as well as [[Sarah, Duchess of York]], and actress [[Isabella Rossellini]].<ref name=\"Bocelli - People 1997 \"/>\n\n==Recognition==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Andrea Bocelli}}\n\n===Honors===\n* Grand Officer of the [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] (''Grande Ufficiale Ordine al Merito della Repubblica Italiana'') awarded in Rome, on 4 March 2006.<ref name=\"BOC2006\"/><ref name=\"radioitalia1169\"/>\n* Grand Officer of the [[Order of Merit of Duarte, Sanchez and Mella]] by the President of the [[Dominican Republic]], [[Leonel Fern\u00e1ndez]] in 2009, for his contributions to International art and culture.<ref>[http://dominicanosHOY.com/articulos/articulo/gobierno-condecora-a-andrea-bocelli Bocelli honored by the Dominican government]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016023643/http://dominicanoshoy.com/articulos/articulo/gobierno-condecora-a-andrea-bocelli |date=16 October 2014 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/594822.html Andrea Bocelli, decorated in Dominican], [[El Universal (Mexico City)]] 2009 article</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Global Foundation for Democracy and Development \u2013 Dominican Republic|url=http://www.dominicanaonline.org/portal/espanol/cpo_noti1587.asp|title=Decoration of Italian artist Andrea Bocelli|publisher=Dominicanaonline.org|accessdate=6 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730131106/http://www.dominicanaonline.org/portal/espanol/cpo_noti1587.asp|archive-date=30 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], for his contribution to [[Theatre|live theater]], at 7000 [[Hollywood Boulevard]], in 2010.<ref name=\"Bocelli gets Star (1)\"/>\n\n===Selected awards===\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Andrea Bocelli}}\n* Winner of the 1994 Newcomers section of the [[Sanremo Music Festival]].<ref name=\"BOC1994\">{{cite web|title=Chronicle 1992\u20131994|publisher=bocelli.de|url=http://www.bocelli.de/en/chronicle1992.htm|accessdate=21 January 2008}}</ref>\n* [[ECHO (music award)|ECHO]] music award for \"[[ECHO (music award)#Single of the Year (National)|Best Single of the Year]]\" for \"[[Con te partir\u00f2|Time to Say Goodbye]]\", in 1997.<ref name=\"BOC1995\"/>\n* [[ECHO (music award)|ECHO Klassik]] \"Best seller of the year\" award for his album, ''[[Viaggio Italiano]]'' in 1997.<ref name=\"BOC1995\"/><ref name=\"echo1997\"/>\n* [[Bambi Award]] in 1997.<ref name=\"BOC1995\"/>\n* Two [[World Music Awards]], one in the category \"Best Italian Singer\", and one for \"Best Classical Interpretation\" in 1998.<ref name=\"BOC1998\"/><ref name=\"IHT6768960\"/>\n* [[ECHO (music award)|ECHO Klassik]], for \"Best selling classical album\" with ''[[Aria: The Opera Album]]'' in 1998.<ref name=\"BOC1998\" />\n* [[ECHO (music award)|ECHO Klassik]] for \"Bestseller of the year\" for ''[[Sacred Arias (Andrea Bocelli album)|Sacred Arias]]'' in 2000.<ref name=\"BOC2000\"/>\n* Two [[Classical BRIT Awards#2000|2000 Classical BRIT Awards]] for \"Best selling classical album\" and \"Album of the year\" for ''[[Sacred Arias (Andrea Bocelli album)|Sacred Arias]]'' in 2000.<ref name=\"BOC2000\"/>\n* [[Goldene Europa]] for classical music in 2000.<ref name=\"BOC2000\"/>\n* [[Goldene Kamera]] award in the \"Music & Entertainment\" category 2002.<ref name=\"BOC2002\"/>\n* Two [[World Music Awards]], for \"World best selling classical artist\" and for \"Best selling Italian artist\" in 2002.<ref name=\"BOC2002\"/>\n* [[Telegatto| Telegatto award]] for the soundtrack of the series ''[[Heart (novel)|Cuore]]'' in 2002.<ref name=\"BOC2002\"/>\n* [[Classical BRIT Awards#2002|2002 Classical BRIT Award]] for \"[[Brit Award for Outstanding Contribution to Music|Outstanding Contribution to Music]]\" in 2002.<ref name=\"BOC2002\"/>\n* Two [[Classical BRIT Awards#2003|2003 Classical BRIT Awards]] for \"Best selling classical album\" and \"Album of the year\" for ''[[Sentimento]]'' in 2003.<ref name=\"BBC2931456\"/>\n* Two [[2006 World Music Awards|World Music Awards]] for \"Best Italian Artist\" and \"World's Best-selling Classical Artist\" in 2006.<ref name=\"BOC2006\"/>\n* [[Telegatto| Telegatto award]] in platinum for ''Italian music in the world'' in 2008.<ref name=\"BOC2008\" />\n* [[2010 World Music Awards|World Music Awards]] for \"World's Best-selling Classical Artist\" in 2010.\n* \"America Award\" of the [[Italy\u2013USA Foundation]] in 2012.\n* \"International Artist of the Year in association with Raymond Weil\" of the [[Classic Brit Awards]] 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicbrits.co.uk/winners/|title=The Classic BRIT Awards 2012 with MasterCard \u2013 Winners|publisher=classicbrits.co.uk|date=2 October 2012|accessdate=3 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005054520/http://www.classicbrits.co.uk/winners/|archive-date=5 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* The [[Billboard Latin Music Lifetime Achievement Award]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cobo|first1=Leila|last2=Cantor-Navas|first2=Judy|title=Marc Anthony's Salsa Revival Sweeps Billboard Latin Music Awards|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/record-labels/6069821/marc-anthonys-salsa-revival-sweeps-billboard-latin-music|website=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=7 December 2017|date=24 April 2014}}</ref>\n* \"[[Art, Science and Peace Prize]]\" 2015 from PIER FRANCO MARCENARO founder of \"Man Center\" and \"School of Spirituality\" for Andrea Bocelli art which elevates the spirit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.schoolofspirituality.org/Award_2015_ENG.html|title=PIER FRANCO MARCENARO Awards 2015|date=5 December 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106142546/http://www.schoolofspirituality.org/Award_2015_ENG.html|archivedate=6 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:AndreaBocelliVeronicaBertiMar10.jpg|thumb|right|Bocelli with his wife Veronica Berti in March 2010.]]\n\nBocelli met his first wife, Enrica Cenzatti,<ref>[http://www.fanpix.net/picture-gallery/enrica-bocelli-picture-10544745.htm Wedding photo of Enrica Cenzatti and Andrea Bocelli]</ref> while singing at piano bars early in his career.<ref name=\"chronicle\"/> They were married on 27 June 1992, and had two children.<ref name=\"BOC1992\"/> Their first child, Amos, was born in February 1995. Their second son, Matteo, was born in October 1997.<ref name=\"BOC1995\"/> The couple separated in 2002.<ref name=\"BOC2002\"/> Bocelli lives with his second wife and manager, Veronica Berti. They met in 2002. In September 2011, the couple announced that Berti was expecting her first and Bocelli's third child, a daughter,<ref>{{cite news|title=Bocelli's fiancee expecting his first daughter|url=http://uk.omg.yahoo.com/news/bocellis-fiancee-expecting-first-daughter-220000639.html|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=Yahoo omg! UK|date=14 November 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203145944/http://uk.omg.yahoo.com/news/bocellis-fiancee-expecting-first-daughter-220000639.html|archivedate=3 December 2013}}</ref> in the spring.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bright|first=Spencer|title=Andrea Bocelli joins stars in celebrating 50th anniversary of Songs of Praise|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2040696/Andrea-Bocelli-joins-stars-celebrating-50th-anniversary-Songs-Of-Praise.html|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=Mail Online|date=23 September 2011}}</ref> His daughter Virginia was born 21 March 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Virginia arriva con la primavera Fiocco rosa in casa Bocelli|url=http://www.lanazione.it/massa_carrara/cronaca/2012/03/21/684764-bocelli-virginia-parto.shtml|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=[[La Nazione]]|language=Italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Magrath|first=Andrea|title=Andrea Bocelli and fianc\u00e9e Veronica welcome a baby girl named Virginia|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2121063/Andrea-Bocelli-fianc-e-Veronica-welcome-baby-girl-named-Virginia.html|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=Mail Online|date=27 March 2012}}</ref> The couple live in a spacious [[villa]] in [[Forte dei Marmi]] on the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]. Bocelli's first wife and two sons live in the couple's previous residence in the same [[comune]], in [[Versilia]].<ref name=\"Bocelli fans\"/> Bocelli married Veronica Berti on 21 March 2014 at the Sanctuary of Montenero in the coastal town of Livorno, Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/andrea-bocelli-marries-veronica-berti/|title=Andrea Bocelli Marries Veronica Berti|website=PEOPLE.com|language=EN|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April 2000, Bocelli's father, Alessandro Bocelli, died. His mother encouraged him to honor his commitments, and so he sang for [[Pope John Paul II]], in Rome, on 1 May, and immediately returned home for the funeral. At his 5 July performance, filmed for PBS as ''American Dream\u2014Andrea Bocelli's [[Statue of Liberty]] Concert'', Bocelli dedicated the encore ''Sogno'' (Dream), from his 1999 album ''[[Sogno]]'', to the memory of his father.<ref name=\"BOC2000\"/>\n\nAlthough he is blind, Bocelli has enjoyed [[horseback riding]] for much of his life.<ref>Interview segment with [[Gayle King]] for ''[[CBS This Morning]]'' (broadcast several times during 2018).</ref>\n\nA section of the beach in [[Jesolo]], on the Italian [[Adriatic coast]], was named after Bocelli on 11 August 2003.<ref name=\"BOC2003\"/>\n\nIn October 2013 Bocelli bought a second home in [[North Miami Beach]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://miami.cbslocal.com/2013/10/21/one-on-one-with-andrea-bocelli/|title=One-On-One With Andrea Bocelli|publisher=CBS News|date=21 October 2013|accessdate=23 January 2014|author=Petrillo, Lisa}}</ref>\n\nBocelli is a self-declared passionate fan of Italian football club [[Inter Milan]]. In an interview in Pisa, he claimed to a group of Inter fans that \"My passion for Inter started during my college years, when Inter was winning everything in Italy and the world. When Inter won the Champions League in 2010, I was with my friends and I was listening to the game on the radio, and everything was a little bit in advance so I was celebrating before them. That night I was also brought to tears of joy. The treble is a feeling no one in Italy will be able to equal\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrea Bocelli is a fan of Inter|url=http://www.fcinternews.it/news/bocelli-interista-dagli-anni-del-collegio-il-triplete-gioia-ineguagliabile-la-sera-di-madrid-esultai-prima-perche-266762|website=fcinternews.it}}</ref>\n\n===Teatro del Silenzio===\n{{Main|Teatro del Silenzio}}\nIn 2006, Bocelli convinced the municipality of his hometown [[Lajatico]] to build an outdoor theatre, the \"[[Teatro del Silenzio]]\".<ref name=\"BBCdoc\">{{cite video|title=Andrea Bocelli: The Story Behind the Voice|medium=television documentary|publisher=BBC|date=25 December 2007}}</ref> He serves as its honorary president and performs for one night only, every July; the rest of the year, the theatre remains silent.\n\nSince its opening in 2006, Bocelli has held 12 concerts, every July, with guests including [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[Jos\u00e9 Carreras]], [[Sarah Brightman]], [[Katherine Jenkins]], [[Zucchero]], [[Laura Pausini]], and [[Elisa (Italian singer)|Elisa]]. Bocelli's guests have also included instrumentalists [[Lang Lang]], [[Chris Botti]], and [[Kenny G]]. The 2007 concert was [[Vivere Live in Tuscany|released on CD and DVD]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vivere: Andrea Bocelli Live in Tuscany|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/gperf/episodes/vivere-andrea-bocelli-live-in-tuscany/introduction/128/|work=[[PBS]]|publisher=Educational Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Andrea Bocelli discography}}\n<!-- Do not add any album chart positions or sales records here, keep this list as short as possible. -->\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* 1994: ''[[Il Mare Calmo della Sera]]''\n* 1995: ''[[Bocelli (album)|Bocelli]]''\n* 1996\u201397: ''[[Viaggio Italiano]]''\n* 1998: ''[[Aria: The Opera Album]]''\n* 1999: ''[[Sogno]]''\n* 1999: ''[[Sacred Arias (Andrea Bocelli album)|Sacred Arias]]''\n* 2000: ''[[Verdi (album)|Verdi]]''\n* 2001: ''[[Cieli di Toscana]]''\n* 2002: ''[[Sentimento]]''\n* 2004: ''[[Andrea (Andrea Bocelli album)|Andrea]]''\n* 2006: ''[[Amore (Andrea Bocelli album)|Amore]]''\n* 2008: ''[[Incanto]]''\n* 2009: ''[[My Christmas]]''\n* 2013: ''[[Passione (Andrea Bocelli album)|Passione]]''\n* 2015: ''[[Cinema (Andrea Bocelli album)|Cinema]]''\n* 2018: ''[[S\u00ec (Andrea Bocelli album)|S\u00ec]]''\n\n===Compilation albums===\n* 1997: ''[[Romanza]]''\n* 2007: ''[[The Best of Andrea Bocelli: Vivere]]''\n* 2012: ''[[Opera (Andrea Bocelli album)|Opera]]''\n* 2016: ''[[Romanza|Romanza (20th Anniversary Edition)]]''\n\n===Live albums===\n* 2006: ''[[Under the Desert Sky]]''\n* 2008: ''[[Vivere Live in Tuscany]]''\n* 2011: ''[[Concerto, One Night in Central Park]]''\n* 2013: ''Love in Portofino''\n\n===Extended plays===\n* 2012: ''iTunes Festival: London 2012''\n\n===Digital albums===\n* 2011: ''[[Notte Illuminata]]''\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Collaborative albums===\n* 1997: ''A Hymn for the World''\n* 1998: ''A Hymn for the World 2'' (''Voices From Heaven'')\n* 2000: ''[[Requiem (Verdi)|Verdi's Requiem]]''\n* 2010: ''[[Carmen: Duets & Arias]]''\n\n===Complete opera recordings===\n* 2000: ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]''\n* 2001: ''[[Requiem (Verdi)|Requiem]]''\n* 2002: ''[[Madama Butterfly]]''\n* 2003: ''[[Tosca]]''\n* 2004: ''[[Il trovatore]]''\n* 2005: ''[[Werther]]''\n* 2006: ''[[Pagliacci]]''\n* 2007: ''[[Cavalleria rusticana]]''\n* 2008/2010: ''[[Carmen]]''\n* 2010: ''[[Andrea Ch\u00e9nier]]''\n* 2012: ''[[Rom\u00e9o et Juliette]]''\n* 2014: ''[[Manon Lescaut]]''\n* 2015: ''[[Turandot]]''\n* 2016: ''[[Aida]]''\n\n===Video albums===\n* 1998: ''[[A Night in Tuscany]]''\n* 2000: ''[[Sacred Arias: The Home Video]]''\n* 2002: ''[[Tuscan Skies (film)|Tuscan Skies]]''\n* 2006: ''[[Credo: John Paul II]]''\n* 2006: ''[[Under the Desert Sky]]''\n* 2008: ''[[Vivere Live in Tuscany]]''\n* 2008: ''[[Incanto| Incanto The Documentary]]''\n* 2009: ''[[My Christmas Special]]''\n* 2011: ''[[Concerto: One Night in Central Park]]''\n* 2013: ''Love in Portofino''<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrea Bocelli Love In Portofino|url=https://bia4music.ir/%d8%af%d8%a7%d9%86%d9%84%d9%88%d8%af-%d8%a2%d9%87%d9%86%da%af-love-in-portofino/|publisher=bia4music|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n* 2016: ''Cinema''\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Bibliography==\nBocelli is the author, and co-author, of numerous works available in Italian, English, and other languages.  Some books are available in Braille and others in large print.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=au%3Aandrea+bocelli&qt=advanced&dblist=638|title=Search results for 'au:andrea bocelli'|author=WorldCat|accessdate=11 October 2012}}</ref> The list below is limited to his English language books which are widely available.\n\n* {{cite book|title=The music of silence: a memoir by Andrea Bocelli|last=Bocelli|first=A.|origyear=1999|year=2002|publisher=HarperCollins|location=New York|oclc=54699002}} Braille edition, ISBN not available.\n* {{cite book|title=The music of silence: a memoir|last=Bocelli|first=A.|year=2002|publisher=Thorndike Press|location=Waterville, ME|isbn=9780786239009|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780786239009}} Large print edition.\n* {{cite book|title=Andrea Bocelli \u2013 Amore.|last=Bocelli|first=A.|year=2007|publisher=Hal Leonard Corp|location=Milwaukee, WI|isbn=9788850709922}}\n* {{cite book|title=The music of silence: a memoir|last=Bocelli|first=A.|year=2001|publisher=HarperEntertainment|location=New York|isbn=9780066212869|url=https://archive.org/details/musicofsilence00andr}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Music of Silence; New Edition.|last=Bocelli|first=A.|year=2011|publisher=Hal Leonard Corp|location=Milwaukee, WI|isbn=9781574671971}}\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of best-selling music artists#50 million to 74 million records|List of best-selling music artists]]\n* [[Italian estimated best-selling music artists]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{commons category|Andrea Bocelli}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.andreabocelli.com/}}\n* {{Discogs artist}}\n* {{IMDb person}}\n* {{AllMovie person}}\n\n{{Andrea Bocelli}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bocelli, Andrea}}\n[[Category:Andrea Bocelli| ]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Blind musicians]]\n[[Category:Blind classical musicians]]\n[[Category:Blind people from Italy]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism from atheism or agnosticism]]\n[[Category:Crooners]]\n[[Category:Decca Records artists]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from Italy]]\n[[Category:French-language singers of Italy]]\n[[Category:German-language singers]]\n[[Category:Italian drummers]]\n[[Category:Male drummers]]\n[[Category:Italian flautists]]\n[[Category:Italian guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Italian keyboardists]]\n[[Category:Italian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Italian male singers]]\n[[Category:Italian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Italian pianists]]\n[[Category:Italian pop singers]]\n[[Category:Italian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Italian saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Italian singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Italian operatic tenors]]\n[[Category:Italian trombonists]]\n[[Category:Italian trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Male trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Italian-language singers]]\n[[Category:Latin-language singers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Multi-instrumentalists]]\n[[Category:Opera crossover singers]]\n[[Category:Order of Merit of Duarte, S\u00e1nchez and Mella]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Pisa]]\n[[Category:Portuguese-language singers]]\n[[Category:Sanremo Music Festival winners of the newcomers section]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language singers of Italy]]\n[[Category:Torch singers]]\n[[Category:Traditional pop music singers]]\n[[Category:Universal Music Group artists]]\n[[Category:University of Pisa alumni]]\n[[Category:World Music Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Italian male pianists]]\n", "name_user": "41.246.28.140", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrea_Bocelli"}
