{"title_page": "Maurice Renard", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2019}}\n{{cleanup rewrite|date=February 2019}}\n}}\n[[File:Maurice Renard (1875-1939).jpg|thumb|Maurice Renard]]\n'''Maurice Renard''' (28 February 1875, [[Ch\u00e2lons-en-Champagne]] \u2013 18 November 1939, [[Rochefort, Charente-Maritime|Rochefort-Sur-Mer]]) was a French writer.\n\n== Career ==\nRenard authored the archetypal [[mad scientist]] novel  ''Le Docteur Lerne - Sous-Dieu''  [Dr. Lerne - Undergod] (1908), which he dedicated to [[H. G. Wells]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Altariac|first1=Joseph|translator-last=Ghiringhelli|translator-first=Barbara| chapter=H.G. Wells' critical reception in France|title=The Reception of H.G. Wells in Europe|editor1-last=Parrinder|editor1-first=Patrick|editorlink=Patrick Parrinder|editor2-last=Partington|editor2-first=John S.|publisher= Continuum|date= 2005|isbn= 0826462537 |page= 22}}</ref> In it, a Doctor Moreau-like mad scientist performs [[organ transplants]] not only between men and animals, but also between plants and even machines.\n\nRenard's novel, ''[[The Blue Peril]]'' (''Le P\u00e9ril Bleu'', 1910) postulates the existence of unimaginable, invisible creatures who lived in the upper strata of the atmosphere and fish for men the way men captured fish.  These aliens, dubbed \"Sarvants\" by the human scientists who discover them, feel threatened by our incursions into space the way men would be threatened by an invasion of crabs, and retaliate by capturing men, keeping them in a space zoo and studying them.  Eventually, when the Sarvants come to the realization that men are intelligent, they release their captives.  ''Le P\u00e9ril Bleu'' predates [[Charles Fort]]'s ''[[Book of the Damned]]'' (1919) and retains a humanistic and tolerant rather than fearful and xenophobic philosophy.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nRenard wrote the novel ''[[Les Mains d'Orlac]]'' (\"The Hands of Orlac\", 1920), in which a virtuoso pianist receives the transplanted hands of a murderer and turns into a killer himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/554250/The-Hands-of-Orlac/articles.html|title=The Hands of Orlac (1925) - Articles - TCM.com|website=Turner Classic Movies}}</ref> The book was has led to four film versions as ''[[The Hands of Orlac (1924 film)|The Hands of Orlac]]'' (''Orlacs H\u00e4nde'', 1924) with [[Conrad Veidt]], ''[[Mad Love (1935 film)|Mad Love]]'' (1935) with [[Colin Clive]] and [[Peter Lorre]], ''[[The Hands of Orlac (1960 film)|The Hands of Orlac]]'' (1960) with [[Mel Ferrer]] and [[Christopher Lee]], and ''[[Hands of a Stranger]]'' (1962)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6EgPDierNGUC&pg=PA573#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Leonard Maltin's 2009 Movie Guide|first1=Leonard|last1=Maltin|first2=Luke|last2=Sader|first3=Mike|last3=Clark|date=9 December 2008|publisher=Penguin|via=Google Books}}</ref> directed by Newt Arnold.\n\n''L'Homme Truqu\u00e9'' (\"The Phony Man\", 1923) features the graft of \"electroscopic\" eyes onto a man blinded during [[World War I]].  The result is the strange description of a world perceived through artificial senses.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n''L'Homme Qui Voulait \u00catre Invisible'' (\"The Man Who Wanted To Be Invisible\", 1923) deals with the issue of invisibility; in it, Renard exposes the scientific fallacy inherent in Wells' famous novel. Since, in order to function, the human eye must perform as an opaque dark room, any truly invisible man would also be blind!{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nIn ''Le Singe'' (\"The Monkey\", 1925), written with [[Albert-Jean]], Renard imagined the creation of artificial lifeforms through the process of \"radiogenesis\", a sort of human electrocopying or [[cloning]] process. The [[Roman Catholic]] press ferociously attacked the novel,perceiving it as sacrilegious, and blacklisted by public libraries.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n''Un Homme chez les Microbes: Scherzo'' (\"A Man Amongst The Microbes: Scherzo\", 1928) was one of the first scientific novels on the theme of [[Resizing (fiction)|miniaturization]], and one of the earliest to introduce the concept of a micro-world where atoms were microscopic solar systems with planets. Renard's hero submits himself willingly to a shrinking process that eventually ran out of control. As in [[Richard Matheson]]'s  screenplay for ''[[The Incredible Shrinking Man]]'' (1957), the hero is then attacked by insects, before eventually arriving on an electron-size planet, where scientifically advanced people are able to reverse the process and send him home.\n\nFinally, ''Le Ma\u00eetre de la Lumi\u00e8re'' (The Light Master\", 1933) anticipated [[Bob Shaw]]'s \"[[slow glass]]\" by introducing the concept of a glass that condenses time.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n==Selected bibliography==\n* ''Fant\u00f4mes et Fant\u00f4ches'' [Ghosts And Puppets] (As Vincent Saint-Vincent) (1905)\n* ''Le Docteur Lerne, Sous-Dieu'' [''Doctor Lerne, Undergod''] (1908) translated by [[Brian Stableford]] as ''Doctor Lerne'', 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-935558-15-6}}  (previously translated in 1923 as ''New Bodies For Old'', published by The Macaulay Company in New York<ref>{{cite web|title=New Bodies for Old (worldcat)|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/new-bodies-for-old/oclc/963171|website=Worldcat}}</ref>)\n* ''Le Voyage Immobile'' [The Motionless Journey] (1909) transl. as ''The Flight of the Aerofix'' (1932); translated by Brian Stableford and included in ''A Man Among the Microbes'', 2010, q.v.\n* Le P\u00e9ril Bleu [The Blue Peril] (1912) translated by Brian Stableford as ''The Blue Peril'', 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-935558-17-0}}\n* M. D'Outremort [Mr. Beyonddeath] (1913) translated by Brian Stableford and included in ''The Doctored Man'', 2010, q.v.\n* ''Les Mains d'Orlac'' (1920; transl. as ''The Hands of Orlac'', 1929)\n* L'Homme Truqu\u00e9 [The Doctored Man] (1921) translated by Brian Stableford as ''The Doctored Man'', 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-935558-18-7}}\n* L'Homme Qui Voulait \u00catre Invisible [The Man Who Wanted To Be Invisible] (1923) translated by Brian Stableford and included in ''The Doctored Man'', 2010, q.v.\n* Le Singe [The Monkey] (With [[Albert-Jean]]) (1924; transl. as Blind Circle, 1928)\n* L'Invitation \u00e0 la Peur [The Invitation to Fear] (1926)\n* Lui? Histoire d'un Myst\u00e8re [Him? Tale of a Mystery] (1927)\n* Un Homme chez les Microbes: Scherzo [A Man Amongst The Microbes: Scherzo] (written 1908, pub. 1928) translated by Brian Stableford as ''A Man Among the Microbes'', 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-935558-16-3}}\n* Le Carnaval du Myst\u00e8re [The Merry-Go-Round of Mystery] (1929)\n* La Jeune Fille du Yacht [The Young Girl From The Yacht] (1930)\n* Celui Qui n'a pas Tu\u00e9 [He Who Did Not Kill] (1932)\n* Le Ma\u00eetre de la Lumi\u00e8re [The Light Master] (1933) translated by Brian Stableford as ''The Master of Light'', 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-935558-19-4}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==  External links ==\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=50553 |name=Maurice Renard}}\n* [http://data.bnf.fr/11921503/maurice_renard/ Maurice Renard] on [[data.bnf.fr]]\n* [http://www.depauw.edu/sfs/backissues/64/evans.htm - article by Arthur B. Evans, published in ''Science Fiction Studies'']\n* [http://www.depauw.edu/sfs/documents/renard.htm - Renard's 1909 essay \"On the Scientific-Marvelous Novel and its Influence on the Understanding of Progress\"]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Renard, Maurice}}\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ch\u00e2lons-en-Champagne]]\n[[Category:French science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:French fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:French crime fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French novelists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2019}}\n{{cleanup rewrite|date=February 2019}}\n[[File:Maurice Renard (1875-1939).jpg|thumb|Maurice Renard]]\n'''Maurice Renard''' (28 February 1875, [[Ch\u00e2lons-en-Champagne]] \u2013 18 November 1939, [[Rochefort, Charente-Maritime|Rochefort-Sur-Mer]]) was a French writer.\n\n== Career ==\nRenard authored the archetypal [[mad scientist]] novel  ''Le Docteur Lerne - Sous-Dieu''  [Dr. Lerne - Undergod] (1908), which he dedicated to [[H. G. Wells]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Altariac|first1=Joseph|translator-last=Ghiringhelli|translator-first=Barbara| chapter=H.G. Wells' critical reception in France|title=The Reception of H.G. Wells in Europe|editor1-last=Parrinder|editor1-first=Patrick|editorlink=Patrick Parrinder|editor2-last=Partington|editor2-first=John S.|publisher= Continuum|date= 2005|isbn= 0826462537 |page= 22}}</ref> In it, a Doctor Moreau-like mad scientist performs [[organ transplants]] not only between men and animals, but also between plants and even machines.\n\nRenard's novel, ''[[The Blue Peril]]'' (''Le P\u00e9ril Bleu'', 1910) postulates the existence of unimaginable, invisible creatures who lived in the upper strata of the atmosphere and fish for men the way men captured fish.  These aliens, dubbed \"Sarvants\" by the human scientists who discover them, feel threatened by our incursions into space the way men would be threatened by an invasion of crabs, and retaliate by capturing men, keeping them in a space zoo and studying them.  Eventually, when the Sarvants come to the realization that men are intelligent, they release their captives.  ''Le P\u00e9ril Bleu'' predates [[Charles Fort]]'s ''[[Book of the Damned]]'' (1919) and retains a humanistic and tolerant rather than fearful and xenophobic philosophy.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nRenard wrote the novel ''[[Les Mains d'Orlac]]'' (\"The Hands of Orlac\", 1920), in which a virtuoso pianist receives the transplanted hands of a murderer and turns into a killer himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/554250/The-Hands-of-Orlac/articles.html|title=The Hands of Orlac (1925) - Articles - TCM.com|website=Turner Classic Movies}}</ref> The book was has led to four film versions as ''[[The Hands of Orlac (1924 film)|The Hands of Orlac]]'' (''Orlacs H\u00e4nde'', 1924) with [[Conrad Veidt]], ''[[Mad Love (1935 film)|Mad Love]]'' (1935) with [[Colin Clive]] and [[Peter Lorre]], ''[[The Hands of Orlac (1960 film)|The Hands of Orlac]]'' (1960) with [[Mel Ferrer]] and [[Christopher Lee]], and ''[[Hands of a Stranger]]'' (1962)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6EgPDierNGUC&pg=PA573#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Leonard Maltin's 2009 Movie Guide|first1=Leonard|last1=Maltin|first2=Luke|last2=Sader|first3=Mike|last3=Clark|date=9 December 2008|publisher=Penguin|via=Google Books}}</ref> directed by Newt Arnold.\n\n''L'Homme Truqu\u00e9'' (\"The Phony Man\", 1923) features the graft of \"electroscopic\" eyes onto a man blinded during [[World War I]].  The result is the strange description of a world perceived through artificial senses.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n''L'Homme Qui Voulait \u00catre Invisible'' (\"The Man Who Wanted To Be Invisible\", 1923) deals with the issue of invisibility; in it, Renard exposes the scientific fallacy inherent in Wells' famous novel. Since, in order to function, the human eye must perform as an opaque dark room, any truly invisible man would also be blind!{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nIn ''Le Singe'' (\"The Monkey\", 1925), written with [[Albert-Jean]], Renard imagined the creation of artificial lifeforms through the process of \"radiogenesis\", a sort of human electrocopying or [[cloning]] process. The [[Roman Catholic]] press ferociously attacked the novel,perceiving it as sacrilegious, and blacklisted by public libraries.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n''Un Homme chez les Microbes: Scherzo'' (\"A Man Amongst The Microbes: Scherzo\", 1928) was one of the first scientific novels on the theme of [[Resizing (fiction)|miniaturization]], and one of the earliest to introduce the concept of a micro-world where atoms were microscopic solar systems with planets. Renard's hero submits himself willingly to a shrinking process that eventually ran out of control. As in [[Richard Matheson]]'s  screenplay for ''[[The Incredible Shrinking Man]]'' (1957), the hero is then attacked by insects, before eventually arriving on an electron-size planet, where scientifically advanced people are able to reverse the process and send him home.\n\nFinally, ''Le Ma\u00eetre de la Lumi\u00e8re'' (The Light Master\", 1933) anticipated [[Bob Shaw]]'s \"[[slow glass]]\" by introducing the concept of a glass that condenses time.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n==Selected bibliography==\n* ''Fant\u00f4mes et Fant\u00f4ches'' [Ghosts And Puppets] (As Vincent Saint-Vincent) (1905)\n* ''Le Docteur Lerne, Sous-Dieu'' [''Doctor Lerne, Undergod''] (1908) translated by [[Brian Stableford]] as ''Doctor Lerne'', 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-935558-15-6}}  (previously translated in 1923 as ''New Bodies For Old'', published by The Macaulay Company in New York<ref>{{cite web|title=New Bodies for Old (worldcat)|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/new-bodies-for-old/oclc/963171|website=Worldcat}}</ref>)\n* ''Le Voyage Immobile'' [The Motionless Journey] (1909) transl. as ''The Flight of the Aerofix'' (1932); translated by Brian Stableford and included in ''A Man Among the Microbes'', 2010, q.v.\n* Le P\u00e9ril Bleu [The Blue Peril] (1912) translated by Brian Stableford as ''The Blue Peril'', 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-935558-17-0}}\n* M. D'Outremort [Mr. Beyonddeath] (1913) translated by Brian Stableford and included in ''The Doctored Man'', 2010, q.v.\n* ''Les Mains d'Orlac'' (1920; transl. as ''The Hands of Orlac'', 1929)\n* L'Homme Truqu\u00e9 [The Doctored Man] (1921) translated by Brian Stableford as ''The Doctored Man'', 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-935558-18-7}}\n* L'Homme Qui Voulait \u00catre Invisible [The Man Who Wanted To Be Invisible] (1923) translated by Brian Stableford and included in ''The Doctored Man'', 2010, q.v.\n* Le Singe [The Monkey] (With [[Albert-Jean]]) (1924; transl. as Blind Circle, 1928)\n* L'Invitation \u00e0 la Peur [The Invitation to Fear] (1926)\n* Lui? Histoire d'un Myst\u00e8re [Him? Tale of a Mystery] (1927)\n* Un Homme chez les Microbes: Scherzo [A Man Amongst The Microbes: Scherzo] (written 1908, pub. 1928) translated by Brian Stableford as ''A Man Among the Microbes'', 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-935558-16-3}}\n* Le Carnaval du Myst\u00e8re [The Merry-Go-Round of Mystery] (1929)\n* La Jeune Fille du Yacht [The Young Girl From The Yacht] (1930)\n* Celui Qui n'a pas Tu\u00e9 [He Who Did Not Kill] (1932)\n* Le Ma\u00eetre de la Lumi\u00e8re [The Light Master] (1933) translated by Brian Stableford as ''The Master of Light'', 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-935558-19-4}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==  External links ==\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=50553 |name=Maurice Renard}}\n* [http://data.bnf.fr/11921503/maurice_renard/ Maurice Renard] on [[data.bnf.fr]]\n* [http://www.depauw.edu/sfs/backissues/64/evans.htm - article by Arthur B. Evans, published in ''Science Fiction Studies'']\n* [http://www.depauw.edu/sfs/documents/renard.htm - Renard's 1909 essay \"On the Scientific-Marvelous Novel and its Influence on the Understanding of Progress\"]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Renard, Maurice}}\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ch\u00e2lons-en-Champagne]]\n[[Category:French science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:French fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:French crime fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French novelists]]\n", "name_user": "Call me when you get the chance", "label": "safe", "comment": "Article has multiple issues", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maurice_Renard"}
{"title_page": "Mrs. Serial Killer", "text_new": "{{short description|Upcoming 2020 Indisn crime thriller web film}}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name                = Mrs. Serial Killer\n| image                    = \n| caption                  = \n| director                 = [[Shirish Kunder]]\n| starring                 = {{plainlist|\n* [[Jacqueline Fernandez]]\n* [[Manoj Bajpayee]]\n* [[Mohit Raina]]\n}}\n| country                  = India\n| language                 = English\n| producer                 = Farah Khan\n| distributor              = [[Netflix]]\n| released                 = {{Film date|df=yes|2020|05|01}}\n| last_aired               = \n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = \n| production_website       = \n| screenplay               = \n}}\n\n'''''Mrs. Serial Killer''''', also spelt as '''''Mrs Serial Killer''''' is an upcoming 2020 Indian [[Hindi language|Hindi]]-language [[web film]], produced as an Original for [[Netflix]]. The film is written and directed by [[Shirish Kunder]] and produced by his wife Farah Khan. The film stars [[Jacqueline Fernandez]], [[Manoj Bajpayee]] and [[Mohit Raina]] in the main lead roles while [[Amir Khan (actor)|Amir Khan]]'s niece Zayn Marie makes her acting debut appearance in a film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/web-series/jacqueline-fernandez-and-manoj-bajpayees-netflix-film-mrs-serial-killer-to-premiere-on-may-1-video-6363450/|title=Jacqueline Fernandez and Manoj Bajpayee\u2019s Netflix film Mrs Serial Killer to premiere on May 1|date=2020-04-15|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> This web film also marks the digital debut appearance for Jacqueline Fernandez who also marks her first collaboration with Netflix.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/entertainment-news-jacqueline-fernandez-makes-digital-debut-in-mrs-serial-killer/